{"title_page": "Claudio Di Veroli", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian-Argentinian harpsichordist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      = Claudio Di Veroli\n| honorific_suffix          = \n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| image                     = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place               = Buenos Aires, Argentina\n| disappeared_date          = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place         = \n| disappeared_status        = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| body_discovered           = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = \n| other_names               = \n| ethnicity                 = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship               = \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = \n| years_active              = \n| employer                  = \n| organization              = \n| agent                     = \n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| net_worth                 = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height                    = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight                    = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| title                     = \n| term                      = \n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 = \n| party                     = \n| movement                  = \n| opponents                 = \n| boards                    = \n| religion                  = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination              = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| relatives                 = \n| callsign                  = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n'''Claudio Di Veroli''' (born 1946) is an Italian-Argentinian [[harpsichordist]] who has written several books and papers on baroque performance practice. Born in [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, he was raised in an Italian family  and attended Italian primary and secondary school. He studied privately in Buenos Aires under {{ill|Ernesto Epstein|de|vertical-align=sup}} (piano and interpretation), {{ill|Erwin Leuchter|de|vertical-align=sup}} (harmony) and [[Ljerko Spiller]] (chamber music), obtained a degree in Mathematics from the [[University of Buenos Aires]] and a PhD in Statistics from [[Imperial College]], London,<ref>{{cite news|title=J. Claudio Di Veroli|url=https://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=142140|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Mathematics Genealogy Project}}</ref> under the supervision of Prof. Sir [[David Cox (statistician)]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Optimal Continuous Policies for Repair and Replacement|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/324388029|accessdate=May 1, 2018|journal=Operational Research Quarterly |volume=25|issue=1|pages=89\u201397|date=March 1, 1974 |doi=10.2307/3007778|jstor=3007778|last1=Veroli|first1=J. C. Di}}</ref> Living in Europe in the early 70's he studied harpsichord with [[Colin Tilney]] in London and {{ill|Hubert B\u00e9dard|fr|vertical-align=sup}} in Paris.\n\nHe then returned to Buenos Aires, where he pioneered the performance of Baroque music based on ancient practices.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Juarez|first=Miguel|title=Instrumentos originales en la Argentina|journal=Clasica|date=January 1994|volume=3|issue=1|page=55|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina}}</ref> He was Professor of Harpsichord and examiner of the Organ course at the [[Conservatorio Nacional Superior de Musica (Argentina)|Conservatorio Nacional]] in Buenos Aires.  As a soloist he has performed extensively in concert halls, churches and television, both solo and with ensembles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=List of Public Performances|url=http://harps.braybaroque.ie/recitals.htm|website=Bray Baroque|location=Bray, Rep. Ireland|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> After a harpsichord recital a reviewer observed that he \"did not miss any detail in order to complete the historical legitimacy of his performance, and also produced a logical, live expressivness\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Camps|first=Pompeyo|title=Fascinante experiencia en el Museo Larreta|newspaper=Clar\u00edn|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|date=June 26, 1984}}</ref> After another concert the same reviewer noted his \"virtuosity in the formidable 'Cadenza' of the Fifth Brandenburg Concerto\", a performance  which was the world's first contemporary one with Baroque fingerings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Camps|first=Pompeyo|title= Los Solistas Bach tocaron su homenaje|newspaper=Clar\u00edn|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|date=March 27, 1985}}</ref> He has lived since 2001 in Ireland, where he has offered recitals and masterclasses on the interpretation of Baroque keyboard music.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harpsichord workshop treat for music lovers|url=http://www.braypeople.ie/news/harpsichord-workshop-treat-for-music-lovers-2810703.html|accessdate=June 17, 2012|newspaper=Bray People|location=Bray, Rep. Ireland|date=June 29, 2011}}</ref> He is also musically active in Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Claudio Di Veroli Plays Couperin in Lucca, Italy|url=http://www.luccamusica.it/events/event/claudio-di-veroli-plays-couperin-2/|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Lucca Musica|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Masterclass and Recital in Pescara, Italy|url=https://www.facebook.com/massimo.salcito/posts/1599596086745076|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Massimo Salcito Facebook page|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDi Veroli is the author of several books and papers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=Vallotti as the Ideal German Good Temperament|journal=Harpsichord & Fortepiano|date=Autumn 2010|volume=14|issue=2|pages=9\u201313|location=Worcestershire, UK|url=http://www.hfmagazine.info/uploads/CONTENTS-Vol-15-1-aut2010-mislabelled%20as%2014-2.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=In\u00e9galit\u00e9 and Rameau's Concerts: a case of 'Ille dixit'?|journal=Harpsichord & Fortepiano|date=Spring 2000|volume=8|issue=2|pages=28\u201334|location=Lincoln, UK}}</ref> Favourable reviews have appeared in Stimulus,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rasch|first=Rudolf A.|title=Owen Jorgensen: Tuning the historical temperaments by ear (1977) and Cl. Di Veroli: Unequal Temperaments and their role in the performance of early music (1978)|journal=Stimulus: The Ancient Music Journal of the University of Utrecht|year=1980|issue=1980|pages=32\u201337}}</ref> Early Music America<ref>{{cite journal|last=Persone|first=Pedro|title=Review of \"Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice\"|journal=Early Music America|date=March 2010|pages=2|url=http://www.earlymusic.org/publications/ema-magazine/vol-16-no-1-spring-2010|access-date=2014-07-06|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140709180709/http://www.earlymusic.org/publications/ema-magazine/vol-16-no-1-spring-2010|archive-date=2014-07-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the British Clavichord Society Newsletter.<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Delft|first=Menno|title=Review of \"Baroque Keyboard Fingering: A Method\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=June 2009|volume=44|pages=15\u201317|url=http://clavichord.org.uk/More/Newsletter/NLcontents.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hitchin|first=David|title=Review of \"Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=October 2009|volume=45|pages=18\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Cave|first=Penelope|title=Review of \"Playing the Baroque Harpsichord: essays on interpretation and performance, with relevant topics for the Clavichord and Organ\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=February 2011|volume=49|pages=18\u201322}}</ref>).\n\n==Major works==\n* ''Unequal Temperaments and their Role in the Performance of Early Music'' (1978).\n* ''Baroque Keyboard Fingering: a Method'' (2008, 2016).\n* ''Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice'' (2009, 2017).\n* ''Playing the Baroque Harpsichord: essays on the instrument, interpretation and performance, with relevant topics for the clavichord and organ'' (2010, 2018).\n* ''Baroque Keyboard Masterpieces Fingered with Baroque Technique'' (2011).\n* ''J.S. Bach's Six Keyboard Partitas with Baroque Fingerings and a Performance Guide'' (2015).\n\n==References==\n {{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://harps.braybaroque.ie/index.htm Claudio Di Veroli] - Personal website\n* Claudio Di Veroli [https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100013148084418] - Facebook page\n* Claudio Di Veroli [https://independent.academia.edu/ClaudioDiVeroli] - Academia.edu list of papers\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Veroli, Claudio}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baroque musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicologists]]\n[[Category:Italian harpsichordists]]\n[[Category:Italian performers of early music]]\n[[Category:Argentine performers of early music]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian-Argentinian harpsichordist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      = Claudio Di Veroli\n| honorific_suffix          = \n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| image                     = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place               = Buenos Aires, Argentina\n| disappeared_date          = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place         = \n| disappeared_status        = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| body_discovered           = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = \n| other_names               = \n| ethnicity                 = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship               = \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = \n| years_active              = \n| employer                  = \n| organization              = \n| agent                     = \n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| net_worth                 = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height                    = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight                    = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| title                     = \n| term                      = \n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 = \n| party                     = \n| movement                  = \n| opponents                 = \n| boards                    = \n| religion                  = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination              = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| relatives                 = \n| callsign                  = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n'''Claudio Di Veroli''' (born 1946) is an Italian-Argentinian [[harpsichordist]] who has written several books and papers on baroque performance practice. Born in [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, he was raised in an Italian family  and attended Italian primary and secondary school. He studied privately in Buenos Aires under {{ill|Ernesto Epstein|de|vertical-align=sup}} (piano and interpretation), {{ill|Erwin Leuchter|de|vertical-align=sup}} (harmony) and [[Ljerko Spiller]] (chamber music), obtained a degree in Mathematics from the [[University of Buenos Aires]] and a PhD in Statistics from [[Imperial College]], London,<ref>{{cite news|title=J. Claudio Di Veroli|url=https://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=142140|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Mathematics Genealogy Project}}</ref> under the supervision of Prof. Sir [[David Cox (statistician)]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Optimal Continuous Policies for Repair and Replacement|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/324388029|accessdate=May 1, 2018|journal=Operational Research Quarterly |volume=25|issue=1|pages=89\u201397|date=March 1, 1974 |doi=10.2307/3007778|jstor=3007778|last1=Veroli|first1=J. C. Di}}</ref> Living in Europe in the early 70's he studied harpsichord with [[Colin Tilney]] in London and {{ill|Hubert B\u00e9dard|fr|vertical-align=sup}} in Paris.\n\nHe then returned to Buenos Aires, where he pioneered the performance of Baroque music based on ancient practices.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Juarez|first=Miguel|title=Instrumentos originales en la Argentina|journal=Clasica|date=January 1994|volume=3|issue=1|page=55|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina}}</ref> He was Professor of Harpsichord and examiner of the Organ course at the [[Conservatorio Nacional Superior de Musica (Argentina)|Conservatorio Nacional]] in Buenos Aires.  As a soloist he has performed extensively in concert halls, churches and television, both solo and with ensembles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=List of Public Performances|url=http://harps.braybaroque.ie/recitals.htm|website=Bray Baroque|location=Bray, Rep. Ireland|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> After a harpsichord recital a reviewer observed that he \"did not miss any detail in order to complete the historical legitimacy of his performance, and also produced a logical, live expressivness\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Camps|first=Pompeyo|title=Fascinante experiencia en el Museo Larreta|newspaper=Clar\u00edn|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|date=June 26, 1984}}</ref> After another concert the same reviewer noted his \"virtuosity in the formidable 'Cadenza' of the Fifth Brandenburg Concerto\", a performance  which was the world's first contemporary one with Baroque fingerings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Camps|first=Pompeyo|title= Los Solistas Bach tocaron su homenaje|newspaper=Clar\u00edn|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|date=March 27, 1985}}</ref> He has lived since 2001 in Ireland, where he has offered recitals and masterclasses on the interpretation of Baroque keyboard music.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harpsichord workshop treat for music lovers|url=http://www.braypeople.ie/news/harpsichord-workshop-treat-for-music-lovers-2810703.html|accessdate=June 17, 2012|newspaper=Bray People|location=Bray, Rep. Ireland|date=June 29, 2011}}</ref> He is also musically active in Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Claudio Di Veroli Plays Couperin in Lucca, Italy|url=http://www.luccamusica.it/events/event/claudio-di-veroli-plays-couperin-2/|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Lucca Musica|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Masterclass and Recital in Pescara, Italy|url=https://www.facebook.com/massimo.salcito/posts/1599596086745076|accessdate=April 2, 2018|newspaper=Massimo Salcito Facebook page|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDi Veroli is the author of several books and papers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=Vallotti as the Ideal German Good Temperament|journal=Harpsichord & Fortepiano|date=Autumn 2010|volume=14|issue=2|pages=9\u201313|location=Worcestershire, UK|url=http://www.hfmagazine.info/uploads/CONTENTS-Vol-15-1-aut2010-mislabelled%20as%2014-2.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Di Veroli|first1=Claudio|title=In\u00e9galit\u00e9 and Rameau's Concerts: a case of 'Ille dixit'?|journal=Harpsichord & Fortepiano|date=Spring 2000|volume=8|issue=2|pages=28\u201334|location=Lincoln, UK}}</ref> Favourable reviews have appeared in Stimulus,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rasch|first=Rudolf A.|title=Owen Jorgensen: Tuning the historical temperaments by ear (1977) and Cl. Di Veroli: Unequal Temperaments and their role in the performance of early music (1978)|journal=Stimulus: The Ancient Music Journal of the University of Utrecht|year=1980|issue=1980|pages=32\u201337}}</ref> Early Music America<ref>{{cite journal|last=Persone|first=Pedro|title=Review of \"Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice\"|journal=Early Music America|date=March 2010|pages=2|url=http://www.earlymusic.org/publications/ema-magazine/vol-16-no-1-spring-2010|access-date=2014-07-06|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140709180709/http://www.earlymusic.org/publications/ema-magazine/vol-16-no-1-spring-2010|archive-date=2014-07-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the British Clavichord Society Newsletter.<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Delft|first=Menno|title=Review of \"Baroque Keyboard Fingering: A Method\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=June 2009|volume=44|pages=15\u201317|url=http://clavichord.org.uk/More/Newsletter/NLcontents.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hitchin|first=David|title=Review of \"Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=October 2009|volume=45|pages=18\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Cave|first=Penelope|title=Review of \"Playing the Baroque Harpsichord: essays on interpretation and performance, with relevant topics for the Clavichord and Organ\"|journal=The British Clavichord Society Newsletter|date=February 2011|volume=49|pages=18\u201322}}</ref>).\n\n==Major Works==\n* ''Unequal Temperaments and their Role in the Performance of Early Music'' (1978).\n* ''Baroque Keyboard Fingering: a Method'' (2008, 2016).\n* ''Unequal Temperaments: Theory, History and Practice'' (2009, 2017).\n* ''Playing the Baroque Harpsichord: essays on the instrument, interpretation and performance, with relevant topics for the clavichord and organ'' (2010, 2018).\n* ''Baroque Keyboard Masterpieces Fingered with Baroque Technique'' (2011).\n* ''J.S. Bach's Six Keyboard Partitas with Baroque Fingerings and a Performance Guide'' (2015).\n\n==References==\n {{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://harps.braybaroque.ie/index.htm Claudio Di Veroli] - Personal website\n* Claudio Di Veroli [https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100013148084418] - Facebook page\n* Claudio Di Veroli [https://independent.academia.edu/ClaudioDiVeroli] - Academia.edu list of papers\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Veroli, Claudio}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baroque musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicologists]]\n[[Category:Italian harpsichordists]]\n[[Category:Italian performers of early music]]\n[[Category:Argentine performers of early music]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMajor works:replaced: Works \u2192 works", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudio_Di_Veroli"}
{"title_page": "Ajoy Chakrabarty", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Pandit Ajoy Chakrabarty\n| image = Ajoy Chakrabarty - Kolkata 2015-12-4 2128.JPG\n| caption = Ajoy Chakrabarty at Kolkata\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Ajoy Chakrabarty\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1952|12|25}}\n| origin = [[Shyamnagar, West Bengal]], [[India]]\n| occupation = [[Vocalist]]\n| genre = [[Hindustani classical music]]\n| years_active = 1977\u2013present\n}}\n\nPandit '''Ajoy Chakrabarty''' (born 25 December 1952) is an Indian [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani classical]] [[Singing|vocalist]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Jyotirmaya |date=19 March 2005 |title=Ahoy Ajoy! |url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/03/19/stories/2005031901280300.htm |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=11 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050506120503/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/03/19/stories/2005031901280300.htm |archive-date=6 May 2005 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>He was given the [[Padma Bhushan]] Award, the third highest civilian award in India in 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/padma-honours-for-ajoy-chakraborty-manilal-nag/articleshow/73621920.cms | title=Padma honours for Ajoy Chakraborty, Manilal Nag  | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | date=26 January 2020 | accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/former-ministers-arun-jaitley-sushma-swaraj-and-george-fernandes-given-padma-vibhushan/articleshow/73617205.cms | title=Arun Jaitley, Sushma Swaraj, George Fernandes given Padma Vibhushan posthumously. Here's full list of Padma award recipients | publisher=[[The Economic Times]] | date=26 January 2020 | accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MINISTRY OF HOME AFFAIRS |url=https://padmaawards.gov.in/PDFS/2020AwardeesList.pdf |website=padmaawards.gov.in |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and Gurus==\nChakrabarty was born in Kolkata, [[West Bengal]]. His father moved to India from his homeland, [[Mymensingh]] of [[Bangladesh]] during the partition and raised two sons in [[Shyamnagar, West Bengal|Shyamnagar]]. His younger brother, Sanjay Chakraborty, is a lyricist and composer.\n\nHe graduated top of his class in music, both in B.A and M.A from the prestigious [[Rabindra Bharati University]] in Kolkata and joined the [[ITC Sangeet Research Academy]] in 1977.\n\nHis father was his first Guru. He then studied with Pannalal Samanta, Kanaidas Baigari and [[Jnan Prakash Ghosh]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Jyotirmaya |date=28 April 2006 |title=In honour of Bade Khansaheb |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/04/28/stories/2006042801520300.htm |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nBesides that, he had learnt from Latafat Hussain Khan, Nibruttibua Sarnaik, Hirabai Barodekar and in Carnatic styles from [[M. Balamuralikrishna]], that kept enriching his musical expression and repertoire{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Despite having such pure classical \"taleem\" in the [[Khyal]] genre, he also renders lighter forms such as [[Thumri]], [[Tappa]], [[Bhajan]], [[Kirtan]], [[Indian folk music|Folk]], Film/Non-Film and modern songs, in several different languages.\n\nHe has received several prestigious awards including the Padma Shri (2011), Sangeet Natak Akademi Award (Delhi, 1999\u20132000), Kumar Gandharva National Award  (1993) and the Best Male Playback Singer Award (Bengali Film \"Chhandaneer\" 1990) (\"For bringing the rare depth of emotion, adorned by his command on the classical idiom\") and [[Tansen Samaroh|National Tansen Samman]] 2015 - by the Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soulsteer.com/Gwalior/hindustani-classical-vocalist-pandit-ajoy-chakrabarty-awarded-201415-national-tansen-samman/|title=Hindustani classical vocalist Pandit Ajoy Chakrabarty|date=2015-12-25|publisher=SouLSteer|accessdate=2015-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225184432/http://soulsteer.com/Gwalior/hindustani-classical-vocalist-pandit-ajoy-chakrabarty-awarded-201415-national-tansen-samman/|archive-date=25 December 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has also received felicitations from both the former and present Chief Ministers of his own State, West Bengal. In 2012, Chief Minister of West Bengal, [[Mamata Banerjee]] conferred him the Maha Sangeet Samman and the [[Banga Bibhushan]], two of the State\u2019s highest awards. In 2015 he has received Guru Jnan Prakash Ghosh Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\nHe also was awarded honorary citizenship in New Orleans, after performing with jazz musicians at Preservation Hall, the birthplace of jazz music.\n\n==Singing career==\n\n\nHe is a recipient of the [[Padma Shri]] ([[List of Padma Shri award recipients (2010\u201319)|2011]]) and [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] (Delhi, 1999-2000) and the [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]] in 1989- in Bengali Film \"Chhandaneer\" 1989.<ref name=\"37thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/37nfa.pdf|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|title=37th National Film Awards |accessdate=29 January 2012|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Indian classical vocalist to be invited by [[Pakistan]] and [[China]] and by BBC for their Golden Jubilee Celebration of India\u2019s Independence.\n\nHe has performed in some of the most prestigious venues around the world such as [[Carnegie Hall]], [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|The Kennedy Center]], New Orleans Jazz Preservation Hall in the US, the [[Royal Albert Hall|Royal Albert hall]] and Queen Elizabeth Hall in the UK, and [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Ville|Theatre de la Ville]] in France.\n\nInspired by the ideals of his Guru Jnan Prakash Ghosh, Chakrabarty founded [[Shrutinandan]], a school of music.\n\n==Personal life==\nChakrabarty is married to Chandana Chakraborty. Their daughter, [[Kaushiki Chakraborty]], is also a vocalist of [[Hindustani classical music]]. Their son, Ananjan Chakraborty, is a sound engineer.\n\n==Movies==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n!  Year !! Song !! Film !! Co-Singer !! Composer !! Lyricist\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |1985|| Bela Jay Shyamrai || ''Baidurjya Rahasya''  ||  None || [[Tapan Sinha]] || [[Tapan Sinha]]\n|-\n| Nain Mein Nandalal || ''Baidurjya Rahasya''  ||  None || [[Tapan Sinha]] || [[Tapan Sinha]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |1999|| Ore Jaat Jaat koris kano || ''Niyoti''  ||  None || [[Manoranjan Saha]] || [[Bablu Samaddar]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2000|| Isaiyil Thodanguthamma || ''[[Hey Ram]]'' ||  None || [[Ilayaraja]] || [[Ilayaraja]]\n|-\n| Har Koi Samjhe || ''[[Hey Ram]]'' || None || [[Ilayaraja]] || [[Ilayaraja]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2001|| Aan Milo Sajna || ''[[Gadar: Ek Prem Katha]]''  ||  [[Parveen Sultana]] || [[Uttam Singh]] || [[Anand Bakshi]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2005|| Yeh Kaun Mujhe Yaad Aaya || ''[[Taj Mahal: An Eternal Love Story]]''  || None || [[Naushad Ali]] || [[Naqsh Lyallpuri]]\n|-\n| Vaishnava Jan To || ''[[Water (2005 film)|Water]]'' || [[Kaushiki Desikan]] || [[A. R. Rahman]],(originally composed by [[Narsinh Mehta]]) || [[Sukhwinder Singh]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2011|| Bhorer Alo || ''[[Bhorer Alo]]''  ||  None || [[Jeet Gannguli]] || Priyo Chattopadhyay\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2013|| Rabso Neha Laage ([[Bilaval]] [[Bandish]]) || ''[[Shunyo Awnko]]''  ||  [[Kaushiki Desikan]] || [[Gautam Ghose]] || [[Gautam Ghose]]\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n*[[National Film Awards|National Award]] \u2013 1989\n*[[Kumar Gandharva Award]] \u2013 1993\n*[[Sangeet Natak Akademi award]] \u2013 2000\n*[[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] \u2013 2011<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015193758/http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 October 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Banga Bibhushan]] \u2013 2012\n* Alva's Virasat Award \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite news |date=6 January 2012 |title=Alva's Virasat off to a flying start |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/article2779899.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Padma Bhushan]] 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ajoychakrabarty.com/ Ajoy Chakrabarty Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110725015311/http://www.asavari.org/Ajoy_Chakrabarty.html Ajoy Chakraborty in Asavari]\n*[http://www.asianclassicalmp3.org/ajoy.htm Ajoy Chakraborty: Live on BBC]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070321170230/http://www.shatatantri.com/artists/Ajoy_Chakrabarty/ Ajoy Chakrabarty Biography and discussion forum]\n\n{{National Film Award Best Male Playback Singer}}\n{{Bengal Film Journalists' Association Best Male Playback Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2020\u20132029}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chakrabarty, Ajoy}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Hindustani singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rabindra Bharati University alumni]]\n[[Category:Thumri]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Best Male Playback Singer National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian Classical Musicians of Bengal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Pandit Ajoy Chakrabarty\n| image = Ajoy Chakrabarty - Kolkata 2015-12-4 2128.JPG\n| caption = Ajoy Chakrabarty at Kolkata\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Ajoy Chakrabarty\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1952|12|25}}\n| origin = [[Shyamnagar, West Bengal]], [[India]]\n| occupation = [[Vocalist]]\n| genre = [[Hindustani classical music]]\n| years_active = 1977\u2013present\n}}\n\nPandit '''Ajoy Chakrabarty''' (born 25 December 1952) is an Indian [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani classical]] [[Singing|vocalist]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Jyotirmaya |date=19 March 2005 |title=Ahoy Ajoy! |url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/03/19/stories/2005031901280300.htm |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=11 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050506120503/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/03/19/stories/2005031901280300.htm |archive-date=6 May 2005 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>He was given the [[Padma Bhushan]] Award, the third highest civilian award in India in 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/padma-honours-for-ajoy-chakraborty-manilal-nag/articleshow/73621920.cms | title=Padma honours for Ajoy Chakraborty, Manilal Nag  | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | date=26 January 2020 | accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/former-ministers-arun-jaitley-sushma-swaraj-and-george-fernandes-given-padma-vibhushan/articleshow/73617205.cms | title=Arun Jaitley, Sushma Swaraj, George Fernandes given Padma Vibhushan posthumously. Here's full list of Padma award recipients | publisher=[[The Economic Times]] | date=26 January 2020 | accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MINISTRY OF HOME AFFAIRS |url=https://padmaawards.gov.in/PDFS/2020AwardeesList.pdf |website=padmaawards.gov.in |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\n==Early life and Gurus==\nChakrabarty was born in Kolkata, [[West Bengal]]. His father moved to India from his homeland, [[Mymensingh]] of [[Bangladesh]] during the partition and raised two sons in [[Shyamnagar, West Bengal|Shyamnagar]]. His younger brother, Sanjay Chakraborty, is a lyricist and composer.\n\nHe graduated top of his class in music, both in B.A and M.A from the prestigious [[Rabindra Bharati University]] in Kolkata and joined the [[ITC Sangeet Research Academy]] in 1977.\n\nHis father was his first Guru. He then studied with Pannalal Samanta, Kanaidas Baigari and [[Jnan Prakash Ghosh]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Jyotirmaya |date=28 April 2006 |title=In honour of Bade Khansaheb |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/04/28/stories/2006042801520300.htm |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nBesides that, he had learnt from Latafat Hussain Khan, Nibruttibua Sarnaik, Hirabai Barodekar and in Carnatic styles from [[M. Balamuralikrishna]], that kept enriching his musical expression and repertoire{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Despite having such pure classical \"taleem\" in the [[Khyal]] genre, he also renders lighter forms such as [[Thumri]], [[Tappa]], [[Bhajan]], [[Kirtan]], [[Indian folk music|Folk]], Film/Non-Film and modern songs, in several different languages.\n\nHe has received several prestigious awards including the Padma Shri (2011), Sangeet Natak Akademi Award (Delhi, 1999\u20132000), Kumar Gandharva National Award  (1993) and the Best Male Playback Singer Award (Bengali Film \"Chhandaneer\" 1990) (\"For bringing the rare depth of emotion, adorned by his command on the classical idiom\") and [[Tansen Samaroh|National Tansen Samman]] 2015 - by the Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soulsteer.com/Gwalior/hindustani-classical-vocalist-pandit-ajoy-chakrabarty-awarded-201415-national-tansen-samman/|title=Hindustani classical vocalist Pandit Ajoy Chakrabarty|date=2015-12-25|publisher=SouLSteer|accessdate=2015-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225184432/http://soulsteer.com/Gwalior/hindustani-classical-vocalist-pandit-ajoy-chakrabarty-awarded-201415-national-tansen-samman/|archive-date=25 December 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has also received felicitations from both the former and present Chief Ministers of his own State, West Bengal. In 2012, Chief Minister of West Bengal, [[Mamata Banerjee]] conferred him the Maha Sangeet Samman and the [[Banga Bibhushan]], two of the State\u2019s highest awards. In 2015 he has received Guru Jnan Prakash Ghosh Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\nHe also was awarded honorary citizenship in New Orleans, after performing with jazz musicians at Preservation Hall, the birthplace of jazz music.\n\n==Singing career==\n\n\nHe is a recipient of the [[Padma Shri]] ([[List of Padma Shri award recipients (2010\u201319)|2011]]) and [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] (Delhi, 1999-2000) and the [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]] in 1989- in Bengali Film \"Chhandaneer\" 1989.<ref name=\"37thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/37nfa.pdf|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|title=37th National Film Awards |accessdate=29 January 2012|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Indian classical vocalist to be invited by [[Pakistan]] and [[China]] and by BBC for their Golden Jubilee Celebration of India\u2019s Independence.\n\nHe has performed in some of the most prestigious venues around the world such as [[Carnegie Hall]], [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|The Kennedy Center]], New Orleans Jazz Preservation Hall in the US, the [[Royal Albert Hall|Royal Albert hall]] and Queen Elizabeth Hall in the UK, and [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Ville|Theatre de la Ville]] in France.\n\nInspired by the ideals of his Guru Jnan Prakash Ghosh, Chakrabarty founded [[Shrutinandan]], a school of music.\n\n==Personal life==\nChakrabarty is married to Chandana Chakraborty. Their daughter, [[Kaushiki Chakraborty]], is also a vocalist of [[Hindustani classical music]]. Their son, Ananjan Chakraborty, is a sound engineer.\n\n==Movies==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n!  Year !! Song !! Film !! Co-Singer !! Composer !! Lyricist\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |1985|| Bela Jay Shyamrai || ''Baidurjya Rahasya''  ||  None || [[Tapan Sinha]] || [[Tapan Sinha]]\n|-\n| Nain Mein Nandalal || ''Baidurjya Rahasya''  ||  None || [[Tapan Sinha]] || [[Tapan Sinha]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |1999|| Ore Jaat Jaat koris kano || ''Niyoti''  ||  None || [[Manoranjan Saha]] || [[Bablu Samaddar]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2000|| Isaiyil Thodanguthamma || ''[[Hey Ram]]'' ||  None || [[Ilayaraja]] || [[Ilayaraja]]\n|-\n| Har Koi Samjhe || ''[[Hey Ram]]'' || None || [[Ilayaraja]] || [[Ilayaraja]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2001|| Aan Milo Sajna || ''[[Gadar: Ek Prem Katha]]''  ||  [[Parveen Sultana]] || [[Uttam Singh]] || [[Anand Bakshi]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2005|| Yeh Kaun Mujhe Yaad Aaya || ''[[Taj Mahal: An Eternal Love Story]]''  || None || [[Naushad Ali]] || [[Naqsh Lyallpuri]]\n|-\n| Vaishnava Jan To || ''[[Water (2005 film)|Water]]'' || [[Kaushiki Desikan]] || [[A. R. Rahman]],(originally composed by [[Narsinh Mehta]]) || [[Sukhwinder Singh]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2011|| Bhorer Alo || ''[[Bhorer Alo]]''  ||  None || [[Jeet Gannguli]] || Priyo Chattopadhyay\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |2013|| Rabso Neha Laage ([[Bilaval]] [[Bandish]]) || ''[[Shunyo Awnko]]''  ||  [[Kaushiki Desikan]] || [[Gautam Ghose]] || [[Gautam Ghose]]\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n*[[National Film Awards|National Award]] \u2013 1989\n*[[Kumar Gandharva Award]] \u2013 1993\n*[[Sangeet Natak Akademi award]] \u2013 2000\n*[[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] \u2013 2011<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015193758/http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 October 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Banga Bibhushan]] \u2013 2012\n* Alva's Virasat Award \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite news |date=6 January 2012 |title=Alva's Virasat off to a flying start |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/article2779899.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Padma Bhushan]] 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ajoychakrabarty.com/ Ajoy Chakrabarty Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110725015311/http://www.asavari.org/Ajoy_Chakrabarty.html Ajoy Chakraborty in Asavari]\n*[http://www.asianclassicalmp3.org/ajoy.htm Ajoy Chakraborty: Live on BBC]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070321170230/http://www.shatatantri.com/artists/Ajoy_Chakrabarty/ Ajoy Chakrabarty Biography and discussion forum]\n\n{{National Film Award Best Male Playback Singer}}\n{{Bengal Film Journalists' Association Best Male Playback Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2020\u20132029}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chakrabarty, Ajoy}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Hindustani singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rabindra Bharati University alumni]]\n[[Category:Thumri]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Best Male Playback Singer National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian Classical Musicians of Bengal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n", "name_user": "Prathamesh Patki", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed Empty and Duplicate tag \"Early Life\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ajoy_