ireann|RT\u00c9]]).<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0604/murphyp.html|title= Death of former RT\u00c9 presenter Peter Murphy|publisher= RT\u00c9 News|date= 4 June 2011|accessdate= 26 January 2012}}</ref>\n* 22 October \u2013 [[Cathal O'Shannon (TV presenter)|Cathal O'Shannon]], 83; journalist and television presenter.<ref>{{cite news|title=RT\u00c9 journalist Cathal O'Shannon dies aged 83 |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1022/oshannonc.html |accessdate=22 October 2011 |newspaper=RT\u00c9 News |date=22 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024081210/http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1022/oshannonc.html |archivedate=24 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2011 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2011}}\n\n==2012==\n* Ongoing \u2013 [[TV50]], a series of special events throughout 2012, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the launch of [[RT\u00c9 Television]], then known as Telef\u00eds \u00c9ireann, on 31 December 1961.<ref name=\"RT\u00c9 launches TV50\"/>\n\n===January===\n*3 January \u2013 RT\u00c9 offended viewers by depicting a dog having its legs tied together and being tossed overboard into the sea off the coast of [[County Donegal]] as part of its ''TV50'' celebrations in a broadcast on 3 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.donegaldaily.com/2012/01/05/horror-as-rte-show-footage-of-dog-being-drowned-off-donegal-coast/|title=Horror as RT\u00c9 show footage of dog being drowned off Donegal coast|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=5 January 2012|work=Donegal Daily}}</ref>\n* 17 January \u2013 RT\u00c9 agrees to scrap its advertising \"share deal\" scheme from July following an investigation by the [[Competition Authority (Ireland)|Competition Authority]]. Rival broadcaster [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] had argued the practice, in which RT\u00c9 offered a discount to any advertiser which committed a percentage of its budget for television advertising to them was anti-competitive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0117/rte-business.html |title=RT\u00c9 to change ad discount system |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9.ie |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>\n* 30 January \u2013 Employees at RT\u00c9 vote to back the broadcaster's plans to cut its staff budget by \u20ac1m a year following a ballot of members of the Trade Union Group. The vote comes after a recommendation for them to do so from an internal industrial relations tribunal, and will see the money saved through reductions in holiday pay.<ref>{{cite news|first=Cormac |last=Murphy |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/rte-staff-agree-to-1m-cuts-for-pay-hikebut-stars-wont-be-hit-3003522.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120803062647/http://www.herald.ie/news/rte-staff-agree-to-1m-cuts-for-pay-hikebut-stars-wont-be-hit-3003522.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 August 2012 |title=RT\u00c9 staff agree to \u20ac1m cuts for pay hike...but stars won't be hit |publisher=Herald.ie |work=Evening Herald |date=30 January 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 6 February \u2013 [[Anglo Irish Bank]] agrees to allow Doughty-Hanson, the UK-based private equity firm that owns the loss-making [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] to take a repayment holiday on an \u20ac80m loan until the TV network is sold.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/anglo-to-park-private-equity-companys-80m-loan-in-tv3-deal-3011358.html|title= Anglo to 'park' private equity company's \u20ac80m loan in TV3 deal|publisher= |work= Irish Independent|first= Laura|last= Noonan|date= 7 February 2012|accessdate= 9 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 11 February \u2013 The live televised [[France national rugby union team|France]] versus [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]] match in the [[2012 Six Nations Championship]] is cancelled minutes prior to kick-off, prompting boos to ring out among disgruntled spectators inside a packed [[Stade de France]]. It is the first time such an event has happened since 1985.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0211/rugby.html |title=Ireland match called off over frozen pitch |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 News |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Chris |last=Whyatt |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/16969821 |title=Six Nations: France v Ireland match called off at last minute |publisher=BBC |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Evan |last=Fanning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/feb/11/six-nations-france-ireland-live |title=Six Nations 2012: France v Ireland \u2013 as it (very nearly) happened |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> [[Ryle Nugent]] tells viewers from his Irish commentary box, \"It is a dark day in the history of the Six Nations\".<ref name=rte_as_it_didnt_happen/> [[Tom McGurk]] in studio asks, \"What are we doing in a rugby stadium at 9pm on a Saturday night in February?\"<ref name=rte_as_it_didnt_happen>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/sixnations/2012/0211/live_sixnations_ireland_france.html |title=As it Didn't Happen: France v Ireland |first=Brendan |last=Cole |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=11 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212232727/http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/sixnations/2012/0211/live_sixnations_ireland_france.html |archivedate=12 February 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 12 February \u2013 [[David Kelly (actor)|David Kelly]], the \"grand old man of Irish acting\", dies in [[Dublin]] aged 82 following a short illness.<ref name=DavidKellyTimes/>\n* 13 February \u2013 The first advert in the UK and Ireland aimed specifically at dogs is broadcast by [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]]. The 60-second commercial for the [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare|Bakers]] dog food brand features high-pitched sounds that cannot be heard by humans, and is a send up of the 1969 film ''[[The Italian Job]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=Collins |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/pets/9077741/First-advert-for-dogs-to-reach-British-TV-screens.html |title=First advert for dogs to reach British TV screens |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 February \u2013 ''In Bed with the Irish'', a documentary set among Irish couples under duvets, is broadcast by RT\u00c9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0213/realitybites.html|title=Ireland under duvet in documentary|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=13 February 2012|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 17 February \u2013 A 59-year-old RT\u00c9 props assistant, who injured himself after falling over a studio floor lamp while working on ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'', is awarded \u20ac18,500 in damages. The judge says he had worked accident free in RT\u00c9 for 38 years, that he had been working in poorly lit conditions in a cluttered studio when he was injured by one of RT\u00c9's props, and that he had been in pain since sustaining his injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0217/mcullena.html |title=\u20ac18,500 damages for Saturday Night Show injury |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302020620/http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0217/312505-mcullena/ |archivedate=2 March 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 5 March \u2013 TV3 airs the documentary ''[[Paul Connolly (journalist)|Ireland's Secret Sex Lives: Paul Connolly Investigates]]'' which looks at the subcultures of [[Swinging (sexual practice)|swingers]] and [[Dogging (sexual slang)|dogging]] in Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|first=Niamh |last=Horan |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/swinging-sex-clubs-attracting-societys-elites-3038998.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802205458/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/swinging-sex-clubs-attracting-societys-elites-3038998.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 2 August 2012 |title=Swinging sex clubs attracting society's elites |publisher=Independent.ie |newspaper=Sunday Independent |date=4 March 2012 |accessdate=4 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 7 March \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] upholds a complaint against RT\u00c9 made by [[Se\u00e1n Gallagher]] relating to the tweet that derailed [[2011 Irish presidential election|his presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0307/gallaghers.html|title=BAI upholds complaint against Frontline tweet|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 March \u2013 ''Pyjama Girls'', a documentary set among Dublin's public pyjama wearing community, is broadcast by RT\u00c9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0313/girlsp.html|title=Pyjama Girls on RT\u00c9 One tonight|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 March \u2013 TV3 defends its reality programme ''[[Tallafornia]]'' after it was condemned by Senator [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] as a \"drink-sodden programme\" which encourages its participants to \"behave licentiously and compete to bring people home to bed them\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tallafornia-exploiting-its-stars-says-norris-3049065.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120803043625/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tallafornia-exploiting-its-stars-says-norris-3049065.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 3 August 2012 |title='Tallafornia' exploiting its stars, says Norris |publisher=Independent.ie |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=14 March 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 17 March \u2013 Debut of RT\u00c9's #HowToBeIrish, a programme made entirely of clips sent in by viewers explaining what being Irish means to them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0217/howtobeirish.html |title=How Irish are you? |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 March \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] Director of Programming Ben Frow calls for resignations at RT\u00c9 in the wake of the Father [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Kevin Reynolds]] scandal to prevent the libel case causing further damage to the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/heads-should-roll-over-priest-libel-tv3-chief-3059358.html |title=Heads should roll over priest libel |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=23 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 25 March \u2013 As the 100th anniversary of the [[sinking of the RMS Titanic]] approaches TV3 begins airing [[Julian Fellowes]]' epic [[Titanic (2012 miniseries)|retelling of the disaster]]. TV3 has itself invested \u20ac300m in the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tv3-hoping-their-titanic-stays-afloat-3060164.html |title=TV3 hoping their 'Titanic' stays afloat |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 27 March \u2013  RT\u00c9 broadcasts a tribute to deceased comedian [[Hal Roach (comedian)|Hal Roach]] in one of its [[graveyard slot]]s, a repeat airing of a programme from the ''That's Entertainment'' series first broadcast in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0327/roachh.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120908090913/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0327/roachh.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 8 September 2012 |title=RT\u00c9 tribute to Hal Roach tonight |date=27 March 2012 |accessdate=27 March 2012 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |df= }}</ref>\n* 29 March \u2013 [[Director-General of RT\u00c9|RT\u00c9 Director-General]] [[Noel Curran]] announces \u20ac25m of budget cuts at the broadcaster, including pay reductions, staff redundancies and the closure of [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]'s London office.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rte-staff-stunned-as-second-tier-stars-take-a-30-pc-pay-cut-3066452.html |title=RT\u00c9 staff stunned as 'second tier' stars take a 30 pc pay cut |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=30 March 2012 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 31 March \u2013 Former [[broadcast journalism|broadcast journalist]] [[Mike Nesbitt]] is [[2012 Ulster Unionist Party leadership election|elected]] leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-17572015|title= Mike Nesbitt is new Ulster Unionist leader|publisher= BBC|work= BBC News|date= 31 March 2012|accessdate= 31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 3 April \u2013 Following last year's defamation of [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Father Kevin Reynolds]] by [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]], the state-controlled broadcaster's head of current affairs Ed Mulhall retires, Ken O'Shea resigns from ''Prime Time'' and its stablemate, ''Prime Time Investigates'' is axed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/rte-axes-prime-time-following-watchdog-report-3069870.html |title=Prime Time Investigates axed following watchdog report |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=3 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0403/breaking38.html?via=rel |title=RT\u00c9's head of news steps down |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=Irish Times Trust |date=3 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 6 April \u2013 RT\u00c9 breaks with the [[Good Friday]] tradition of not sounding the [[Angelus]] bells by broadcasting them as usual on television. They are also heard for the first time on [[Holy Saturday]], a move contrary to [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] practice which is for them to be silenced to mark the period between the [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]] and [[Resurrection of Jesus]]. RT\u00c9 argues that the daily prayer belongs to everyone rather than a single faith.<ref>{{cite news|first=Justine |last=McCarthy |first2=Harry |last2=Leech |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1012435.ece |title=Toll and trouble as RTE keeps Angelus on TV |publisher=News UK |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=8 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2015 |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Damien |last=Corless |url=http://www.independent.ie/life/for-whom-the-bell-tolls-31114607.html |title=For whom the bell tolls |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=4 April 2015 |accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 10 April \u2013  RT\u00c9 says it is disappointed after details of a report from the [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] into the ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time Investigates]]'' programme ''[[Mission to Prey]]'' were leaked. The report shows the BAI will find the documentary was unfair and breached the privacy of [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Fr Kevin Reynolds]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17665860 |work=BBC News |title=Leaked priest defamation report 'finds RT\u00c9 unfair' |publisher=BBC |date=10 April 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The BAI has launched an investigation into how the leak occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/watchdog-probes-rte-report-leak-16142996.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720182112/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/watchdog-probes-rte-report-leak-16142996.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 July 2012 |title=Watchdog probes RT\u00c9 report leak |publisher= |newspaper=Belfast Telegraph |date=10 April 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2012 }}</ref>\n* 17 April \u2013 An edition of the recently axed ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time Investigates]]'' about the illegal cigarette trade is among three RT\u00c9 documentaries to win awards at the 2012 New York Festivals International Television and Film Awards.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eva |last=Hall |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4284818&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=RT\u00c9 Scoops Three International Awards For Documentary |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=19 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 17 April \u2013 TV3 apologises for disparaging remarks that were made about [[Limerick]] in a recent edition of its series ''[[Come Dine with Me (Ireland)|Come Dine with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheridan |first=Anne |url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/news/local/tv3-apologises-for-remarks-about-limerick-on-come-dine-with-me-1-3747188 |title=TV3 apologises for remarks about Limerick on 'Come Dine With Me' |newspaper=Limerick Leader |publisher= |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 18 April \u2013 Journalists at RT\u00c9 condemn the broadcaster's proposed closure of its London office as a \u201cbetrayal of RT\u00c9's public service remit\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ronan |last=McGreevy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0418/breaking56.html |title=RT\u00c9 journalists condemn closure |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 18 April \u2013 Plans are announced for TV3 to double the size of its headquarters building at Westgate Business Park, Ballymount, Dublin, after the broadcaster signed a new lease with its landlord, Irish Property Unite Trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/0418/1224314872124.html |title=TV3 doubles down on HQ lease |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 April \u2013 The [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] urges the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] to support calls for RT\u00c9 to reverse its decision to close its London office, which is scheduled to shut following [[2012 Summer Olympics|this year's Olympic games]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0424/1224315104222.html |title=Support sought to halt RT\u00c9 closure |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 April \u2013 Pat Hayes, the [[Mayor of Waterford]] expresses his dismay over suggestions RT\u00c9 might close its studio in the city and cover the southeast region from Dublin. Waterford is one of four regional studios facing the axe because of budget cuts by the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0424/1224315104311.html |title=Mayor urges RT\u00c9 not to downgrade coverage of the southeast region |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 25 April \u2013 RT\u00c9 defends its broadcasting of ''Masterpiece: Ireland's Favourite Painting'' after presenter [[Michael Murphy (journalist)|Mike Murphy]] wrote to ''[[The Irish Times]]'' criticising the show's length and timeslot (it aired for an hour from 10.15pm on 17 April, which Murphy described as: \u201cCromwellian edict of arts programming being banished into the Connacht of broadcasting, ie, at, or past most people\u2019s bedtime\u201d).<ref>{{cite news|first=Ronan |last=McGreevy |url=