le=Sky Customers Get Connected in Ireland |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 BAI confirms its intention to enter into negotiations with UTV Ireland Limited for a television content provision contract.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newton |first=Aisling |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286832&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=BAI to enter into TV Content Contract with 'UTV Ireland' |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n*7 February \u2013 The Data Protection Commissioner launches an investigation after revelations that [[An Post]] has been making people disclose their bank account details if they wish to pay their [[television licensing in the Republic of Ireland|television license]] by [[direct debit]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=McCabe |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/an-post-faces-probe-after-seeking-bank-details-for-tv-licences-29987601.html |title=An Post faces probe after seeking bank details for TV licences |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n*14 February \u2013 Figures released by [[UPC Ireland]] show an 11% growth in broadband subscribers to 338,300 over the past 12 months, but a 4% fall in its overall TV subscribers to 427,000.<ref>{{cite news|first=Adrian |last=Weckler \u2013 Updated&nbsp;14 February 2014 02:09 PM |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/technology/upc-ireland-adds-broadband-subscribers-but-tv-users-fall-30009475.html |title=UPC Ireland adds broadband subscribers but TV users fall |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*22 February \u2013 RT\u00c9 airs the Rugby Union match between the Irish women\u2019s team and England from Twickenham.<ref>{{cite news|first=Johnny |last=Watterson |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/rugby/ireland-women-s-twickenham-match-set-for-live-television-broadcast-1.1690776 |title=Ireland women\u2019s Twickenham match set for live television broadcast |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*26 February \u2013 A third series of the BBC period crime drama ''[[Ripper Street]]'', axed by the broadcaster in 2013, will be produced in Ireland by [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] for its video on-demand service.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sorcha |last=Corcoran |url=http://www.businessandleadership.com/exporting/item/44899-third-series-of-tv-drama/ |title=Third series of TV drama 'Ripper Street' to be produced in Ireland |publisher=Businessandleadership.com |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286891&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Amazon Revives BBC Crime Drama \u2018Ripper Street\u2019 |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 [[UTV Ireland]] signs a ten-year contract with BAI to provide a general entertainment channel based in Dublin that will go on air from 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0227/507064-utv/ |title=UTV Ireland signs deal for TV service in Republic |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=27 February 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*3 March \u2013 A technical glitch during RT\u00c9's ''[[Primetime (Irish TV program)|Primetime]]'' current affairs show leads to a small portion of an interview with [[Maxim Peshkov]], Russia's ambassador to Ireland, playing on a loop for several minutes. The phrase \"Irish Ukrainians not Russians\" is heard for around fifteen minutes, with the clip quickly becoming popular on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26431150 |work=BBC News |title=RT\u00c9 'Irish Ukrainians not Russians' glitch a Twitter hit |publisher=BBC |date=4 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 TV3 names Ireland's Element Pictures and Britain's Company Pictures as its preferred partners in plans to launch a new soap.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286906&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 Announces its Preferred Soap Partners |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=3 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n*4 March \u2013 [[John Yorke (producer)|John Yorke]], a former executive producer of ''[[EastEnders]]'', will oversee production of TV3's new soap, it is announced.<ref>{{cite news|first=Meg |last=Drewett |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a555305/former-eastenders-executive-producer-to-head-up-new-irish-soap-for-tv3.html#~p4sDngsGktcDw8 |title=Former EastEnders executive producer to head up new Irish soap for TV3 |publisher=Digital Spy |date=4 March 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 RT\u00c9 creates a video tribute to former Irish rugby captain [[Brian O'Driscoll]] imagining how he might be remembered in forty years from now, as an old man recalls the player's career to his awestruck grandson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/blog/sportblog/rte-create-stirring-brian-odriscoll-tribute-video-ahead-of-italian-clash-30075059.html |title=RTE create stirring Brian O'Driscoll tribute video ahead of Italian clash |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=8 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n*27 March \u2013 Sky announce details of a scholarship for students taking the Broadcast Production MA offered by [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]]'s National Film School. The Sky Academy TV Scholarship will be available from September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/training/TrainingNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287008&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Sky Launches TV Scholarship with IADT |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 [[Saorview]] customers will be unable to receive [[RT\u00c9 One]] after today if they have not retuned their set-top boxes to receive technical upgrades for high-definition television.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fiona |last=Dillon |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/retune-your-tv-or-lose-rte-one-saorview-customers-are-warned-30140299.html |title=Re-tune your TV or lose RT\u00c9 One, Saorview customers are warned |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=31 March 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April \u2013 The [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]] announce a new three year broadcasting rights deal that will see RT\u00c9 air 31 games of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Championships]], with a further 14 games being shown via subscription on [[Sky Sports]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0401/606047-gaa-tv-rights/ |title=GAA announces TV rights allocation |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=1 April 2014 |accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> The decision will bring [[Gaelic football]] to a wider audience outside Ireland, but prompts concerns among fans and some players that the deal could lead to the game losing its amateur status.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ian |last=McCourt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/apr/15/gaelic-football-selling-games-soul-to-sky |title=Gaelic football and hurling's ruling body accused of selling its soul to Sky |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n*2 April \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 Two]] announces the launch of The RT\u00c9 Two New Voices Award, in conjunction with the National Student Media Awards, which will give students an opportunity to compete for a summer work placement at the station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0402/606135-rte-two-looking-for-new-presenting-talent/ |title=RT\u00c9 Two looking for new presenting talent |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=2 April 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n*15 April \u2013 TV3 secures the broadcasting rights for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/rugby-world-cup/2014/0415/608984-tv3-win-broadcasting-rights-for-rugby-world-cup/ |title=TV3 wins rights to broadcast 2015 Rugby World Cup |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Kirsty |last=Blake-Knox |first2=Joyce |last2=Fegan |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/tv3-outbids-rte-for-rugby-world-cup-2015-30189826.html |title=TV3 outbids RT\u00c9 for Rugby World Cup 2015 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=16 April 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*27 April \u2013 [[Brendan McCahey]] wins the [[The Voice of Ireland (series 3)|third series]] of ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0428/612160-brendan-mccahey-wins-voice-of-ireland/ |title=Brendan McCahey wins Voice of Ireland |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=28 April 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n*29 April \u2013 Mary Curtis is appointed as head of [[UTV Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287107&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=UTV Ireland Appoints Mary Curtis as Head of Channel |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=29 April 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*1 May \u2013 Launch of [[Irish TV]], a [[free-to-air]] international channel for the Irish diaspora, broadcasting in Ireland, Europe and the United States.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4287121&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=IrishTV Launches Tonight |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n*7 May \u2013 TV3 confirms its new soap will be set in a police precinct in a fictional harbour town, and  has the working title ''[[Red Rock (TV series)|Red Rock]]''. It will employ around 100 people, and is expected to begin airing in January 2015. The series is part of a schedule that will see the channel spending more on home made content than imports for the first time, with it airing up to 100 hours of homegrown content per week. TV3 also have the broadcast rights for the 2015 series of ''[[The X Factor (TV series)|The X Factor]]'', ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' and ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', as well as exclusive coverage of the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]]. The channel also announces plans to produce an Irish version of the UK television series ''[[Gogglebox]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4287140&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 announces its \"most ambitious schedule ever\" |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=7 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a569488/new-irish-soap-gets-working-title-red-rock.html#~p4sMyLr8H3IbYx |title=New Irish soap gets working title Red Rock |publisher=Digital Spy |date=8 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*12 May \u2013 TV3 executives Daragh Byrne, Joanne King, Paula McCarthy, David McMunn and Daragh O\u2019Halloran have been recruited by UTV Ireland, the new broadcaster has announced. They are among nine people recruited to senior positions at the upcoming channel.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sam |last=Griffin |first2=Kirsty |last2=Blake Knox |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/five-senior-tv3-executives-defect-to-new-broadcaster-utv-30267862.html |title=Five senior TV3 executives defect to new broadcaster UTV |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Joyce |last=Fegan |first2=Eimear |last2=Rabbitte |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/utv-raid-tv3-staff-as-rivalry-grows-30267555.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150216144509/http://www.herald.ie/news/utv-raid-tv3-staff-as-rivalry-grows-30267555.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 February 2015 |title=UTV raid TV3 staff as rivalry grows |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=13 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n*21 May \u2013 RT\u00c9 Gaelic football pundit [[Joe Brolly]] apologises to [[Sky Sports]] presenter [[Rachel Wyse]] after posting a tweet in which he described Sky's planned GAA coverage, which is to feature Wyse as a presenter, as \"TV3 plus Baywatch babe\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/joe-brolly-issues-grovelling-apology-to-rachel-wyse-for-crass-baywatch-jibe-30293208.html |title=Joe Brolly issues grovelling apology to Rachel Wyse for crass 'Baywatch' jibe |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=21 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n*24 May \u2013 ''[[The Irish Independent]]'' reports the dramatic departure of two producers from TV3's ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'', an event occurring only days after the channel lost five of its senior executives.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sam |last=Griffin |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/shock-for-tv3-as-producers-quit-vincent-browne-programme-30300182.html |title=Shock for TV3 as producers quit Vincent Browne programme |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=24 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*4 June \u2013 RT\u00c9 One airs the documentary ''The Torture Files'' which explores the treatment of the \"Hooded Men\" of [[Derry]] following [[Operation Demetrius|their internment]] by the British Army in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derryjournal.com/what-s-on/arts-culture/rte-to-screen-hooded-men-documentary-1-6094724 |title=RTE to screen Hooded Men documentary |publisher=Derry Journal Newspapers |newspaper=Derry Journal |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*5 June \u2013 TV3 airs the first Pride of Ireland Awards, an annual event launched to honour ordinary people who have acted bravely or extraordinarily in challenging situations. The event is held at Dublin's [[Mansion House, Dublin|Mansion House]] and presented by [[Una Foden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/pr_sub.php?type=1&view_pr=539 |title=TV3 will air Ireland\u2019s very first Pride of Ireland Awards |publisher=TV3 |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287215&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 to air Pride of Ireland Awards |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n*9 June \u2013 Broadcaster [[Vincent Browne]] reveals that he recently suffered a bout of pneumonia but continued to work during his illness. Details of his condition are disclosed following his absence from the evening's edition of his ''Tonight'' programme and reports that he had spent the previous weekend in hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/vincent-browne-was-struck-by-pneumonia-last-month-but-continued-to-work-30340922.html |title=Vincent Browne was struck by pneumonia last month but continued to work |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> ''Tonight with Vincent Browne'' is presented by [[Tom McGurk]] in Browne's absence.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joe |last=O'Shea |url=http://www.independent.ie/life/falling-ratings-but-tv3s-400k-anchor-isnt-about-to-step-down-30352214.html |title=Falling ratings ... but TV3's \u20ac400k anchor isn't about to step down |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=15 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*9 June \u2013 Comedian [[David McSavage]] accuses RT\u00c9 of \"dictatorial\" censorship after the broadcaster banned a comedy sketch featuring three nuns and a crucified Jesus that parodies a recent [[Diet Coke]] advert. The \"Wild Nuns\" sketch was due to form part of the fourth episode of the latest series of McSavage's comedy show ''Savage Eye'', but in an email to the comedian, RT\u00c9 said it would not air the piece because they felt it could \"very quickly generate the potential for justifiable offence from viewers of the Christian faith\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/republic-of-ireland/raunchy-nuns-diet-coke-jesus-parody-banned-by-rte-30343039.html |title=Raunchy nuns Diet Coke Jesus parody banned by RTE |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*16 June \u2013 [[Minister for Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]] [[Pat Rabbitte]] announces a review of television coverage of the designated sporting and other events to determine what content should be [[free-to-air]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Anne-Marie |last=Walsh |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rabbitte-to-begin-review-of-freetoair-sport-on-tv-30356759.html |title=Rabbitte to begin review of free-to-air sport on TV |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=16 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*17 June \u2013 The ''Irish Independent'' reports that ''[[Republic of Telly]]'' presenter [[Jennifer Maguire]] will front a programme as part of RT\u00c9 Two's ''Reality Bites'' strand in which she will help young unemployed people find work. ''[[The Unemployables]]'' will air in the autumn and see her