ew ad model on sports channel \u2013 Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmedia.ie/bundles/broadband-tv-phone/|title=Broadband, TV & Phone Bundles in Ireland \u2013 Virgin Media Ireland|website=www.virginmedia.ie|accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n*28 September \u2013 ''[[Players of the Faithful]]'' airs on RT\u00c9 One.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.loosehorse.ie/portfolio-items/players-of-the-faithful/|title=Players of the Faithful}}</ref>\n*12 October \u2013 ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'' is broadcast live from [[Central Hall Westminster]] in London, the first time the programme has broadcast from the United Kingdom since 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/1012/1001927-tubridy-says-london-late-late-will-be-irish-on-tour/ |title=Tubridy excited and nervous ahead of London Late Late |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=12 October 2018 |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/1003/1000719-late-late-show-in-london/ |title= London Late Late Shows |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 Archives |year=2018 |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2018 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2018}}\n\n==2019==\n*2 February \u2013 The second series of ''[[Ireland's Got Talent]]'' debuts on [[Virgin Media One]].\n*19 February \u2013 Launch of the timeshift channel [[RT\u00c92+1]].\n*8 March \u2013 \n**[[Sarah McTernan]] is announced by RT\u00c9 as the Irish representative for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]] in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]], where she will perform the song \"[[22 (Sarah McTernan song)|22]]\".\n**The Friday evening edition was [[Virgin Media One]]'s ''[[The 6 O'Clock Show]]'' is replaced by ''[[Xpos\u00e9]]''.\n*24 March \u2013 [[Mairead Ronan]] and dance partner [[John Nolan (dancer)|John Nolan]] win the [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish series 3)|third series]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*27 March \u2013 Virgin Media announces that its partnership with Sky's AdSmart will to go live in Ireland in the final quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/news/2019/03/27/virgin-media-sets-date-run-addressable-tv-ads-through-game-changer-sky-adsmart|title=Virgin Media sets date to run addressable TV ads through 'game changer' Sky AdSmart|website=The Drum|accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n*7 April \u2013 BSD win the [[Ireland's Got Talent (series 2)|second series]] of ''[[Ireland's Got Talent]]''.\n*16 May \u2013 Sarah McTernan becomes the fifth Irish act in six years to not reach the Eurovision Song Contest final, when she is among the semi-finalists who are not selected for the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-48268909 |title=Eurovision 2019: Ireland knocked out in second semi-final |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 May 2019 |accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n*23 June \u2013 The ''Sunday Independent'' reports that the [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] has recommended that on-demand television services broadcasting in Ireland should pay a levy to do so.<ref>{{cite news|first=Samantha |last=McCaughren |url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/apple-tv-faces-irish-levy-under-new-bai-rules-38243636.html |title=Apple TV faces Irish levy under new BAI rules |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=23 June 2019 |accessdate=29 June 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n*25 June \u2013 Pensioners stage a protest outside the BBC studios in Belfast and Derry following the BBC's decision to end universal free UK television licenses for those aged 75 and over, a decision that will affect those living in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-48759552 |title=TV licence: Protest at BBC for over-75s decision |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 June 2019 |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n*28 June \u2013 Veteran presenter [[Gay Byrne]] is honoured with the Ireland-US Council's Lifetime Achievement Award at a ceremony at [[Dublin Castle]], but is unable to attend the event due to a broken wrist and chest infection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2019/0628/1059121-gay-byrne-honoured-with-lifetime-achievement-award/ |title=Gay Byrne honoured with Lifetime Achievement Award |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=28 June 2019 |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n*15 August \u2013 [[eir Sport]] and [[Virgin Media Sport]] contract a deal to show Virgin Media Sport on [[eir Vision]] and eir Sport 1 on [[Virgin Media Ireland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/eir-sport-and-virgin-media-agree-deal-to-share-sports-packages-1.3987033|title=Eir Sport and Virgin Media agree deal to share sports packages|first=Ruaidhr\u00ed|last=Croke|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n*12 September \u2013 Virgin Media Sport HD launches on [[Sky Ireland|Sky]] on channel 422.\n*4 November \u2013 The death is announced of veteran broadcaster [[Gay Byrne]], who presented ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'' for 37 years.<ref name=Byrne>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-50289744 |title=Gay Byrne: Veteran Irish broadcaster dies aged 85 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 November 2019 |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n* 14 March \u2013 [[Pat Laffan]], 79, actor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/father-ted-actor-pat-laffan-best-known-as-pat-mustard-has-passed-away-aged-79-37914718.html |title =Father Ted actor Pat Laffan \u2013 best known as 'Pat Mustard' \u2013 has passed away aged 79|date=14 March 2019|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n*June \u2013 Tom Jordan, actor (''[[Fair City]]'')<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2019/0629/1059223-veteran-fair-city-star-tom-jordan-dies/ |title=Veteran Fair City star Tom Jordan dies |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=29 June 2019 |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n*11 July \u2013 [[Brendan Grace]], 68, comedian and singer (''[[Father Ted]]'')<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2019/0711/1061410-irish-comedian-brendan-grace-has-died/ |title=Comedian Brendan Grace has died |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=11 July 2019 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48947352 |title=Brendan Grace: Irish comedian and Father Ted actor dies |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 July 2019 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n*14 July \u2013 [[Karl Shiels]], 47, actor (''[[Fair City]]'')<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-48996274 |title=Karl Shiels: Irish TV and theatre star dies at 47 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 July 2019 |accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n*23 July \u2013 [[Danika McGuigan]], 33, actress<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-49095513 |title=Danika McGuigan: Actress and daughter of ex-boxer dies aged 33 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 July 2019 |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n*4 November \u2013 [[Gay Byrne]], 85, broadcaster (''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'')<ref name=Byrne/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2019}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2009 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2010}}\n\n[[Category:2011 in Irish television|2011 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2012 in Irish television|2012 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2013 in Irish television|2013 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2014 in Irish television|2014 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2015 in Irish television|2015 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2016 in Irish television|2016 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2017 in Irish television|2017 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2018 in Irish television|2018 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2019 in Irish television|2019 in Irish television]]\n[[Category:2010 in Irish television|2010 in Irish television]]\n", "text_old": "{{split|2010 in Irish television|2011 in Irish television|2012 in Irish television|2013 in Irish television|2014 in Irish television|2015 in Irish television|2016 in Irish television|2017 in Irish television|2018 in Irish television|2019 in Irish television|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n\n==2010==\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n*January \u2013 The compliance committee of the [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] upholds a further ten complaints against [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] in relation to ''[[Play TV (Ireland)|Play TV]]''. A further three complaints are upheld in February.\n*8 January - Amid a deep freeze and in what has since been commemorated as \"one of the most memorable moments of Irish television\", an RT\u00c9 news bulletin broadcasts one male individual slipping and sliding down the street in Dublin.<ref>{{cite news|first=Denise|last=O'Donoghue|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/discover/the-nation-first-saw-this-guy-slipping-on-ice-five-years-ago-today-657245.html|title=The nation first saw this guy slipping on ice five years ago today|work=BreakingNews.ie|date=8 January 2015|accessdate=8 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409191654/http://www.breakingnews.ie/discover/the-nation-first-saw-this-guy-slipping-on-ice-five-years-ago-today-657245.html|archivedate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*1 February \u2013 Minister for Communications [[Eamon Ryan]] signs an agreement with the UK's [[Ben Bradshaw]] enabling viewers within [[Northern Ireland]] to watch [[RT\u00c9 One]], [[RT\u00c9 Two]] and [[TG4]] on a [[free-to-air]] basis as of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0202/1224263582384.html|title=RT\u00c9 and TG4 to be freely available in North in 2012 \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Tue, 2 Feb 2010|accessdate=3 January 2012 | date=2 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0201/communications.html|title=RT\u00c9 News: Ryan signs TG4 agreement with the British government|accessdate=3 January 2012 | date=1 February 2010}}</ref> The agreement between both jurisdictions will also guarantee that viewers within the Republic of Ireland will be able to view [[BBC One Northern Ireland]] and [[BBC Two Northern Ireland]] on the Republic's free-to-air service which is to debut in late 2010. A cross-border initiative has always been on the agenda for the [[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]] in the Republic of Ireland, but it is later confirmed that BBC Northern Ireland services will be offered in the Republic on a 'paid-for' basis and not the original free-to-air basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boards.ie/vbulletin/showthread.php?t=2055815871&page=9 |title=Government agreement: Free-To-Air RTE in NI, BBC in RoI on DTT platform \u2013 Page 9 |publisher=boards.ie |date= |accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n*26 February \u2013 An edition of [[RT\u00c9 One]]'s ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' aired on this date attracts criticism after accusations the show snubbed a television journalist from a rival broadcaster. [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]]'s Western Correspondent [[Jenny McCudden]] was in the audience to promote her book ''Impact: The Human Stories Behind Ireland's Road Tragedies'', but although the title was mentioned by host [[Ryan Tubridy]], McCudden's presence was ignored.<ref name=petty_rivalry_with_tv3>{{cite news|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/authors-friends-accuse-rte-of-late-late-snub-due-to-petty-rivalry-with-tv3-2092728.html|title=Author's friends accuse RT\u00c9 of Late Late snub due to petty rivalry with TV3|date=9 March 2010|accessdate=19 January 2012|first=Caitlin|last=McBride|work=Evening Herald}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*3 March \u2013 TV3 announces that ''[[Play TV (Ireland)|Play TV]]'''s contract has been terminated with immediate effect. In their statement they put the removal of the \"infomercial\" down purely to audience figures rather than the complaints received and upheld by the Broadcasting Authority of Ireland. They do not apologise for their conduct.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0305/breaking70.html | work=The Irish Times | title=TV3 cancels 'PlayTV' contract | date=3 March 2010|accessdate= 21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*19 April \u2013 The first part of ''[[Growing Up Gay]]'', a groundbreaking<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gcn.ie/Gay_Youth_on_RTE |title=Gay Youth on RT\u00c9 |work=Gay Community News |publisher=GCN |accessdate=25 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206134516/http://www.gcn.ie/Gay_Youth_on_RTE |archivedate= 6 February 2013 |df= }}</ref> two-part documentary series, is broadcast on [[RT\u00c9 One]], exploring the experiences of the first generation of lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) people growing up in an Ireland where it was legal to be themselves.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/programmes/growing_up_gay.html|title=Growing Up Gay|work=RT\u00c9 Television|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann| accessdate= 25 January 2012 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4282994&tpl=archnews&only=1|title=Crossing the Line Explores \u2018Growing Up Gay\u2019|work=Irish Film and Television Network|publisher=IFTN|date=15 April 2010|accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/telling-dad-im-gay-was-really-tough-but-hes-fine-now-says-teenage-star-of-new-rte-series-2136901.html|title=Telling dad I'm gay was really tough, but he's fine now, says teenage star of new RT\u00c9 series|first=Aoife|last=Anderson|work=Evening Herald|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=14 April 2010|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n*26 April \u2013  [[Ryanair]] chief executive [[Michael O'Leary (businessman)|Michael O'Leary]] is briefly left speechless on an edition of RT\u00c9 Two's comedy show ''[[Republic of Telly]]'' when presenter [[Jennifer Maguire]] asks him: \"What's it like being the biggest prick in Ireland?\"<ref name=onair_jibe_lost_for_words>{{cite news|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/jennifers-onair-jibe-leaves-oleary-lost-for-wordsbut-only-briefly-2152584.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217223553/http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/jennifers-onair-jibe-leaves-oleary-lost-for-wordsbut-only-briefly-2152584.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 February 2013 |title=Jennifer's on-air jibe leaves O'Leary lost for words |date=26 April 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010 |first=Caitlin |last=McBride |newspaper=Evening Herald |publisher=Independent News and Media }}</ref>\n*30 April \u2013 The broadcaster [[Gerry Ryan]] is [[Death of Gerry Ryan|found dead]] at his [[Leeson Street]] apartment in Dublin.<ref name=BBCRyan1May2010/>\n\n===May===\n*No events\n\n===June===\n*No events\n\n===July===\n*No events\n\n===August===\n*18 August \u2013 In an interview with ''[[The Irish Times]]'' to launch the network's autumn schedule, TV3 CEO David McRedmond admits that mistakes have been made regarding ''Play TV'' and that the programme was axed not just due to falling audience figures, but also due to the bad press and the regulators constant scrutiny of the show. He still refuses to apologise to viewers on behalf of TV3.<ref name=\"Hancock\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2010/0820/1224277227972.html|title=Channelling enthusiasm|last=Hancock|first=Ciaran|date=20 August 2010|accessdate=21 January 2012|work=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*9 September \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] begins airing ''[[Brain Box]]'', an interactive quiz already showing on [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] in Northern Ireland and [[STV (TV network)|STV]] in Scotland, but ceases transmission after a week. The programme continued on UTV and STV until February 2011.\n*19 September \u2013 Long running children's television block ''[[The Den (Ireland)|The Den]]'' gets axed after being shown on Irish television for over 24 years on [[RT\u00c9 Two]].\n*24 September \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] launches its [[iPhone application]].\n*28 September \u2013 Launch of [[RT\u00c9 Two]]'s block of programmes for children, [[TRT\u00c9]].\n\n===October===\n*29 October \u2013 Launch of [[Saorview]], the national [[free-to-air]] [[digital terrestrial television]] (DTT) service in the Republic of Ireland. The service operates on a trial basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2010/1030/1224282314323.html |title=Digital terrestrial television launched on trial basis |publisher=The Irish Times |date=30 October 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/rte-turns-on-republic-of-irelands-free-digital-tv-service-14991011.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804002420/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/rte-turns-on-republic-of-irelands-free-digital-tv-service-14991011.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 August 2012 |title=RT\u00c9 turns on Republic of Ireland's free digital TV service \u2013 Republic of Ireland, Local & National |work=Belfast Telegraph |publisher=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk |date=30 October 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2012 }}</ref>\n*29 October \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 News Now]] launches as a free-to-air channel on Saorview.\n\n===November===\n*November \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 News Now]]'s [[iPhone app]] wins Best Media app, Best Apple App and the Grand Prix awards at 'The Appy's 2010 with The Carphone Warehouse'.<ref>{{cite news|author=GrabOne daily deals |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/technology/appy-award-winners-announced-2409544.html |title=Appy award winners announced \u2013 Technology, Business |publisher=Independent.ie |date= 5 November 2010|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n*9 November \u2013 [[Noel Curran]] is appointed [[Director-General of RT\u00c9]].<ref name=\"Curran DG\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/1109/rte.html|title=Curran named as RT\u00c9's next Director General|date=9 November 2010|publisher=RT\u00c9|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*10 December \u2013 A Dublin inquest hears that [[cocaine]] was most likely the cause of the [[death of Gerry Ryan]] after traces of the drug were found in the broadcaster's body.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11969126 |title=Cocaine 'likely trigger' in RT\u00c9 star Gerry Ryan's death |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=10 December 2010 |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n*13 December \u2013 [[Michelle Massey]] wins the third series of ''[[The Apprentice (Irish TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/1214/1224285490350.html|title=Michelle secures \u20ac100,000 'Apprentice' dream job|date=14 December 2010|accessdate=14 December 2010|first=Genevieve|last=Carbery|work=The Irish Times|publisher=Irish Times Trust}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2010/1214/theapprentice.html |title=The Apprentice winner is crowned |date=14 December 2010 |accessdate=14 December 2010 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216030823/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2010/1214/theapprentice.html |archivedate=16 December 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Debuts==\n===RT\u00c9===\n*5 January \u2013 {{flagicon|UK}}/{{flagicon|CAN}} ''[[Waybuloo]]'' on [[RT\u00c9 Two]] (2009\u20132013)\n*30 January \u2013 ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'' on [[RT\u00c9 One]] (2010\u20132015)\n*15 March \u2013 {{flagicon|USA}} ''[[The Good Wife]]'' on [[RT\u00c9 Two]] (2009\u20132016)\n*10 April \u2013 ''[[Tonight with Craig Doyle]]'' on [[RT\u00c9 One]] (2010)\n*13 April \u2013 ''[[Fame: The Musical (Irish TV series)|Fame: The Musical]]'' on RT\u00c9 One (2010)\n*7 September \u2013 ''Do the Right Thing'' on RT\u00c9 Two (2010)\n*20 September \u2013 ''[[The Daily Show (Irish TV series)|The Daily Show]]'' on RT\u00c9 One (2010\u20132012)\n*3 October \u2013 ''[[Love/Hate (TV series)|Love/Hate]]'' on RT\u00c9 One (2010\u2013present)\n*25 October \u2013 ''[[Mission Beach USA (Irish TV series)|Mission Beach USA]]'' on RT\u00c9 Two (2010\u20132011)\n*11 November \u2013 ''[[Fade Street]]'' on RT\u00c9 Two (2010\u20132011)\n*Autumn \u2013 ''[[Four Live (Irish TV series)|Four Live]]'' on RT\u00c9 One (2010\u20132012)\n*Undated \u2013 {{flagicon|CAN}} ''[[Ruby Gloom]]'' on RT\u00c9 Two (2006\u20132008)\n\n===TV3===\n*2 August \u2013 ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n*15 October \u2013 ''[[Take Me Out (Irish game show)|Take Me Out]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n\n===TG4===\n*7 April \u2013 ''[[An Crisis]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n*Undated \u2013 {{flagicon|SPA}}/{{flagicon|IND}}/{{flagicon|POR}} ''[[Sandra the Fairytale Detective]]'' (2009\u20132010)\n\n==Changes of network affiliation==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Shows\n! Moved from\n! Moved to\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CAN}}/{{flagicon|FRA}} ''[[Atomic Betty]]''\n| [[RT\u00c92]]\n| [[TG4]]\n|}\n\n==Ongoing television programmes==\n===1960s===\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: Nine O'Clock]]'' (1961\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: Six One]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n*''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n\n===1970s===\n*''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' (1975\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News on Two]]'' (1978\u2013present)\n*''[[The Sunday Game]]'' (1979\u2013present)\n\n===1980s===\n*''[[Fair City]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: One O'Clock]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n\n===1990s===\n* ''[[Would You Believe (TV series)|Would You Believe]]'' (1990s\u2013present)\n*''[[Winning Streak]]'' (1990\u2013present)\n*''Prime Time'' (1992\u2013present)\n*''[[Nuacht RT\u00c9]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n*''[[Nuacht TG4]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n*''[[Ros na R\u00fan]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n*''[[Premier Soccer Saturday]]'' (1998\u20132013)\n*''[[TV3 News]]'' (1998\u2013present)\n*''[[The View (Irish TV series)|The View]]'' (1999\u20132011)\n*''[[Ireland AM]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n*''[[Telly Bingo]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n\n===2000s===\n*''[[Nationwide (Irish TV series)|Nationwide]]'' (2000\u2013present)\n*''[[TV3 News at 5.30]]'' (2001\u2013present)\n*''[[The Panel (Irish TV series)|The Panel]]'' (2003\u20132011)\n*''[[Against the Head]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[news2day]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[Other Voices (TV series)|Other Voices]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2005\u2013present)\n*''[[Anonymous (TV series)|Anonymous]]'' (2006\u20132011)\n*''[[One to One (TV series)|One to One]]'' (2006\u20132013)\n*''[[The Week in Politics]]'' (2006\u2013present)\n*''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'' (2007\u20132017)\n*''[[Xpos\u00e9]]'' (2007\u20132019)\n*''[[The Apprentice (Irish TV series)|The Apprentice]]'' (2008\u20132011)\n*''[[Monday Night Soccer]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[At Your Service (TV series)|At Your Service]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Championship Live]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' (2008\u20132016)\n*''[[Operation Transformation (TV series)|Operation Transformation]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Raw (TV series)|Raw]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[The Big Money Game]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[Brain Box]]'' (2009\u20132011)\n*''[[3e News]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n*''[[Dragons' Den (Ireland)|Dragons' Den]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n*''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*''[[Midweek (Irish TV series)|Midweek]]'' (2009\u20132014)\n*''[[The Morning Show with Sybil & Martin]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*''[[Republic of Telly]]'' (2009\u20132016)\n*''[[Traffic Blues]]'' (2009\u20132011)\n*''[[Two Tube]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n\n==Ending this year==\n*6 March \u2013 ''[[Play TV (Ireland)|Play TV]]'' (2009\u20132010)\n*12 March \u2013 ''[[Deal or No Deal (Ireland)|Deal or No Deal]]'' (2009\u20132010)\n*27 April \u2013 ''[[The Podge and Rodge Show]]'' (2006\u20132010)\n*20 May \u2013 ''[[Ryan Confidential]]'' (2004\u20132010)\n*29 May \u2013 ''[[Tonight with Craig Doyle]]'' (2010)\n*May \u2013 ''[[The Afternoon Show]]'' (2004\u20132010)\n*17 September \u2013 ''[[Championship Throw-In]]'' (2008\u20132010)\n*19 September \u2013 ''[[Dempsey's Den]]'' (1986\u20132010)\n\n==Deaths==\n*3 January \u2013 [[Dick Hill (broadcaster)|Dick Hill]], 71, former controller of programmes of [[RT\u00c9 Television]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/dick-hill--exrte-chief-dies-1997127.html|title=Dick Hill, ex-RT\u00c9 chief, dies |publisher=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|date=3 January 2010|accessdate=13 February 2012|first=Daniel|last=McConnell}}</ref>\n*30 April \u2013 [[Gerry Ryan]], 53, radio and television broadcaster<ref name=BBCRyan1May2010>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8654812.stm |title=Book of condolence for Gerry Ryan |publisher=BBC News |date=1 May 2010 |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n\n==2011==\n===January===\n*1 January \u2013 Long running British-Irish sitcom ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'' starring [[Brendan O'Carroll]] as the grumpy old woman begins on [[RT\u00c9 One]].\n*4 January \u2013 [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] announces details for the launch of ITV1+1, together with the possibility that both [[STV (TV network)|STV]] and UTV will launch their own [[Timeshift channel|timeshift]] services, STV +1 and UTV +1 in Scotland and Northern Ireland respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freeview.co.uk/Resolutions/About-Channels/Channel-changes/ITV1-1-to-launch-on-11-January-2011|title=ITV1 + 1 to launch on 11 January 2011|publisher=Freeview|accessdate=19 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109012433/http://www.freeview.co.uk/Resolutions/About-Channels/Channel-changes/ITV1-1-to-launch-on-11-January-2011|archivedate=9 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> UTV later confirms it will launch UTV+1 at 8pm on 11 January 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cable.co.uk/news/virgin-media-viewers-get-access-to-itv11-tonight-800335321/|title=Virgin Media viewers get access to ITV1+1 tonight|publisher=Cable.co.uk|date=11 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*21 February \u2013 British-Irish sitcom ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'' begins airing for the first time in the UK on the [[BBC]].\n\n===March===\n*No events\n\n===April===\n*No events\n\n===May===\n*May \u2013 ''[[Mission to Prey]]'', presented by [[Aoife Kavanagh]], is aired on [[RT\u00c9 One]], leading to the defamation of [[Fr. Kevin Reynolds]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/aoife-kavanagh-journalist-who-made-the-headlines-2942507.html|title=Aoife Kavanagh: Journalist who made the headlines|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=23 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15850770|title= Republic's government order probe into RT\u00c9 Fr Reynolds libel case|publisher= BBC|work= BBC News|date= 23 November 2011|accessdate= 3 January 2011}}</ref> Justice and Defence Minister [[Alan Shatter]] supports the programme at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/shatter-in-uturn-on-his-rash-support-for-prime-time-2946451.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804024520/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/shatter-in-uturn-on-his-rash-support-for-prime-time-2946451.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 August 2012 |title=Shatter in U-turn on his 'rash' support for Prime Time |first=Michael |last=Brennan |work=Irish Independent |accessdate=3 January 2012 |date=26 November 2011 }}</ref>\n*23 May \u2013 [[Helen O'Rahilly]], a former director of television at RT\u00c9 launches a scathing attack on its flagship programme, ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' amid criticism that standards on the programme have slipped since [[Ryan Tubridy]] took over as host in 2009. In an online blog, O'Rahilly says, \u201cIf I was back in charge of RT\u00c9, you wouldn\u2019t see this utter shite on Friday night\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-RT\u00c9 chief condemns Late Late as 'utter sh*te' |url=http://www.joe.ie/entertainment/what-to-watch/ex-rte-chief-condemns-late-late-as-utter-shte-0012440-1 |accessdate=25 January 2012 |work=JOE.ie |date=23 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302191910/http://www.joe.ie/uncategorized/ex-rte-chief-condemns-late-late-as-utter-shte/24316?shortlink=1 |archivedate=2 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n*25 May \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 News Now]] revamps its on-screen identity, giving viewers more detailed content.\n*26 May \u2013 [[Saorview]], the [[free to air]] [[digital television]] service is launched. The service has eight channels \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 One]], [[RT\u00c9 Two HD]], [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]], [[TG4]], [[RT\u00c9 News Now]], [[3e]], [[RT\u00c9jr]] and [[RT\u00c9 One + 1]] \u2013 and is available to 97% of households in Ireland. Saorview also carries a new digital [[RT\u00c9 Aertel]] service and [[RT\u00c9 Radio|RT\u00c9's radio services]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0526/saorview.html |title=Free-to-air digital service Saorview launched \u2013 RT\u00c9 News |publisher=Rte.ie |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*6 June \u2013 The [[BBC]] announces that the national variations of [[BBC One Northern Ireland]], [[BBC One Scotland]] and [[BBC One Wales]] will become available in [[High-definition television|high definition]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/aboutthebbc/reports/pdf/workplan_0611.pdf|title=BBC Executive priorities and summary workplan for 2011/12|page=11|format=PDF|work=[[BBC Online]]|date=6 June 2011|accessdate= 4 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*No events\n\n===August===\n*No events\n\n===September===\n*No events\n\n===October===\n*6 October \u2013 [[Director-General of the BBC|BBC Director General]] [[Mark Thompson (television executive)|Mark Thompson]] announces that [[BBC HD]] will close to be replaced by a high definition simulcast of BBC Two. This ''BBC Two HD'' will work much the same way as [[BBC One HD]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC set to cut 2,000 jobs by 2017|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15165926|accessdate= 4 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 October 2011}}</ref> This move allows the corporation to save \u00a32.1 million, used to count towards their budget deficit following the freezing of the license fee and the additional financial responsibility of addition services.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC cuts at a glance|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15186116|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 October 2011}}</ref>\n*8 October \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]]'s Video on Demand (VOD) is relaunched as [[3Player]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.marketing.ie/?p=7467 |title=TV3 unveils new player \u00ab Blog |publisher=Blog.marketing.ie |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref> It replaces the original TV3 Catch-Up service previously available at tv3.ie and through its iPhone/iPad app. The new service was revealed at a press call the previous day1. It is estimated by the TV3 Group that the service will be worth about \u20ac7.5 million by 2015. 3Player is in HTML5 format which makes it available on the majority of operating systems.\n\n===November===\n*15 November \u2013 The [[Houses of the Oireachtas Channel]] begins broadcasting on [[UPC Ireland]] channel 801, as part of a trial initiative for a period of six months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/2011/11/15/00003.asp|title=D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann Debate Vol. 746 No. 3 Unrevised|publisher=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=15 November 2011|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n*23 November \u2013 ''Prime Time Investigates'' is axed as [[Director-General of RT\u00c9]] [[Noel Curran]] describes the broadcasting of \"[[Mission to Prey]]\" as \"one of the gravest editorial mistakes ever made\" at RT\u00c9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2011/1123/1224308004000.html?via=mr|title=RT\u00c9 shelves investigative series and concedes 'grave mistake'|first=Paul|last=Cullen|author2=McGreevy, Ronan|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*19 December - Eugene Heary wins the fourth series of ''[[The Apprentice (Irish TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/apprentice-winner-reveals-his-secret-fears-for-mum-2968071.html|title= Apprentice winner reveals his secret fears for mum|date= 20 December 2011|work=The Evening Herald|publisher=Independent News and Media |accessdate=4 December 2012 }}</ref>\n*26 December \u2013 Launch of [[TV50]], a series of special events throughout 2012, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the launch of [[RT\u00c9 Television]], then known as Telef\u00eds \u00c9ireann, on 31 December 1961.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/1226/tv50.html|title=RT\u00c9 launches TV50|date=26 December 2011|accessdate=3 January 2012|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\n===TV3===\n*8 April \u2013 ''[[Head Chef (TV program)|Head Chef]]'' (2011)\n*3 June \u2013 ''[[The GAA Show]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n*6 June \u2013 ''[[Come Dine With Me (Ireland)|Come Dine with Me]]'' (2011\u20132013)\n*7 June \u2013 ''[[Paul Connolly Investigates]]'' (2011\u20132015)\n*11 December \u2013 ''[[Tallafornia]]'' (2011\u20132013)\n\n==Ongoing television programmes==\n\n===1960s===\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: Nine O'Clock]]'' (1961\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: Six One]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n*''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n\n===1970s===\n*''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' (1975\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News on Two]]'' (1978\u2013present)\n*''[[The Sunday Game]]'' (1979\u2013present)\n\n===1980s===\n*''[[Fair City]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n*''[[RT\u00c9 News: One O'Clock]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n\n===1990s===\n* ''[[Would You Believe (TV series)|Would You Believe]]'' (1990s\u2013present)\n*''[[Winning Streak]]'' (1990\u2013present)\n*''Prime Time'' (1992\u2013present)\n*''[[Nuacht RT\u00c9]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n*''[[Nuacht TG4]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n*''[[Ros na R\u00fan]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n*''[[Premier Soccer Saturday]]'' (1998\u20132013)\n*''[[TV3 News]]'' (1998\u2013present)\n*''[[Ireland AM]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n*''[[Telly Bingo]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n\n===2000s===\n*''[[Nationwide (Irish TV series)|Nationwide]]'' (2000\u2013present)\n*''[[TV3 News at 5.30]]'' (2001\u2013present)\n*''[[Against the Head]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[news2day]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[Other Voices (TV series)|Other Voices]]'' on RT\u00c9 Two (2003\u2013present)\n*''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2005\u2013present)\n*''[[One to One (TV series)|One to One]]'' (2006\u20132013)\n*''[[The Week in Politics]]'' (2006\u2013present)\n*''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'' (2007\u20132017)\n*''[[Xpos\u00e9]]'' (2007\u20132019)\n*''[[Monday Night Soccer]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[At Your Service (TV series)|At Your Service]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Championship Live]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' (2008\u20132016)\n*''[[Operation Transformation (TV series)|Operation Transformation]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n*''[[Raw (TV series)|Raw]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[The Big Money Game]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*''[[3e News]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n*''[[Dragons' Den (Ireland)|Dragons' Den]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n*''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*''[[Midweek (Irish TV series)|Midweek]]'' (2009\u20132014)\n*''[[The Morning Show with Sybil & Martin]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*''[[Republic of Telly]]'' (2009\u20132016)\n*''[[Two Tube]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n\n===2010s===\n*''[[Fade Street]]'' (2010\u20132011)\n*''[[Four Live (Irish TV series)|Four Live]]'' (2010\u20132012)\n*''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n*''[[Love/Hate (TV series)|Love/Hate]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n*''[[Take Me Out (Irish game show)|Take Me Out]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n*''[[The Daily Show (Irish TV series)|The Daily Show]]'' (2010\u20132012)\n*''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'' (2010\u20132015)\n\n==Ending this year==\n*28 January \u2013 ''[[Sesame Tree]]'' (2008\u20132011)\n*12 February \u2013 ''[[Brain Box]]'' (2009\u20132011)\n*11 April \u2013 ''[[Anonymous (TV series)|Anonymous]]'' (2006\u20132011)\n*27 May \u2013 ''[[Head Chef (TV program)|Head Chef]]'' (2011)\n*11 July - ''[[Traffic Blues]]'' (2009\u20132011)\n*August \u2013 ''[[Stars Go Racing]]'' (2011)\n*September \u2013 ''[[The Committee Room]]'' (2011)\n*19 November \u2013 ''[[The Apprentice (Irish TV series)|The Apprentice]]'' (2008\u20132011)\n*November - ''[[Mission Beach USA (Irish TV series)|Mission Beach USA]]'' (2010\u20132011)\n*13 December \u2013 ''[[The View (Irish TV series)|The View]]'' (1999\u20132011)\n\n==Deaths==\n* 14 March \u2013 [[Gerald Barry (Irish journalist)|Gerald Barry]], 63; broadcast and print journalist, following a long illness.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/national-news/tributes-paid-to-brilliant-journalist-gerald-barry-2579346.html \"Tributes paid to 'brilliant' journalist Gerald Barry\"]. ''Irish Independent''. 14 March 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2011/0315/1224292162357.html \"Tributes paid on death of Gerald Barry\"]. ''The Irish Times''. 14 March 2011.</ref>\n* 3 June \u2013 [[Peter Murphy (broadcaster)|Peter Murphy]], 88; television presenter ([[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]).<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0604/murphyp.html|title= Death of former RT\u00c9 presenter Peter Murphy|publisher= RT\u00c9 News|date= 4 June 2011|accessdate= 26 January 2012}}</ref>\n* 22 October \u2013 [[Cathal O'Shannon (TV presenter)|Cathal O'Shannon]], 83; journalist and television presenter.<ref>{{cite news|title=RT\u00c9 journalist Cathal O'Shannon dies aged 83 |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1022/oshannonc.html |accessdate=22 October 2011 |newspaper=RT\u00c9 News |date=22 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024081210/http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1022/oshannonc.html |archivedate=24 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2011 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2011}}\n\n[[Category:2011 in Irish television|2011 in Irish television]]\n\n==2012==\n* Ongoing \u2013 [[TV50]], a series of special events throughout 2012, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the launch of [[RT\u00c9 Television]], then known as Telef\u00eds \u00c9ireann, on 31 December 1961.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/1226/tv50.html|title=RT\u00c9 launches TV50|date=26 December 2011|accessdate=3 January 2012|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\n===January===\n*3 January \u2013 RT\u00c9 offended viewers by depicting a dog having its legs tied together and being tossed overboard into the sea off the coast of [[County Donegal]] as part of its ''TV50'' celebrations in a broadcast on 3 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.donegaldaily.com/2012/01/05/horror-as-rte-show-footage-of-dog-being-drowned-off-donegal-coast/|title=Horror as RT\u00c9 show footage of dog being drowned off Donegal coast|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=5 January 2012|work=Donegal Daily}}</ref>\n* 17 January \u2013 RT\u00c9 agrees to scrap its advertising \"share deal\" scheme from July following an investigation by the [[Competition Authority (Ireland)|Competition Authority]]. Rival broadcaster [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] had argued the practice, in which RT\u00c9 offered a discount to any advertiser which committed a percentage of its budget for television advertising to them was anti-competitive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0117/rte-business.html |title=RT\u00c9 to change ad discount system |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9.ie |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>\n* 30 January \u2013 Employees at RT\u00c9 vote to back the broadcaster's plans to cut its staff budget by \u20ac1m a year following a ballot of members of the Trade Union Group. The vote comes after a recommendation for them to do so from an internal industrial relations tribunal, and will see the money saved through reductions in holiday pay.<ref>{{cite news|first=Cormac |last=Murphy |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/rte-staff-agree-to-1m-cuts-for-pay-hikebut-stars-wont-be-hit-3003522.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120803062647/http://www.herald.ie/news/rte-staff-agree-to-1m-cuts-for-pay-hikebut-stars-wont-be-hit-3003522.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 August 2012 |title=RT\u00c9 staff agree to \u20ac1m cuts for pay hike...but stars won't be hit |publisher=Herald.ie |work=Evening Herald |date=30 January 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 6 February \u2013 [[Anglo Irish Bank]] agrees to allow Doughty-Hanson, the UK-based private equity firm that owns the loss-making [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] to take a repayment holiday on an \u20ac80m loan until the TV network is sold.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/anglo-to-park-private-equity-companys-80m-loan-in-tv3-deal-3011358.html|title= Anglo to 'park' private equity company's \u20ac80m loan in TV3 deal|publisher= |work= Irish Independent|first= Laura|last= Noonan|date= 7 February 2012|accessdate= 9 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 11 February \u2013 The live televised [[France national rugby union team|France]] versus [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]] match in the [[2012 Six Nations Championship]] is cancelled minutes prior to kick-off, prompting boos to ring out among disgruntled spectators inside a packed [[Stade de France]]. It is the first time such an event has happened since 1985.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0211/rugby.html |title=Ireland match called off over frozen pitch |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 News |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Chris |last=Whyatt |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/16969821 |title=Six Nations: France v Ireland match called off at last minute |publisher=BBC |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Evan |last=Fanning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/feb/11/six-nations-france-ireland-live |title=Six Nations 2012: France v Ireland \u2013 as it (very nearly) happened |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> [[Ryle Nugent]] tells viewers from his Irish commentary box, \"It is a dark day in the history of the Six Nations\".<ref name=rte_as_it_didnt_happen/> [[Tom McGurk]] in studio asks, \"What are we doing in a rugby stadium at 9pm on a Saturday night in February?\"<ref name=rte_as_it_didnt_happen>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/sixnations/2012/0211/live_sixnations_ireland_france.html |title=As it Didn't Happen: France v Ireland |first=Brendan |last=Cole |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |date=11 February 2012 |accessdate=11 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212232727/http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/sixnations/2012/0211/live_sixnations_ireland_france.html |archivedate=12 February 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 12 February \u2013 [[David Kelly (actor)|David Kelly]], the \"grand old man of Irish acting\", dies in [[Dublin]] aged 82 following a short illness.<ref name=DavidKellyTimes/>\n* 13 February \u2013 The first advert in the UK and Ireland aimed specifically at dogs is broadcast by [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]]. The 60-second commercial for the [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare|Bakers]] dog food brand features high-pitched sounds that cannot be heard by humans, and is a send up of the 1969 film ''[[The Italian Job]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=Collins |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/pets/9077741/First-advert-for-dogs-to-reach-British-TV-screens.html |title=First advert for dogs to reach British TV screens |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 February \u2013 ''In Bed with the Irish'', a documentary set among Irish couples under duvets, is broadcast by RT\u00c9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0213/realitybites.html|title=Ireland under duvet in documentary|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=13 February 2012|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 17 February \u2013 A 59-year-old RT\u00c9 props assistant, who injured himself after falling over a studio floor lamp while working on ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'', is awarded \u20ac18,500 in damages. The judge says he had worked accident free in RT\u00c9 for 38 years, that he had been working in poorly lit conditions in a cluttered studio when he was injured by one of RT\u00c9's props, and that he had been in pain since sustaining his injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0217/mcullena.html |title=\u20ac18,500 damages for Saturday Night Show injury |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302020620/http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0217/312505-mcullena/ |archivedate=2 March 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 5 March \u2013 TV3 airs the documentary ''[[Paul Connolly (journalist)|Ireland's Secret Sex Lives: Paul Connolly Investigates]]'' which looks at the subcultures of [[Swinging (sexual practice)|swingers]] and [[Dogging (sexual slang)|dogging]] in Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|first=Niamh |last=Horan |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/swinging-sex-clubs-attracting-societys-elites-3038998.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802205458/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/swinging-sex-clubs-attracting-societys-elites-3038998.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 2 August 2012 |title=Swinging sex clubs attracting society's elites |publisher=Independent.ie |newspaper=Sunday Independent |date=4 March 2012 |accessdate=4 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 7 March \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] upholds a complaint against RT\u00c9 made by [[Se\u00e1n Gallagher]] relating to the tweet that derailed [[2011 Irish presidential election|his presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0307/gallaghers.html|title=BAI upholds complaint against Frontline tweet|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 March \u2013 ''Pyjama Girls'', a documentary set among Dublin's public pyjama wearing community, is broadcast by RT\u00c9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0313/girlsp.html|title=Pyjama Girls on RT\u00c9 One tonight|work=RT\u00c9 Ten|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 March \u2013 TV3 defends its reality programme ''[[Tallafornia]]'' after it was condemned by Senator [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] as a \"drink-sodden programme\" which encourages its participants to \"behave licentiously and compete to bring people home to bed them\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tallafornia-exploiting-its-stars-says-norris-3049065.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120803043625/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tallafornia-exploiting-its-stars-says-norris-3049065.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 3 August 2012 |title='Tallafornia' exploiting its stars, says Norris |publisher=Independent.ie |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=14 March 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 17 March \u2013 Debut of RT\u00c9's #HowToBeIrish, a programme made entirely of clips sent in by viewers explaining what being Irish means to them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0217/howtobeirish.html |title=How Irish are you? |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 March \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] Director of Programming Ben Frow calls for resignations at RT\u00c9 in the wake of the Father [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Kevin Reynolds]] scandal to prevent the libel case causing further damage to the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/heads-should-roll-over-priest-libel-tv3-chief-3059358.html |title=Heads should roll over priest libel |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=23 March 2012 |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 25 March \u2013 As the 100th anniversary of the [[sinking of the RMS Titanic]] approaches TV3 begins airing [[Julian Fellowes]]' epic [[Titanic (2012 miniseries)|retelling of the disaster]]. TV3 has itself invested \u20ac300m in the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tv3-hoping-their-titanic-stays-afloat-3060164.html |title=TV3 hoping their 'Titanic' stays afloat |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 27 March \u2013  RT\u00c9 broadcasts a tribute to deceased comedian [[Hal Roach (comedian)|Hal Roach]] in one of its [[graveyard slot]]s, a repeat airing of a programme from the ''That's Entertainment'' series first broadcast in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0327/roachh.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120908090913/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0327/roachh.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 8 September 2012 |title=RT\u00c9 tribute to Hal Roach tonight |date=27 March 2012 |accessdate=27 March 2012 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann |df= }}</ref>\n* 29 March \u2013 [[Director-General of RT\u00c9|RT\u00c9 Director-General]] [[Noel Curran]] announces \u20ac25m of budget cuts at the broadcaster, including pay reductions, staff redundancies and the closure of [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]'s London office.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rte-staff-stunned-as-second-tier-stars-take-a-30-pc-pay-cut-3066452.html |title=RT\u00c9 staff stunned as 'second tier' stars take a 30 pc pay cut |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=30 March 2012 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n* 31 March \u2013 Former [[broadcast journalism|broadcast journalist]] [[Mike Nesbitt]] is [[2012 Ulster Unionist Party leadership election|elected]] leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-17572015|title= Mike Nesbitt is new Ulster Unionist leader|publisher= BBC|work= BBC News|date= 31 March 2012|accessdate= 31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 3 April \u2013 Following last year's defamation of [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Father Kevin Reynolds]] by [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]], the state-controlled broadcaster's head of current affairs Ed Mulhall retires, Ken O'Shea resigns from ''Prime Time'' and its stablemate, ''Prime Time Investigates'' is axed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/rte-axes-prime-time-following-watchdog-report-3069870.html |title=Prime Time Investigates axed following watchdog report |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=3 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0403/breaking38.html?via=rel |title=RT\u00c9's head of news steps down |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=Irish Times Trust |date=3 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 6 April \u2013 RT\u00c9 breaks with the [[Good Friday]] tradition of not sounding the [[Angelus]] bells by broadcasting them as usual on television. They are also heard for the first time on [[Holy Saturday]], a move contrary to [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] practice which is for them to be silenced to mark the period between the [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]] and [[Resurrection of Jesus]]. RT\u00c9 argues that the daily prayer belongs to everyone rather than a single faith.<ref>{{cite news|first=Justine |last=McCarthy |first2=Harry |last2=Leech |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1012435.ece |title=Toll and trouble as RTE keeps Angelus on TV |publisher=News UK |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=8 April 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2015 |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Damien |last=Corless |url=http://www.independent.ie/life/for-whom-the-bell-tolls-31114607.html |title=For whom the bell tolls |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=4 April 2015 |accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 10 April \u2013  RT\u00c9 says it is disappointed after details of a report from the [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] into the ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time Investigates]]'' programme ''[[Mission to Prey]]'' were leaked. The report shows the BAI will find the documentary was unfair and breached the privacy of [[Kevin Reynolds (priest)|Fr Kevin Reynolds]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17665860 |work=BBC News |title=Leaked priest defamation report 'finds RT\u00c9 unfair' |publisher=BBC |date=10 April 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The BAI has launched an investigation into how the leak occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/watchdog-probes-rte-report-leak-16142996.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720182112/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/watchdog-probes-rte-report-leak-16142996.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 July 2012 |title=Watchdog probes RT\u00c9 report leak |publisher= |newspaper=Belfast Telegraph |date=10 April 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2012 }}</ref>\n* 17 April \u2013 An edition of the recently axed ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time Investigates]]'' about the illegal cigarette trade is among three RT\u00c9 documentaries to win awards at the 2012 New York Festivals International Television and Film Awards.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eva |last=Hall |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4284818&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=RT\u00c9 Scoops Three International Awards For Documentary |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=19 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 17 April \u2013 TV3 apologises for disparaging remarks that were made about [[Limerick]] in a recent edition of its series ''[[Come Dine with Me (Ireland)|Come Dine with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheridan |first=Anne |url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/news/local/tv3-apologises-for-remarks-about-limerick-on-come-dine-with-me-1-3747188 |title=TV3 apologises for remarks about Limerick on 'Come Dine With Me' |newspaper=Limerick Leader |publisher= |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 18 April \u2013 Journalists at RT\u00c9 condemn the broadcaster's proposed closure of its London office as a \u201cbetrayal of RT\u00c9's public service remit\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ronan |last=McGreevy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0418/breaking56.html |title=RT\u00c9 journalists condemn closure |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 18 April \u2013 Plans are announced for TV3 to double the size of its headquarters building at Westgate Business Park, Ballymount, Dublin, after the broadcaster signed a new lease with its landlord, Irish Property Unite Trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/0418/1224314872124.html |title=TV3 doubles down on HQ lease |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 April \u2013 The [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] urges the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] to support calls for RT\u00c9 to reverse its decision to close its London office, which is scheduled to shut following [[2012 Summer Olympics|this year's Olympic games]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0424/1224315104222.html |title=Support sought to halt RT\u00c9 closure |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 April \u2013 Pat Hayes, the [[Mayor of Waterford]] expresses his dismay over suggestions RT\u00c9 might close its studio in the city and cover the southeast region from Dublin. Waterford is one of four regional studios facing the axe because of budget cuts by the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0424/1224315104311.html |title=Mayor urges RT\u00c9 not to downgrade coverage of the southeast region |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 25 April \u2013 RT\u00c9 defends its broadcasting of ''Masterpiece: Ireland's Favourite Painting'' after presenter [[Michael Murphy (journalist)|Mike Murphy]] wrote to ''[[The Irish Times]]'' criticising the show's length and timeslot (it aired for an hour from 10.15pm on 17 April, which Murphy described as: \u201cCromwellian edict of arts programming being banished into the Connacht of broadcasting, ie, at, or past most people\u2019s bedtime\u201d).<ref>{{cite news|first=Ronan |last=McGreevy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0425/breaking49.html |title=Murphy criticises RT\u00c9 arts coverage |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=25 April 2012 |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n* 29 April \u2013 [[Pat Byrne (singer)|Pat Byrne]] wins the [[The Voice of Ireland (series 1)|first series]] of ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/teacher-pat-byrne-chalks-up-voice-victory-but-bressie-a-winner-too-26848366.html |title=Teacher Pat Byrne chalks up 'Voice' victory, but Bressie a winner too |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=30 April 2012 |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 2 May \u2013 TV3 and RT\u00c9 sign a deal to retain the rights to broadcast [[UEFA Champions League]] football until at least 2015. TV3 is to continue to air Tuesday night matches while RT\u00c9 is to broadcast games on Wednesday nights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4284884&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 & RT\u00c9 To Retain Champions League Football Rights |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher= |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2 May \u2013 RT\u00c9 reaches an agreement with [[Equity (trade union)|Equity]] and the Irish Playwrights and Screenwriters' Guild to allow them to make their soap '\u2018[[Fair City]]'\u2019 available on [[RT\u00c9 Player]] and [[RT\u00c9 One + 1]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/finance/finance_news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4284885&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=\u2018Fair City\u