k=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=23 July 2012 |accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 July \u2013 RT\u00c9 subsidiary company [[2RN (RT\u00c9 Networks)|RT\u00c9 Transmission Network Ltd]] (RT\u00c9 NL) is to be rebranded, and located away from the Donnybrook campus as part of an ongoing restructuring at the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.techcentral.ie/19428/rte-announces-repositioning-of-network-subsidiary |title=RT\u00c9 announces repositioning of network subsidiary |publisher=Tech Central |date=24 July 2012 |accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 18 August \u2013 RT\u00c9 begins its Ireland on Screen season, teaming up with the [[Irish Film Board]] to showcase a number of home-produced films. The season begins with [[Jim Sheridan]]'s ''[[The Boxer (1997 film)|The Boxer]]'' on RT\u00c9 One, and also includes network TV premieres of ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'', ''[[Happy Ever Afters]]'' and ''[[The Runway (film)|The Runway]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285252&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Ireland on Screen Film Season To Begin on RT\u00c9 |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher=Iftn.ie |date=17 August 2012 |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>\n* 18 August \u2013 [[Littlewoods|Littlewoods Ireland]] takes over Ireland's sponsorship of ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'' as the programme returns to TV3 for a [[The X Factor (UK series 9)|ninth season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/0816/1224322254968.html |title=X marks the spot for new sponsor |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 August \u2013 TV3 unveils its Autumn Schedule, which includes ''Deception'', the broadcaster's first drama set on a [[Celtic Tiger]] era housing estate, and its first sitcom, ''On the Couch'' about three couples receiving counselling.<ref>{{cite news|first= Ronan|last=McGreevy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0823/breaking27.html |title=TV3 unveils first drama series |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=23 August 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref>\n* 28 August \u2013 [[UTV Media]] \u2013 which owns the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] franchise for Northern Ireland and the UK-based sports-orientated radio station [[talkSPORT]] \u2013 reports a summer of mixed fortunes in terms of advertising revenue. Coverage of the [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 European Cup]] proved lucrative for talkSPORT, but television advertising was hit by the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark |last=Sweney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/aug/28/utv-media-mixed-results-summer-sport?newsfeed=true |title=UTV Media gets mixed results from summer of sporting events |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref>\n* 29 August \u2013 The main evening edition of [[BBC Northern Ireland]]'s regional news programme ''[[BBC Newsline|Newsline]]'' is relaunched with a fresh look, including a new studio and a single anchor replacing the two-presenter format.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/northern-ireland/and-here-is-the-news-brought-to-you-by-a-bbc-sports-presenter-16202911.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130419232659/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/northern-ireland/and-here-is-the-news-brought-to-you-by-a-bbc-sports-presenter-16202911.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 April 2013 |first=Maureen |last=Coleman |title=And here is the news... brought to you by a BBC sports presenter |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Belfast Telegraph |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* 3 September \u2013 The [[Dallas (2012 TV series)|updated version]] of the U.S. soap opera [[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]] makes its Irish television debut on TV3.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/0906/1224323651916.html |title=TV3 strikes oil with 'Dallas' |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=6 September 2012 |accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref>\n* 4 September \u2013 [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour]]\u2019s Disability Spokeswoman Senator [[Mary Moran (politician)|Mary Moran]] criticises RT\u00c9\u2019S decision not to show live coverage of the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]], describing it as \"bitterly disappointing\" and saying that she will write to the Director-General on the issue.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ronan |last=McGreevy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0904/1224323575435.html |title=Senator criticises RT\u00c9 decision not to broadcast Games live on TV |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref>\n* 10 September \u2013 TV3's breakfast television strand ''[[Ireland AM]]'' is relaunched with a \"newsier\" format amid speculation that RT\u00c9 is to launch its own breakfast television service later in the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tv3s-ireland-am-braces-for-breakfast-tv-battle-with-rte-3225836.html |title=TV3's Ireland AM braces for Breakfast TV battle with RT\u00c9 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 September \u2013 TV3 announced the name of its new HD studio after signing a deal with [[Sony International]] to equip it with Sony technology. It will be called the Sony HD Studio.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eva |last=Hall |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285346&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3's New Sony HD Studio Could Create 'Hundreds of Jobs' |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher=Iftn.ie |date=13 September 2012 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* 20 September \u2013 TG4's reality series ''Feirm Factor'' \u2013 in which 10 farmers compete in a series of agricultural tasks to become the nation's best farmer \u2013 is optioned to six European countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285375&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Irish TV Format 'Feirm Factor' Goes Global |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=20 September 2012 |accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* 2 October \u2013 TG4 launches its first high-definition channel titled TG4 HD. The service is launched on [[UPC Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://businessetc.thejournal.ie/rte-news-now-tg4-upc-619405-Oct2012/ |title=RT\u00c9 News Now and TG4 HD now available on UPC |publisher=The Journal |date=2 October 2012 |accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> TG4 also update their on-air and off-air identity.\n* 10 October \u2013 The first stage of the [[Digital switchover dates in the United Kingdom|digital switchover]] occurs in the [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] region.\n* 16 October \u2013 TV3 announce that their Director of Programming [[Ben Frow]] will leave the TV3 Group at the end of the year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cummins |first=Steve |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285486&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Ben Frow To Leave TV3 After Five Years |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=16 October 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 22 October \u2013 RT\u00c9 Director of News and Current Affairs Kevin Bakhurst rules out a breakfast television programme for the broadcaster on cost grounds.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Lavery |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/breakfast-tv-is-not-on-the-menu-at-rte-news-chief-3268236.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217191216/http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/breakfast-tv-is-not-on-the-menu-at-rte-news-chief-3268236.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 February 2013 |title=Breakfast TV is not on the menu at RT\u00c9 \u2013 news chief |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Evening Herald |date=22 October 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2012 }}</ref>\n* 22 October \u2013 TV3 confirms plans to rebrand their [[TV3 News at 5.30|5.30 news bulletin]] as \"The 5.30\". The programme moves to a specially designed new virtual set at the station's Ballymount headquarters.<ref>{{cite news|first=Brian |last=O'Reilly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/tv3-announces-revamp-to-news-at-530-as-channel-goes-high-tech-3269839.html |title=TV3 announces revamp to \u2018News at 5.30\u2019 as channel goes high tech |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=22 October 2012 |accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 October \u2013 Northern Ireland completes its digital switchover at 11.30pm when the analogue signal is switched off.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-20048154 |work=BBC News |title=Northern Ireland completes UK digital TV switchover |publisher=BBC |date=23 October 2012 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n* 24 October \u2013 The analogue television service in the Irish Republic is [[Digital television transition#Republic of Ireland|switched off]] at 10.00am, and is replaced by a second multiplex for [[Saorview]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/1024/digital-switchover-television.html |title=Analogue TV signal replaced by digital |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=24 October 2012 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Aideen |last=Sheehan |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/analogue-tv-switched-off-amid-lastminute-rush-3270961.html |title=Analogue TV switched off amid last-minute rush |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=24 October 2012 |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref> Saorview is available to 98% of Ireland, but there are problems receiving it in some mountainous areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/av/2012/1024/media-3421831.html# |work=Six One News |title=Digital switchover creates problems in southwest Kerry |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=24 October 2012 |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n* 25 October \u2013 TV3 makes its content available on [[Roku]], an online subscription service that streams content in the United States, Canada and Britain.<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Slattery |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/1025/1224325669984.html |title=Atlantic crossing for stars of TV3 |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=25 October 2012 |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 3 November \u2013 TG4 airs the [[Match for Michaela]], a [[Gaelic Football]] match between [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]] and [[Ulster GAA|Ulster]] from Belfast's [[Casement Park]]. The game is in aide of the Michaela Foundation, established in memory of [[Murder of Michaela McAreavey|Michaela McAreavey]], who was murdered while on her honeymoon in Mauritius in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ian |last=O'Riordan |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2012/1102/1224326034304.html |title=Match for Michaela helps Hartes and McAreaveys focus on positives |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=2 November 2012 |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ciar\u00e1n |last=Hanna |url=http://insideireland.ie/2012/11/04/18000-watch-ulster-beat-donegal-in-match-for-michaela-in-belfast-81210/ |title=Over 18,000 watch Ulster beat Donegal in Match for Michaela in Belfast |work=Inside Ireland |publisher= |date=4 November 2012 |accessdate=7 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116070246/http://insideireland.ie/2012/11/04/18000-watch-ulster-beat-donegal-in-match-for-michaela-in-belfast-81210/ |archivedate=16 January 2013 }}</ref>\n* 5 November \u2013 TV3 admits that it failed to properly notify viewers of its motoring show, ''The Driving Seat'' that car makers had been asked to pay up to \u20ac5,000 to have their products featured.<ref>{{cite news|first=Connor |last=Pope |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/1105/1224326141043.html |title=TV3 failed to notify viewers of product placement |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n* 9 November \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] upholds four viewer complaints against TV3's ''Psychic Readings Live''. They include two involving predictions of pregnancy and one case in which a woman was told her flat would burn down.<ref>{{cite news|first=Connor |last=Pope |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/1109/breaking48.html |title=TV3's psychics breach code again |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n* 13 November \u2013 Ben Frow, the outgoing Director of Content at TV3, is hired by UK commercial broadcaster [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] as their Director of Programmes, and will take up the position from February 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark |last=Sweney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/13/channel-5-ben-frow |title=Channel 5 appoints Ben Frow as director of programmes |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 November 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 15 November \u2013 BAI begins its quintennial funding review of public service broadcasting in Ireland, expecting to complete the process in March 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Slattery |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/1115/1224326602258.html |title=RT\u00c9 rivals pitch in over public service broadcasting study |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=15 November 2012 |accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n* 22 November \u2013 BAI calls on RT\u00c9 to publish the findings of its internal report on the ''Frontline'' presidential debate programme broadcast in October 2011. The watchdog believes the editorial failings of the programme are more significant than have been publicly identified.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Patsy |last=McGarry |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/1122/breaking44.html |title=RT\u00c9's Frontline criticised for failings |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=22 November 2012 |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 November \u2013 In a letter to BAI chairman Bob Jones and the broadcaster RT\u00c9, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] claims that the election of [[Michael D. Higgins]] as [[President of Ireland|President]] has been \"undermined\" by the \"failure\" of RT\u00c9 to \"adhere to proper standards\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Jody |last=Corcoran |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/ff-letter-higgins-election-is-undermined-by-rte-3304999.html |title=FF letter: Higgins election is 'undermined' by RT\u00c9 |newspaper=Sunday Independent |publisher=Independent News and Media |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n* 23 November \u2013 ''The Irish Times'' reports that TV3 is considering the introduction of a [[paywall]] for its [[3Player]] service following [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s decision to begin charging for some of its online content.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/1123/1224327007115.html |title=Coming soon TV3 signals pay-per-view experiment for online content |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=23 November 2012 |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 2 December \u2013 It is reported that the Catholic Communications Office has made an official complaint to RT\u00c9 over a sketch by impersonator [[Mario Rosenstock]] that appeared to mock [[Holy Communion]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jerome |last=Reilly |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/church-demands-rte-apology-over-sketch-by-comic-3312124.html |title=Church demands RT\u00c9 apology over sketch by comic |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Sunday Independent |date=2 December 2012 |accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref>\n* 3 December \u2013 ''Psychic Readings Live'' airs for the last time after TV3 cancelled the programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://businessetc.thejournal.ie/tv3s-psychics-live-show-cancelled-700645-Dec2012/ |title=TV3 axes Psychics Readings Live show |publisher=Distilled Media |work=Thejournal.ie |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 5 December \u2013 [[Finance Minister (Ireland)|Finance Minister]] [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]] extends TV and film tax relief until 2020, and signals it will be restructured to take the form of a tax credit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/uk-government-confirms-25-tv-tax-credit-6m-pool-for-training-ireland-extends-relief-to-2020/5049694.article |title=UK government confirms 25% TV tax credit, \u00a36m pool for training; Ireland extends relief to 2020  |publisher=|work=Screen Daily |date=5 December 2012 |accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 7 December \u2013 It is reported RT\u00c9 is to provide staff training on what subjects are appropriate for discussion on social media sites such as Twitter following several controversies involving tweets from presenters and other employees of the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|first=Claire |last=Murphy |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/the-tweet-hits-the-fan-rte-3318652.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217205153/http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/the-tweet-hits-the-fan-rte-3318652.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 February 2013 |title=The tweet hits the fan @RTE |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Evening Herald |date=7 December 2012 |accessdate=8 December 2012 }}</ref>\n*7 December \u2013 TG4 launches an on demand service on the pay-per-view service [[UPC Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Eva |last=Hall |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285635&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TG4 Content Now Available on Demand on UPC |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher= |date=7 December 2012 |accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 11 December \u2013 The ''[[Irish Examiner]]'' reports that the largest and most expensive television to go on sale in Ireland has gone on sale at the [[Harvey Norman]] stores in [[Carrickmines]], [[County Dublin]]. The LG 84in Ultra HD TV has a reach longer than the arm span of most adults, and is on sale for \u20ac26,999.<ref>{{cite news|first=Se\u00e1n |last=McC\u00e1rthaigh |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/size-matters-27k-tv-is-biggest-ever-sold-in-ireland-216620.html |title=Size matters: \u20ac27k TV is biggest ever sold in Ireland |publisher= Thomas Crosbie Holdings|newspaper=Irish Examiner |date=11 December 2012 |accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 21 December \u2013 A record \u20ac118 million of foreign direct investment went into Irish film and television productions in 2012, it is reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2012/1221/1224328081384.html |title=Irish film and television industry enjoys 'remarkable year' as investment soars |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=21 December 2012 |accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n\n==Deaths==\n* 10 January \u2014 [[Mary Raftery]], 54, journalist (''[[States of Fear]]'', \"[[Cardinal Secrets]]\"), ovarian cancer<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2012/0110/breaking10.html|title=Journalist Mary Raftery dies|date=10 January 2012|accessdate=10 January 2012|first=Patsy|last=McGarry|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0110/rafterym.html |title=Journalist Mary Raftery dies aged 54 |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=10 January 2012 |work=RT\u00c9 News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415063804/http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0110/rafterym.html |archivedate=15 April 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n* 6 February \u2014 [[Noel Kelehan]], 76, musician, former conductor of the [[RT\u00c9 Concert Orchestra]] and former musical director of [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0207/1224311401117.html|title= RT\u00c9 conductor Noel Kelehan dies|publisher= |work= The Irish Times|first= Eoin|last= Burke-Kennedy|date= 6 February 2012|accessdate= 9 February 2012}}</ref>\n*12 February \u2014 [[David Kelly (actor)|David Kelly]], 82, film and television actor<ref name=DavidKellyTimes>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0213/1224311684377.html |title=Grand old man of Irish acting dies, aged 82 |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher= |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n*24 August \u2014 [[Maureen Toal]], 82, actress best known for her role as Teasy McDaid in ''[[Glenroe]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/0825/1224322964711.html|title='Greatest'actor Maureen Toal dies|newspaper=The Irish Times|publisher= The Irish Times Trust|first= Fiona|last= Gartland|date=25 August 2012|accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2012 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2012}}\n\n[[Category:2012 in Irish television|2012 in Irish television]]\n\n==2013==\n\n===January===\n*6 January \u2013 It is reported that [[Se\u00e1n Gallagher]], a former candidate in the [[2011 Irish presidential election]] is launching legal proceedings against [[RT\u00c9]] over an incident in its ''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|Frontline]]'' Presidential Debate in which a tweet was wrongly attributed to the official Twitter account of the [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]'s [[Martin McGuinness]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0106/gallagher-takes-legal-action-over-frontline-debate.html |title=Gallagher takes legal action over Frontline debate|work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=6 January 2012 |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*7 January \u2013 Debut of [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]]'s first self-produced drama, ''[[Deception (Irish TV series)|Deception]]'', set on a post-[[Celtic Tiger]] housing estate in [[Galway]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/57581/galway-based-drama-series-deception-to-premiere-on-tv3-next-week- |title=Galway based drama series Deception to premiere on TV3 next week |publisher= |newspaper=Galway Advertiser |date=3 January 2013 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Butler |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/our-first-drama-as-good-as-lovehate-tv3-3341620.html |title=Our first drama as good as 'Love/Hate' |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=3 January 2013 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n*30 January \u2013 Former [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] Director of Programmes Jeff Ford has been hired by [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] to become their new Director of Content, a position he will take up in February.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=O'Carroll |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/jan/30/jeff-ford-tv3-head-content |title=Jeff Ford to become head of content at TV3 |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=30 January 2013 |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n*31 January \u2013 Figures published by TAM Ireland/Nielsen indicate viewers in Ireland watched an average of 3.35 hours of television per day (25 hours a week) in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Slattery |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2013/0131/1224329469727.html |title=Viewers loyal to TV as they watch 25 hours a week |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*1 February \u2013 [[Pat Kenny]], most recently presenter of ''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'', returns to host an edition of ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' after the death earlier in the week of regular host [[Ryan Tubridy]]'s father.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Sweeney |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/blast-from-the-past-pat-kenny-to-host-late-late-show-as-ryan-tubridy-mourns-passing-of-father-3371005.html |title=Blast from the past \u2013 Pat Kenny to host 'Late Late Show' as Ryan Tubridy mourns passing of father |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2013/0131/1224329469912.html |title=Tubridy off air following death of his father |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>\n*5 February \u2013 Launch of Irish Horse TV, Ireland's first TV channel dedicated to horse racing and other equine sports.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://horsetalk.co.nz/2013/01/15/ireland-gets-new-equine-tv-channel/#.UPlHef1RuDE|title= Ireland gets new equine TV channel|publisher= |work= Horsetalk|date= 15 January 2013|accessdate= 18 January 2013}}</ref>\n*7 February \u2013 The [[Irish Film and Television Network]] website reports that pre-production has begun on ''An Bronntanas'', a five-part Irish language thriller set in [[Conamara]] that will air on [[TG4]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285772&tpl=archnews&force=1 |first=Eva |last=Hall |title=TG4 Series 'An Bronntanas' Enters Pre-Production |publisher=The Irish Film & Television Network |work= |date=7 February 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n*25 February \u2013 Telecommunications giant [[BT Group|BT]], which bought the rights to some [[Premier League]] matches in 2012 expands its investment in sports broadcasting with the purchase of [[ESPN]]'s channels in Britain and Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Deans |first2=Owen |last2=Gibson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/feb/25/espn-bt-vision |title=BT buys ESPN'S UK and Ireland TV channels |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=25 February 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*4 March \u2013 Online retailer [[Viking Direct]] says it cannot fulfil orders placed for a 51-inch 3D television that was incorrectly priced at \u20ac6.49 instead of \u20ac649. Thousands of orders were placed during the two days the offer was available, but customers will not receive their purchase, nor will they get an automatic refund.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Kennedy |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/mispriced-television-orders-cancelled-1.1317336 |title=Mispriced television orders cancelled |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=5 March 2013 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n*7 March \u2013 [[Minister for Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]] [[Pat Rabbitte]] officially opens TV3's new \u20ac5m Sony HD production centre at [[Ballymount]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin |last=Cronin |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4285858&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 Sony HD Studios launched by Minister for Communications |publisher=The Irish Film & Television Network |date=8 March 2013 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n*14 March \u2013 The [[Lowry Tapes]], containing a telephone conversation between corrupt politician [[Michael Lowry]] and land agent Kevin Phelan, are broadcast in full on ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jody|last=Corcoran|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/coalition-tension-over-lowry-tapes-29120885.html|title=Coalition tension over Lowry tapes|newspaper=Sunday Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=10 March 2013|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/michael-lowry-kevin-phelan-conversation-833051-Mar2013/|title=Garda\u00ed examining Lowry tape as conversation is aired on national TV: Independent TD Michael Lowry can be heard making reference to a \u00a3250,000 payment which he said he never declared|work=TheJournal.ie|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*11 April \u2013 TV3 criticises new regulations that ban radio and television journalists from expressing an on-air opinion on news and current affairs issues as \"a draconian extension of the State's control over media\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Se\u00e1n |last=McC\u00e1rthaigh |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/tv3-slams-new-code-as-draconian-227996.html |title=TV3 slams new code as 'draconian' |publisher= Landmark Media Investments|newspaper=Irish Examiner |date=11 April 2013 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n*28 April \u2013 [[Keith Hanley]] wins the [[The Voice of Ireland (series 2)|second series]] of ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0429/444967-thevoice/ |title=Keith Hanley wins The Voice of Ireland |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=29 April 2013 |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*21 May \u2013 Justice Minister [[Alan Shatter]] apologises to [[Independent (politician)|independent]] deputy [[Mick Wallace]] in the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] after he divulged that Wallace had been excused from receiving [[Penalty points in Ireland|penalty points]] for using a [[mobile phone]] while driving during a debate about people escaping penalty points on an edition of RT\u00c9's ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time]]''. Shatter had previously admitted receiving his information from [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] Commissioner [[Martin Callinan]] but claimed he was not \"in the business of collecting secret files on politicians\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Juno|last=McEnroe|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/shatter-garda-chief-told-me-about-wallace-231998.html|title=Shatter: Garda chief told me about Wallace|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=22 May 2013|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sligotoday.ie/printable.php?id=25882 |title=TD to lodge official complaint over justice minister's remarks |publisher=Sligo Today |date=20 May 2013 |accessdate=30 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911105321/http://sligotoday.ie/printable.php?id=25882 |archive-date=11 September 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*30 May \u2013 Three international deals are announced by Dublin-based Network Ireland Television that will see 50 Irish-made short films aired on television channels in the Americas, Europe and Middle East.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin |last=Cronin |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286135&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Network Ireland Television, Film & TV Distributors, Secure 3 International Deals to Sell 50 Irish Shorts Abroad |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher=Iftn.ie |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*3 June \u2013 [[AerTV]], an Irish-owned online television service launched 18 months previously reports a 130% year-on-year increase in viewership for the first quarter of 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Percival |first=Geoff |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/business/online-tv-service-sees-viewership-rise-130-233191.html |title=Online TV service sees viewership rise 130% |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |newspaper=Irish Examiner |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n*5 June \u2013 Food manufacturers criticise [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] plans to introduce new regulations banning television and radio advertising of foods with high fat, salt, and sugar content during children's programmes.<ref>{{cite news|first=Se\u00e1n |last=McC\u00e1rthaigh |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/industry-attacks-food-ads-ban-for-childrens-tv-233262.html |title=Industry attacks food ads ban for children's TV |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |newspaper=Irish Examiner |date=5 June 2013 |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n*25 June \u2013 [[Setanta Sports]] signs a deal to make their BT Sport channels and ESPN available in the Irish Republic from 1 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.herald.ie/news/setanta-to-add-bt-29371659.html |title=Setanta to add BT |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Evening Herald |date=25 June 2013 |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*11 July \u2013 [[Fine Gael]] Teachta D\u00e1la [[Tom Barry (politician)|Tom Barry]], who had been drinking in the D\u00e1il bar, provokes international headlines after pulling party colleague [[\u00c1ine Collins]] onto his lap on live television during a late-night D\u00e1il debate. Fine Gael later describe the incident was \"silly\" and \"horseplay\". However, the event sparks a national discussion about the treatment of women by men in Irish politics.<ref>{{cite news|first=Emer|last=O'Toole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/12/ireland-abortion-debate-tom-barry-aine-collins|title=The Ireland abortion debate, summed up in one disrespectful gesture|newspaper=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Emer|last=O'Toole|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/10174051/Irish-politician-Tom-Barry-grabs-female-colleague-during-abortion-debate.html|title=The moment a politician grabbed his female colleague and pulled her onto his lap \u2013 during an abortion debate|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n*5 August \u2013 In a ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' interview, journalist and businessman [[Vincent Browne]] criticises programmes about [[Irish Travellers|Travellers]] broadcast by his employer [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]], saying, \"To say it was embarrassing doesn't begin to describe it. I squirmed and I railed against it. The Travellers stuff is appalling, absolutely appalling.\" He also says that when he complained to TV3 executive Ben Frow, the latter was \"just amused at my indignation, which meant I couldn't get anywhere with it\".<ref>[https://archive.today/20130816115137/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/browne-upset-by-tv3-shows-on-travellers-29482694.html Browne upset by TV3 shows on Travellers] Irish Independent, 2013-08-08.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130916173741/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/henry-mckean-attacks-vincent-brownes-mouthing-off-29499608.html Henry McKean attacks Vincent Browne's \"mouthing off\"] Irish Independent, 2013-08-15.</ref>\n*22 August \u2013 TV3 announces plans to commission its first soap opera, and invites companies from Ireland and the UK to put forward ideas. Submissions will be invited from September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286370&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 Seeks Soap Opera and Invites Irish & UK Production Companies to Pitch Ideas |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*25 August \u2013 Research by [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] shows most viewers are still watching television on traditional sets; only 4.6% view content online.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/bai-research-claims-only-46-watch-tv-on-a-laptop-604927.html |title=BAI research claims only 4.6% watch TV on a laptop |publisher=BreakingNews.ie |date=25 August 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n*26 August \u2013 The latest figures from [[UTV Media]] show its half yearly profits fell by 10%, with its radio advertising revenue in both Britain and Ireland continuing to decline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/business/2013/0827/470485-utv-media-results/ |title=Irish radio ad market still difficult|work= RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=26 August 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n*27 August \u2013 The [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il]] publishes plans to replace the [[Television licensing in the Republic of Ireland|television licence]] with a Public Service Broadcasting Charge on all primary residences, and certain businesses.<ref name=\"psbcConsultation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/Broadcasting/Consultation+on+Public+Service+Broadcasting+Charge/|title=Consultation on Public Service Broadcasting Charge|date=27 August 2013|publisher=Department of Communications, Energy and Natural Resources|accessdate=27 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827101726/http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/Broadcasting/Consultation+on+Public+Service+Broadcasting+Charge/|archive-date=27 August 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Holiday and second-home owners are likely to be exempted from the charge, with the onus to pay it on the occupier.<ref>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Cullen |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/second-home-owners-to-escape-broadcasting-charge-1.1506605 |title=Second home owners to escape broadcasting charge |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=27 August 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*11 September \u2013 [[Aertv]] launches the first [[Mobile app|app]] that enables viewers to receive free streamed content of all Irish broadcast material.<ref>Aertv has launched the first app to stream all Irish broadcast channels for free.</ref>\n*20 September \u2013 Fifteenth anniversary of the launch of TV3.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/archives/2013/0920/475391-happy-birthday-tv3-15-today/ |title=15 Today Happy Birthday TV3! - RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=20 September 2013 |accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n*18 October \u2013 RT\u00c9 Gaelic football pundit [[Joe Brolly]] says that it is \"nobody else's business\" if [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]] clubs or tournaments are named after dead republican paramilitaries, after some [[Ulster unionism|Unionist]] politicians criticised the practice as glorifying terrorism. The comments come in the wake of [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]] [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]]'s attendance at a [[Co-Operation Ireland]] dinner held the previous evening to acknowledge the efforts of the GAA in building better community relations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/joe-brolly-its-nobodys-business-if-gaa-clubs-are-named-after-dead-republican-paramilitaries-29671866.html |title=Joe Brolly: 'It's nobody's business if GAA clubs are named after dead republican paramilitaries' |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-24584058 |title=Joe Brolly hits out at GAA republican club name critics |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n*28 October \u2013 Singer [[Edele Lynch]] wins TV3's [[Celebrity Apprentice Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Butler |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/edele-lynch-is-crowned-winner-of-celebrity-apprentice-29707691.html |title=Edele Lynch is crowned winner of Celebrity Apprentice |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=29 October 2013 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n*6 November \u2013 [[UTV Media]] announces plans to launch [[UTV Ireland]], a television channel targeting audiences within the Republic of Ireland. If given the go-ahead by the [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]], the channel will be on air from 2015, and will show some ITV content currently broadcast by TV3.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burke-Kennedy |first1=Eoin |last2=Carbery |first2=Genevieve |url=http://www.irishtimes.