s |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=18 December 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n*28 December \u2013 Ratings for 25 December indicate that comedian [[Brendan O'Carroll]]'s show ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'' achieved the highest Christmas Day viewing figures in both Ireland and the UK. With a viewership of 832,000, it topped the Irish ratings for the third year in a row, while in the UK the episode, titled ''Buckin' Mammy'' achieved an audience of 9.4 million.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nicola |last=Anderson |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/a-first-for-mrs-brown-as-show-tops-irish-and-uk-festive-ratings-29870923.html |title=A first for Mrs Brown as show tops Irish and UK festive ratings |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=28 December 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n===TG4===\n*6 September \u2013 {{flagicon|USA}}/{{flagicon|UK}}/{{flagicon|IRE}} ''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]'' (2011\u20132019)\n\n==Ongoing television programmes==\n\n===1960s===\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: Nine O'Clock]]'' (1961\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: Six One]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n\n===1970s===\n* ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' (1975\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News on Two]]'' (1978\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Sunday Game]]'' (1979\u2013present)\n\n===1980s===\n* ''[[Fair City]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: One O'Clock]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n\n===1990s===\n* ''[[Would You Believe (TV series)|Would You Believe]]'' (1990s\u2013present)\n* ''[[Winning Streak]]'' (1990\u2013present)\n* ''Prime Time'' (1992\u2013present)\n* ''[[Nuacht RT\u00c9]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n* ''[[Nuacht TG4]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n* ''[[Ros na R\u00fan]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n* ''[[TV3 News]]'' (1998\u2013present)\n* ''[[Ireland AM]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n* ''[[Telly Bingo]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n\n===2000s===\n* ''[[Nationwide (Irish TV series)|Nationwide]]'' (2000\u2013present)\n* ''[[TV3 News at 5.30]]'' (2001\u2013present) \u2013 now known as the 5.30\n* ''[[Against the Head]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[news2day]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[Other Voices (TV series)|Other Voices]] (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2005\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Week in Politics]]'' (2006\u2013present)\n* ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'' (2007\u20132017)\n* ''[[Xpos\u00e9]]'' (2007\u2013present)\n* ''[[At Your Service (TV series)|At Your Service]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n* ''[[Championship Live]]'' (2008\u2013present) \u2013 Now rebranded as GAA on 3\n* ''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' (2008\u20132016)\n* ''[[Operation Transformation (TV series)|Operation Transformation]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n* ''[[3e News]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n* ''[[Dragons' Den (Ireland)|Dragons' Den]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n* ''[[Midweek (Irish TV series)|Midweek]]'' (2009\u20132014)\n* ''[[Republic of Telly]]'' (2009\u20132016)\n* ''[[Two Tube]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n\n===2010s===\n* ''[[Irish Pictorial Weekly]]'' (2012-present)\n* ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n* ''[[Love/Hate (TV series)|Love/Hate]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Saturday Night Show]]'' (2010\u20132015)\n* ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[The GAA Show]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[MasterChef Ireland]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[Paul Connolly Investigates]]'' (2011\u20132015)\n* ''[[Championship Matters]]'' (2012\u2013present)\n* ''[[Family Fortunes (TV3)|Family Fortunes]]'' (2012\u20132014)\n* ''[[Today (Irish TV series)|Today]]'' (2012\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Mario Rosenstock Show]]'' (2012\u20132016)\n* ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]'' (2012\u20132016)\n* ''[[The Works (2010s TV series)|The Works]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n\n==Ending this year==\n*4 January \u2013 ''[[OMG! Jedward's Dream Factory]]'' (2011\u20132013)\n*10 January \u2013 ''[[Dublin Wives]]'' (2012\u20132013)\n*28 January - ''[[One to One (TV series)|One to One]]'' (2006\u20132013)\n*29 January \u2013 ''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*8 February \u2013 ''[[The Holiday Show]]'' (2013) \n*10 February - ''[[Raw (TV series)|Raw]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*8 March \u2013 ''[[Take Me Out (Irish game show)|Take Me Out]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n*9 April \u2013 ''[[On the Couch (2013 TV series)|On the Couch]]'' (2013)\n*May \u2013 ''[[Premier Soccer Saturday]]'' (1998\u20132013)\n*13 June \u2013 ''[[Come Dine With Me (Ireland)|Come Dine with Me]]'' (2011\u20132013) and ''[[Celebrity Come Dine with Me (Ireland)|Celebrity Come Dine with Me]]'' (2012\u20132013)\n*August \u2013 ''[[The Big Money Game]]'' (2008\u20132013)\n*30 August - ''The Hit'' (2013)\n*27 September - ''[[The Morning Show with Sybil & Martin]]'' (2009\u20132013)\n*October - ''[[Monday Night Soccer]]'' (2008-2013)\n\n==Deaths==\n\n*27 January \u2013 [[\u00c9amon de Buitl\u00e9ar]], 83, writer, and film and documentary maker<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-21228088 |work=BBC News |title=Irish wildlife filmmaker Eamon de Buitlear dies |publisher=BBC |date=28 January 2013 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2013 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2013}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in Irish television|2013 in Irish television]]\n\n==2014==\n===January===\n*6 January \u2013 [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] announces the shortlist of production companies contending to make the broadcaster's first soap opera or continuing drama.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joyce |last=Fegan |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv3-could-poach-some-fair-city-stars-for-their-new-home-grown-soap-29891669.html |title=TV3 could poach some Fair City stars for their new home grown soap |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=6 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/featureinterviews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286728&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3\u2019s Production Company Drama Shortlist |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=6 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*7 January \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] (BAI) will not proceed with a licensing process for commercial digital terrestrial television, while a report commissioned by the regulator has suggested that without expansion, [[Saorview]] would become economically nonviable by the 2020s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0107/496388-bai-digital-tv/ |title=BAI will not launch commercial digital TV licence |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=7 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Slattery |first=Laura |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/sectors/media-and-marketing/saorview-future-questioned-as-regulator-abandons-commercial-dtt-1.1647571 |title=Saorview future questioned as regulator abandons commercial DTT |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*12 January \u2013 The ''[[Irish Independent]]'' reports that TV3 has sold ''[[Tallafornia]]'' to the UK's [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] for broadcast in that country.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=Webb |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/tv3-sells-hit-series-tallafornia-to-uks-channel-5-29907748.html |title=TV3 sells hit series 'Tallafornia' to UK's Channel 5 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=12 January 2014 |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n*12 January \u2013 ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reports that TV3 have \"voiced grave concerns\" to the Broadcasting Authority of Ireland about UTV's plans to establish a TV channel in the Republic of Ireland, amid concerns it would not be subject to the same obligations as RT\u00c9 and TV3.<ref>{{cite news|first=Samantha |last=McCaughren |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1361699.ece |title=TV3 will oppose UTV Irish licence |publisher=News International |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=12 January 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n*15 January \u2013 [[Ryanair]] launch their \"thank you for flying\" ad campaign on TV3, with plans to treble their advertising budget in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Slattery |first=Laura |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/sectors/media-and-marketing/ryanair-trebles-ad-budget-as-o-leary-embraces-tv-1.1656350 |title=Ryanair trebles ad budget as O\u2019Leary embraces TV |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tv3.ie/entertainment_article.php?locID=1.803.813&article=123667 |title=Ryanair signs up to major commercial partnership with TV3 Group |work=TV3 Xpos\u00e9 Entertainment |publisher=TV3 |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181558/http://www.tv3.ie/entertainment_article.php?locID=1.803.813&article=123667 |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*15 January \u2013 Dermot Horan is appointed Director of Production and Acquisitions at [[RT\u00c9]]. Michelle Spillane becomes Director of RT\u00c9 Global.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dierdre |last=Molumby |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/featureinterviews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286757&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=RT\u00c9 Staff Changes following Recent Departures |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>\n*19 January \u2013 Debut of [[RT\u00c9]]'s four part crime drama, ''[[Amber (TV series)|Amber]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harrison |first=Bernice |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/media/television-amber-alert-high-expectations-plus-low-tension-equals-mediocre-drama-1.1666891 |title=Television: \u2018Amber\u2019 alert: high expectations plus low tension equals mediocre drama |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> The series was filmed in 2011 and originally scheduled for broadcast in Autumn 2012, but postponed due to financial concerns.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Boland |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/television-amber-was-postponed-several-times-now-weve-an-idea-why-29947138.html |title=Television: Amber was postponed several times \u2013 now we've an idea why |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>\n*26 January \u2013 Following [[Sky (UK and Ireland)|Sky]]'s introduction of personalised adverts in the UK, the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' reports that the broadcaster hopes to bring the technology to Ireland by 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Roisin |last=Burke |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/sky-to-roll-out-tailored-ad-content-to-rich-viewers-29950136.html |title=Sky to roll out tailored ad content to rich viewers |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=26 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>\n*30 January \u2013 Figures from Television Audience Measurement Ireland indicate viewers in Ireland watched an average of 3.5 hours of television per day in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/irish-people-watch-over-three-hours-of-tv-a-day-1290778-Jan2014/ |title=How much TV do you watch? If you\u2019re a typical Irish viewer it\u2019s over 3 hours a day |publisher=The Journal |date=30 January 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n*30 January \u2013 The [[Scottish Football Association]] agrees a new four-year deal with [[Sky Sports]] to show its matches in the UK and Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/scottish-football-association-announces-new-3093134 |title=Scottish Football Association announces new four-season television deal with Sky |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Daily Record |date=30 January 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n*31 January \u2013 Figures from Sky show that over 3,000 viewers are accessing catch up services through [[Sky+HD]] on a weekly basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286809&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Sky Customers Get Connected in Ireland |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 BAI confirms its intention to enter into negotiations with UTV Ireland Limited for a television content provision contract.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newton |first=Aisling |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286832&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=BAI to enter into TV Content Contract with 'UTV Ireland' |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n*7 February \u2013 The Data Protection Commissioner launches an investigation after revelations that [[An Post]] has been making people disclose their bank account details if they wish to pay their [[television licensing in the Republic of Ireland|television license]] by [[direct debit]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=McCabe |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/an-post-faces-probe-after-seeking-bank-details-for-tv-licences-29987601.html |title=An Post faces probe after seeking bank details for TV licences |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n*14 February \u2013 Figures released by [[UPC Ireland]] show an 11% growth in broadband subscribers to 338,300 over the past 12 months, but a 4% fall in its overall TV subscribers to 427,000.<ref>{{cite news|first=Adrian |last=Weckler \u2013 Updated&nbsp;14 February 2014 02:09 PM |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/technology/upc-ireland-adds-broadband-subscribers-but-tv-users-fall-30009475.html |title=UPC Ireland adds broadband subscribers but TV users fall |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*22 February \u2013 RT\u00c9 airs the Rugby Union match between the Irish women\u2019s team and England from Twickenham.<ref>{{cite news|first=Johnny |last=Watterson |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/rugby/ireland-women-s-twickenham-match-set-for-live-television-broadcast-1.1690776 |title=Ireland women\u2019s Twickenham match set for live television broadcast |newspaper=The Irish Times |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*26 February \u2013 A third series of the BBC period crime drama ''[[Ripper Street]]'', axed by the broadcaster in 2013, will be produced in Ireland by [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] for its video on-demand service.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sorcha |last=Corcoran |url=http://www.businessandleadership.com/exporting/item/44899-third-series-of-tv-drama/ |title=Third series of TV drama 'Ripper Street' to be produced in Ireland |publisher=Businessandleadership.com |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286891&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Amazon Revives BBC Crime Drama \u2018Ripper Street\u2019 |publisher=The Irish Film and Television Network |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 [[UTV Ireland]] signs a ten-year contract with BAI to provide a general entertainment channel based in Dublin that will go on air from 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0227/507064-utv/ |title=UTV Ireland signs deal for TV service in Republic |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=27 February 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*3 March \u2013 A technical glitch during RT\u00c9's ''[[Primetime (Irish TV program)|Primetime]]'' current affairs show leads to a small portion of an interview with [[Maxim Peshkov]], Russia's ambassador to Ireland, playing on a loop for several minutes. The phrase \"Irish Ukrainians not Russians\" is heard for around fifteen minutes, with the clip quickly becoming popular on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26431150 |work=BBC News |title=RT\u00c9 'Irish Ukrainians not Russians' glitch a Twitter hit |publisher=BBC |date=4 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 TV3 names Ireland's Element Pictures and Britain's Company Pictures as its preferred partners in plans to launch a new soap.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4286906&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 Announces its Preferred Soap Partners |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=3 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n*4 March \u2013 [[John Yorke (producer)|John Yorke]], a former executive producer of ''[[EastEnders]]'', will oversee production of TV3's new soap, it is announced.<ref>{{cite news|first=Meg |last=Drewett |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a555305/former-eastenders-executive-producer-to-head-up-new-irish-soap-for-tv3.html#~p4sDngsGktcDw8 |title=Former EastEnders executive producer to head up new Irish soap for TV3 |publisher=Digital Spy |date=4 March 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 RT\u00c9 creates a video tribute to former Irish rugby captain [[Brian O'Driscoll]] imagining how he might be remembered in forty years from now, as an old man recalls the player's career to his awestruck grandson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/blog/sportblog/rte-create-stirring-brian-odriscoll-tribute-video-ahead-of-italian-clash-30075059.html |title=RTE create stirring Brian O'Driscoll tribute video ahead of Italian clash |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=8 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n*27 March \u2013 Sky announce details of a scholarship for students taking the Broadcast Production MA offered by [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]]'s National Film School. The Sky Academy TV Scholarship will be available from September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/training/TrainingNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287008&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=Sky Launches TV Scholarship with IADT |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 [[Saorview]] customers will be unable to receive [[RT\u00c9 One]] after today if they have not retuned their set-top boxes to receive technical upgrades for high-definition television.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fiona |last=Dillon |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/retune-your-tv-or-lose-rte-one-saorview-customers-are-warned-30140299.html |title=Re-tune your TV or lose RT\u00c9 One, Saorview customers are warned |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=31 March 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April \u2013 The [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]] announce a new three year broadcasting rights deal that will see RT\u00c9 air 31 games of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Championships]], with a further 14 games being shown via subscription on [[Sky Sports]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0401/606047-gaa-tv-rights/ |title=GAA announces TV rights allocation |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=1 April 2014 |accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> The decision will bring [[Gaelic football]] to a wider audience outside Ireland, but prompts concerns among fans and some players that the deal could lead to the game losing its amateur status.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ian |last=McCourt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/apr/15/gaelic-football-selling-games-soul-to-sky |title=Gaelic football and hurling's ruling body accused of selling its soul to Sky |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n*2 April \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 Two]] announces the launch of The RT\u00c9 Two New Voices Award, in conjunction with the National Student Media Awards, which will give students an opportunity to compete for a summer work placement at the station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0402/606135-rte-two-looking-for-new-presenting-talent/ |title=RT\u00c9 Two looking for new presenting talent |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=2 April 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n*15 April \u2013 TV3 secures the broadcasting rights for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/rugby-world-cup/2014/0415/608984-tv3-win-broadcasting-rights-for-rugby-world-cup/ |title=TV3 wins rights to broadcast 2015 Rugby World Cup |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Kirsty |last=Blake-Knox |first2=Joyce |last2=Fegan |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/tv3-outbids-rte-for-rugby-world-cup-2015-30189826.html |title=TV3 outbids RT\u00c9 for Rugby World Cup 2015 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=16 April 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*27 April \u2013 [[Brendan McCahey]] wins the [[The Voice of Ireland (series 3)|third series]] of ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0428/612160-brendan-mccahey-wins-voice-of-ireland/ |title=Brendan McCahey wins Voice of Ireland |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=28 April 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n*29 April \u2013 Mary Curtis is appointed as head of [[UTV Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287107&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=UTV Ireland Appoints Mary Curtis as Head of Channel |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=29 April 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*1 May \u2013 Launch of [[Irish TV]], a [[free-to-air]] international channel for the Irish diaspora, broadcasting in Ireland, Europe and the United States.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4287121&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=IrishTV Launches Tonight |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n*7 May \u2013 TV3 confirms its new soap will be set in a police precinct in a fictional harbour town, and  has the working title ''[[Red Rock (TV series)|Red Rock]]''. It will employ around 100 people, and is expected to begin airing in January 2015. The series is part of a schedule that will see the channel spending more on home made content than imports for the first time, with it airing up to 100 hours of homegrown content per week. TV3 also have the broadcast rights for the 2015 series of ''[[The X Factor (TV series)|The X Factor]]'', ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' and ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', as well as exclusive coverage of the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]]. The channel also announces plans to produce an Irish version of the UK television series ''[[Gogglebox]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4287140&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 announces its \"most ambitious schedule ever\" |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=7 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a569488/new-irish-soap-gets-working-title-red-rock.html#~p4sMyLr8H3IbYx |title=New Irish soap gets working title Red Rock |publisher=Digital Spy |date=8 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*12 May \u2013 TV3 executives Daragh Byrne, Joanne King, Paula McCarthy, David McMunn and Daragh O\u2019Halloran have been recruited by UTV Ireland, the new broadcaster has announced. They are among nine people recruited to senior positions at the upcoming channel.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sam |last=Griffin |first2=Kirsty |last2=Blake Knox |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/five-senior-tv3-executives-defect-to-new-broadcaster-utv-30267862.html |title=Five senior TV3 executives defect to new broadcaster UTV |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Joyce |last=Fegan |first2=Eimear |last2=Rabbitte |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/utv-raid-tv3-staff-as-rivalry-grows-30267555.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150216144509/http://www.herald.ie/news/utv-raid-tv3-staff-as-rivalry-grows-30267555.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 February 2015 |title=UTV raid TV3 staff as rivalry grows |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=13 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n*21 May \u2013 RT\u00c9 Gaelic football pundit [[Joe Brolly]] apologises to [[Sky Sports]] presenter [[Rachel Wyse]] after posting a tweet in which he described Sky's planned GAA coverage, which is to feature Wyse as a presenter, as \"TV3 plus Baywatch babe\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/joe-brolly-issues-grovelling-apology-to-rachel-wyse-for-crass-baywatch-jibe-30293208.html |title=Joe Brolly issues grovelling apology to Rachel Wyse for crass 'Baywatch' jibe |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=21 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n*24 May \u2013 ''[[The Irish Independent]]'' reports the dramatic departure of two producers from TV3's ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'', an event occurring only days after the channel lost five of its senior executives.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sam |last=Griffin |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/shock-for-tv3-as-producers-quit-vincent-browne-programme-30300182.html |title=Shock for TV3 as producers quit Vincent Browne programme |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=24 May 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*4 June \u2013 RT\u00c9 One airs the documentary ''The Torture Files'' which explores the treatment of the \"Hooded Men\" of [[Derry]] following [[Operation Demetrius|their internment]] by the British Army in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derryjournal.com/what-s-on/arts-culture/rte-to-screen-hooded-men-documentary-1-6094724 |title=RTE to screen Hooded Men documentary |publisher=Derry Journal Newspapers |newspaper=Derry Journal |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*5 June \u2013 TV3 airs the first Pride of Ireland Awards, an annual event launched to honour ordinary people who have acted bravely or extraordinarily in challenging situations. The event is held at Dublin's [[Mansion House, Dublin|Mansion House]] and presented by [[Una Foden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/pr_sub.php?type=1&view_pr=539 |title=TV3 will air Ireland\u2019s very first Pride of Ireland Awards |publisher=TV3 |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Aisling |last=Newton |url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287215&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 to air Pride of Ireland Awards |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n*9 June \u2013 Broadcaster [[Vincent Browne]] reveals that he recently suffered a bout of pneumonia but continued to work during his illness. Details of his condition are disclosed following his absence from the evening's edition of his ''Tonight'' programme and reports that he had spent the previous weekend in hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/vincent-browne-was-struck-by-pneumonia-last-month-but-continued-to-work-30340922.html |title=Vincent Browne was struck by pneumonia last month but continued to work |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> ''Tonight with Vincent Browne'' is presented by [[Tom McGurk]] in Browne's absence.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joe |last=O'Shea |url=http://www.independent.ie/life/falling-ratings-but-tv3s-400k-anchor-isnt-about-to-step-down-30352214.html |title=Falling ratings ... but TV3's \u20ac400k anchor isn't about to step down |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=15 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*9 June \u2013 Comedian [[David McSavage]] accuses RT\u00c9 of \"dictatorial\" censorship after the broadcaster banned a comedy sketch featuring three nuns and a crucified Jesus that parodies a recent [[Diet Coke]] advert. The \"Wild Nuns\" sketch was due to form part of the fourth episode of the latest series of McSavage's comedy show ''Savage Eye'', but in an email to the comedian, RT\u00c9 said it would not air the piece because they felt it could \"very quickly generate the potential for justifiable offence from viewers of the Christian faith\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/republic-of-ireland/raunchy-nuns-diet-coke-jesus-parody-banned-by-rte-30343039.html |title=Raunchy nuns Diet Coke Jesus parody banned by RTE |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*16 June \u2013 [[Minister for Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]] [[Pat Rabbitte]] announces a review of television coverage of the designated sporting and other events to determine what content should be [[free-to-air]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Anne-Marie |last=Walsh |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rabbitte-to-begin-review-of-freetoair-sport-on-tv-30356759.html |title=Rabbitte to begin review of free-to-air sport on TV |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=16 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*17 June \u2013 The ''Irish Independent'' reports that ''[[Republic of Telly]]'' presenter [[Jennifer Maguire]] will front a programme as part of RT\u00c9 Two's ''Reality Bites'' strand in which she will help young unemployed people find work. ''[[The Unemployables]]'' will air in the autumn and see her teaming up with [[Darren Kennedy]] with whom she co-devised the series format.<ref>{{cite news|first=Melanie |last=Finn |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/jennifer-maguire-and-darren-kennedy-teaming-up-for-reality-bites-the-unemployables-30360865.html |title=Jennifer Maguire and Darren Kennedy teaming up for 'Reality Bites: The Unemployables' |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>\n*19 June \u2013 [[UTV Ireland]] unveils its new logo at a press conference in Dublin's [[Croke Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/utv-ireland-reveals-new-green-and-yellow-logo-30368470.html |title=UTV Ireland reveals new green and yellow logo |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=19 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*3 July \u2013 Tracy Coyne wins [[The Great Irish Bake Off (series 2)|series two]] of TV3's ''[[The Great Irish Bake Off]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/life/food-drink/food-news/killarneys-tracey-coyne-crowned-the-winner-of-the-great-irish-bake-off-30404884.html |title=Killarney\u2019s Tracey Coyne crowned the winner of The Great Irish Bake Off |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=3 July 2014 |accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n*8 July \u2013 [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|The Cabinet]] approves plans to crack down on television licence evaders by giving inspectors the power to cross reference cable and satellite subscription bills with television licence records. However, [[UPC Ireland]] says that as the law currently stands it will not hand over details of its customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/breaking-news/irish-news/plans-to-target-tv-licence-evaders-30415386.html |title=Plans to target TV licence evaders |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*11 July \u2013 [[Alex White (politician)|Alex White]] is appointed as Communications Minister in a cabinet reshuffle, replacing Pat Rabbitte.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/watch-reshuffle-live-1565312-Jul2014/ |title=Confirmed: Leo Varadkar is the new Health Minister, Pat Rabbitte dropped from Cabinet |publisher=Distilled Media |work=Thejournal.ie |date=11 July 2014 |accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n*13 July \u2013 Veteran RT\u00c9 Sportscaster [[Bill O'Herlihy]] presents his final sports broadcast for the network after 50 years, with coverage of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Anita |last=McSorley |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/rte-sports-anchor-bill-oherlihy-will-consider-work-offers-from-rival-stations-30426744.html |title=RTE sports anchor Bill O'Herlihy will consider work offers from rival stations |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*13 July \u2013 ''The Sunday Independent'' reports that viewing figures for [[RT\u00c9 Two]] have reached an all-time low. Having fallen by a fifth last year, the monthly viewing average in 2013 was 40,600, or a 7.2% audience share.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=Stack |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/rte-two-viewer-numbers-slump-to-record-lows-30425218.html |title=RTE Two viewer numbers slump to record lows |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=13 July 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*16 July \u2013 TV3 announces the establishment of a Public Affairs Documentary Unit, and that its Wednesday night current affairs programme ''[[Midweek (Irish TV series)|Midweek]]'' is being axed to make way for programmes produced by the new department. A current affairs series similar to RT\u00c9's ''[[Primetime (Irish TV program)|Primetime]]'' is also planned for 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Demelza |last=De Burca |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/TV3+ringing+the+changes+as+Midweek+gets+the+axe.-a0375207225 |title=TV3 ringing the changes as Midweek gets the axe |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Irish Mirror |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*17 July \u2013 [[TG4]] begins broadcasting its content in the United States via the Today's Ireland channel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0717/631400-tg4-launches-nationwide-broadcasting-in-the-usa/ |title=TG4 launches nationwide broadcasting in the USA |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n*23 July \u2013 TG4 announce the appointment of three new weather presenters\u2014Irial \u00d3 Ceallaigh, Fiona N\u00ed Fhlaithearta and Caitl\u00edn Nic Aoidh\u2014who were selected following a public competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2014/0723/632577-tg4-introduces-three-new-weather-presenters/ |title=TG4 introduces three new weather presenters |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n*31 July \u2013 ''[[The Herald (Ireland)|The Evening Herald]]'' reports that RT\u00c9 has commissioned a documentary about pornography to be aired as part of its autumn schedule.<ref>{{cite news|last=Finn |first=Melanie |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/porno-documentary-for-rte-schedule-30474369.html |title=Porno documentary for RT\u00c9 schedule |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=31 July 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> The two-part documentary, ''We Need to Talk About Porn'', airs on RT\u00c9 One in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2015/0105/669341-rte-tens-tv-picks-for-today-monday-january-5/ |title=RT\u00c9 TEN'S TV picks for today Monday January 5 |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n*3 August \u2013 ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|The Sunday Independent]]'' reports that advertising agencies are frustrated by the lack of information about UTV Ireland, which is producing a lack of enthusiasm about advertising on the new channel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/ad-agencies-unimpressed-by-utvs-lack-of-plans-30478114.html |title=Ad agencies unimpressed by UTV's lack of plans |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=3 August 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*5 August \u2013 TV3 announce that casting will shortly begin for its new soap, ''Red Rock''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jack |last=Klompus |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a588666/casting-to-begin-for-new-irish-soap-red-rock.html#~p4sCU95qMUUzpP |title=Casting to begin for new Irish soap Red Rock |publisher=Digital Spy |date=5 August 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n*6 August \u2013 [[Setanta Sports]] launches its [[2014\u201315 Premier League]] coverage with an offer to new subscribers to sign up for just \u20ac1 a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/premier-league/setanta-sports-launches-1-offer-ahead-of-premier-league-season-30488138.html |title=Setanta Sports launches \u20ac1 offer ahead of Premier League season |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Independent |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n*6 August \u2013 The ''Irish Independent'' reports that the introduction of the [[Public Service Broadcasting Charge]], scheduled to begin on 1 January 2015, will be delayed to avoid clashes with new water charges due to be introduced in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel |last=McConnell |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/new-tv-fee-delayed-to-avoid-water-bill-clash-30486141.html |title=New TV fee delayed to avoid water bill clash |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*15 August \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] rules that TV3 \"did not show due care\" to the mother of a man responsible for a 2009 murder-suicide in [[Bray, County Wicklow]], about which it made a documentary. ''A Search for Justice: Death in Bray'' was aired by the channel on 10 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/complaints-about-tv3-documentary-death-in-bray-seb-creane-1620839-Aug2014/ |title=Watchdog says TV3 did not show \u2018due care\u2019 over murder-suicide documentary |publisher=Distilled Media |work=Thejournal.ie |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n*17 August \u2013 UTV Ireland announces that it has signed [[Alison Comyn]] to anchor its news bulletins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.u.tv/Entertainment/UTV-Ireland-reveals-new-anchor/cbb6bfff-8261-41bf-9e1a-a3fd8d524310 |title=UTV Ireland reveals new anchor |publisher=UTV |work=UTV Ireland |date=17 August 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402111419/http://www.u.tv/Entertainment/UTV-Ireland-reveals-new-anchor/cbb6bfff-8261-41bf-9e1a-a3fd8d524310 |archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*19 August \u2013 UTV Ireland has signed [[Pat Kenny]] to present a weekly show on the channel, it is announced.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Meagher |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/does-utv-ireland-have-the-x-factor-in-the-republic-30526994.html |title=Does UTV Ireland  have the X factor in the Republic? |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=24 August 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*20 August \u2013 TV3 has retained the broadcast rights for ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Melanie |last=Finn |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/tv3-fights-back-against-utv-with-exclusive-rights-to-x-factor-30522875.html |title=TV3 fights back against UTV with exclusive rights to X Factor |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=20 August 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*20 August \u2013 Veteran broadcaster [[Gay Byrne]] expresses his concern that the 2015 arrival of [[UTV Ireland]] has the potential to threaten the future of TV3.<ref>{{cite news|first=Demelza |last=De-Burca |url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/whats-on/arts-culture-news/gay-byrne-utv-coming-ireland-4080393 |title=Gay Byrne: UTV coming to Ireland could signal the end for TV3 |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Irish Mirror |date=20 August 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*27 August \u2013 [[Adam Weafer]], [[Jane McGrath (actress)|Jane McGrath]] and [[Paul Roe]] are confirmed as the first three cast members of ''Red Rock''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Harry |last=Fletcher |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a592918/new-irish-soap-red-rock-announces-first-cast-members.html#~p4sGFtbtlQlc02 |title=New Irish soap Red Rock announces first cast members |publisher=Digital Spy |date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*4 September \u2013 Speaking to ''[[The Evening Herald]]''{{'}}s Laura Butler, TV3 boss Jeff Ford outlines the channel's strategy for competing with UTV Ireland when it launches next year. This includes a greater emphasis on homegrown content, including ''[[Red Rock (TV series)|Red Rock]]'', a soap set in a [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda station]], and an Irish version of ''[[Blind Date (TV series)|Blind Date]]'', fronted by [[Lucy Kennedy]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Butler |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv3-boss-reveals-plans-to-safeguard-the-station-against-utv-arrival-30561974.html |title=TV3 boss reveals plans to safeguard the station against UTV arrival |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=4 September 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*8 September \u2013 TV3's entertainment series, ''[[Xpos\u00e9]]'', unveils a new studio set as it begins airing live. Previously pre-recorded, the show has been extended to an hour in length with an interactive element, and will follow a similar format to the US entertainment series, ''[[E! News]]''. The programme is co-presented by [[Peter O'Riordan]] and [[Karen Koster]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Butler |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/new-e-news-style-for-hourlong-xpos-as-new-set-revealed-and-peter-joins-team-30570226.html |title=New 'E! News' style for hour-long 'Xpos\u00e9' as new set revealed and Peter joins team |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n*11 September \u2013 RT\u00c9 Two reveals its new schedule, and confirms a rebranding back to its original name of 'RT\u00c9 2'.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=McCabe |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/total-revamp-for-rte2-as-it-launches-new-tv-offensive-30566079.html |title=Total revamp for RT\u00c92 as it launches new TV offensive |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=7 September 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n*16 September \u2013 The Broadcasting Authority of Ireland awards \u20ac800,000 of funding to TV3's new soap, ''Red Rock'', as part of its Sound and Vision scheme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://businessetc.thejournal.ie/bai-sound-and-vision-1674552-Sep2014/ |title=TV3\u2032s new soap Red Rock has been awarded \u20ac800,000 in BAI funding |publisher=Distilled Media |work=Thejournal.ie |date=16 September 2014 |accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref>\n*18 September \u2013 Former Ireland international rugby union player [[Keith Wood]] has been signed up by TV3 to join its coverage of the 2015 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/rugby/keith-wood-confirmed-as-a-pundit-for-tv3s-rugby-world-cup-coverage-30597637.html |title=Keith Wood confirmed as a pundit for TV3's Rugby World Cup coverage |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=18 September 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*19 September \u2013 Controversial media personality [[Katie Hopkins]] appears as a guest on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' in which she criticises fat people, and clashes with ''Irish Independent'' journalist Andrea Smith who recently wrote about being unconcerned with her large size.<ref>{{cite news|first=Brian |last=Byrne |url=http://www.independent.ie/life/you-cant-be-fat-and-happy-katie-hopkins-30601711.html |title='You can\u2019t be fat and happy\u2019 - Katie Hopkins |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=19 September 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n*22 September \u2013 RT\u00c92's rebranding takes effect. New programming includes a revamped news programme, ''News Feed'', presented by [[Carla O'Brien]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287515&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=RT\u00c9 2 Announced Season Highlights |publisher=Irish Film and Television Network |date=11 September 2014 |accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n*24 September \u2013 Vincent Browne apologises to viewers after making a joke about beheadings during a discussion with guests on his ''Tonight'' show.<ref>{{cite news|first=Geraldine |last=Gittens |first2=Denise |last2=Calman |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/tv3s-vincent-browne-apologises-over-controversial-beheading-comments-30616213.html |title=TV3's Vincent Browne apologises over controversial 'beheading' comments |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=25 September 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n*6 October \u2013 [[Una Foden]] and [[Rachel Stevens]] are confirmed as coaches on ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]'', replacing [[Jamelia]] and [[Dolores O'Riordan]] when the series returns in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/una-foden-and-rachel-stevens-announced-as-new-judges-on-the-voice-of-ireland-30642535.html|title=Una Foden and Rachel Stevens announced as new judges on 'The Voice of Ireland'|newspaper=The Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News and Media|date=6 October 2014|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n*10 October \u2013 TV3 confirms that its news presenter [[Claire Brock]] will move to UTV Ireland after she was signed up by the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/tv3-star-claire-brock-to-move-to-utv-30653661.html |title=TV3 star Claire Brock to move to UTV |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*13 October \u2013 TV3 announce a rival to RT\u00c9 One's ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' which will broadcast live from the RDS on 21 November.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fegan |first=Joyce |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/tv3-plans-toy-show-rival-live-from-rds-30658322.html |title=TV3 plans Toy Show rival live from RDS |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*14 October \u2013 RT\u00c9 News announce plans to appoint a new London correspondent, reversing their much-criticised decision of September 2012 to close their London offices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/rte-london-office-criticised-correspondent-axing-1725292-Oct2014/ |title=RTE to reverse much-criticised London correspondent axing |publisher=Distilled Media |work=Thejournal.ie |date=15 October 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*17 October \u2013 UTV Ireland has appointed RT\u00c9 broadcaster [[Paul Colgan]] as its Economics Editor.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/utv-ireland-poaches-another-rte-broadcaster-for-news-team-30671751.html |title=UTV Ireland poaches another RT\u00c9 broadcaster for news team |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=17 October 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*21 October \u2013 UTV Ireland confirms that ''[[Newstalk]]'' breakfast show presenter [[Chris Donoghue]] has been signed up to anchor news bulletins for the channel alongside [[Alison Comyn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/newstalks-chris-donoghue-to-join-utv-ireland-as-news-anchor-30681795.html |title=Newstalk's Chris Donoghue to join UTV Ireland as news anchor |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=21 October 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*23 October \u2013 Former RT\u00c9 radio and television presenter [[Jenny Huston]], who left broadcasting and retrained as a gemologist and jewellery designer, is launching her debut line Edge Only, the ''Irish Independent'' reports.<ref>{{cite news|first=Caitlin |last=McBride |url=http://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/fashion-news/former-rte-star-jenny-huston-launches-debut-jewellery-line-30687412.html |title=Former RT\u00c9 star Jenny Huston launches debut jewellery line |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=23 October 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*23 October \u2013 The Irish language drama ''[[The Gift (2014 film)|An Bronntanas]]'' debuts on TG4.<ref>{{cite news|first=Pat |last=Stacey |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-reviews/an-bronntanas-tg4s-cracking-new-thriller-as-gaeilge-30686695.html |title=An Bronntanas - TG4's cracking new thriller as gaeilge |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=23 October 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n*30 October \u2013 ''[[The Guarantee]]'', a film exploring the [[Post-2008 Irish banking crisis|Irish banking crisis]], debuts in Irish cinemas. It is produced by [[John Kelleher Media]] in association with the BAI, the [[Irish Film Board]] and TV3.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/movie-news/the-guarantee-first-trailer-for-film-about-the-infamous-night-of-the-bank-guarantee-released-30663109.html |title='The Guarantee' \u2013 first trailer for film about the infamous night of the bank guarantee released |publisher=Independent News and Media |date=14 October 2014 |accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n*3 November \u2013 Production begins on TV3's new soap, ''Red Rock''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=Luoma |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a607647/production-gets-underway-on-tv3s-irish-soap-opera-red-rock.html#~p4sylbKGrcwoup |title=Production gets underway on TV3's Irish soap opera Red Rock |publisher=Digital Spy |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The full cast is also unveiled, with [[Richard Flood]] taking the lead role as Garda Supt James McKay.<ref>{{cite news|last=McCahill |first=Elaine |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/richard-flood-is-lead-man-in-tv3s-garda-soap-red-rock-30712257.html |title=Richard Flood is lead man in TV3's garda soap Red Rock |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=3 November 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*5 November \u2013 RT\u00c9 announce the axing of their morning news programme, ''[[Morning Edition (RT\u00c9)|Morning Edition]]'', which the broadcaster says will not return to the schedules in the New Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/shock-as-rte-axes-current-affairs-programme-morning-edition-30721069.html |title=Shock as RT\u00c9 axes current affairs programme Morning Edition |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*13 November \u2013 RT\u00c92 airs the pilot episode of ''[[The Unemployables]]'', a programme in which [[Darren Kennedy]] and [[Jennifer Maguire]] help young unemployed people find work. It is scheduled to return for a full series in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Des |last=O'Driscoll |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/filmandtv/tv-watch-what-to-watch-this-week-296698.html |title=What to watch this week |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |newspaper=Irish Examiner |date=8 November 2014 |accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>\n*20 November \u2013 Two years after closing its London offices, RT\u00c9 News appoints Fiona Mitchell as its new London correspondent. She will take up the position from January 2015 and be based at [[ITN]]'s London offices.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=Stack |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rte-appoints-new-london-correspondent-30760311.html |title=RTE appoints new London correspondent |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*23 November \u2013 ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|The Sunday Independent]]'' reports that RT\u00c9 are planning to launch an online service that would allow its own content, along with that from TV3, [[TG4]] and UTV, to be accessed by internet users on a [[free-to-air]] basis. The service would be similar to that provided by Freeview Connect in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah |last=McCabe |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/media/rte-plans-for-online-viewing-to-take-on-upc-and-sky-30764576.html |title=RTE plans for online viewing to take on UPC and Sky |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Sunday Independent |date=23 November 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n*26 November \u2013 As a result of the buyback of its former debts from [[Anglo Irish Bank]], TV3 reports a net profit of \u20ac7.4m.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ailish |last=O'Hora |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/exceptional-gain-gives-tv3-net-profit-boost-advertising-improving-30778560.html |title=Exceptional gain gives TV3 net profit boost, advertising improving |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n*28 November \u2013 UTV Ireland finally confirms that Claire Brock will be joining its news team. The appointment of two other female journalists is also announced. Former Newstalk head of news and sport [[Sin\u00e9ad O\u2019Donnell]] will join the new channel along with [[Sarah O'Connor]], a reporter with [[North West Radio]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.ie/2014/11/utv-ireland-announce-appointment-of-news-reporters/ |title=UTV Ireland announce appointment of News reporters |publisher=Radio Today Ireland |date=28 November 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n*29 November \u2013 TV3 Group launches its #NewDawn campaign which is part of its rebrand and new schedule for 2015. The campaign kicks off with a 90-second and 60 second TV3 Promo airing at 19:45 on TV3.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/entertainment_article.php?locID=1.803.813&article=152347 |title=TV3 welcomes New Dawn for 2015! |work=TV3 Xpos\u00e9 Entertainment |publisher=TV3 |date=29 November 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123155855/http://www.tv3.ie/entertainment_article.php?locID=1.803.813&article=152347 |archivedate=23 January 2015 }}</ref> An advert promoting their newly produced drama series ''[[Red Rock (TV series)|Red Rock]]'' is also revealed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tv3.ie/e