TV Ireland show |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=8 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*11 October \u2013 TV3's coverage of the 2015 Rugby World Cup continues to break ratings records, with Ireland's match against [[France national rugby union team|France]] seen by an average 1.15 million viewers, peaking at 1.42 million. Figures suggest a total of 1.69 million tuned in to the game's coverage on TV3, which includes the game itself, as well as pre and post match analysis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/ireland-france-tv3-rugby-2383715-Oct2015/ |title=Ireland\u2019s victory over France pulled in record-breaking numbers for TV3 |publisher=Thejournal.ie |date=12 October 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n*19 October \u2013 RT\u00c9 announces that it will revamp its daily ''[[The Angelus (television programme)|Angelus]]'' slot, introducing a new set of short films featuring ordinary Irish people pausing to reflect during the Angelus. There will also be a ''People's Angelus'' on Fridays where viewers will be invited to submit their own footage. RT\u00c9 says the new look Angelus will give people \"of all faiths and none some quiet space in a hectic day-to-day world\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Ciara |last=Flaherty |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/examviral/real-life/the-angelus-has-been-revamped-and-people-arent-sure-what-to-make-of-it-360363.html |title=The Angelus has been revamped and people aren't sure what to make of it |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |newspaper=The Irish Examiner |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n*19 October \u2013 ITV agrees a \u00a3100m deal with [[UTV Media plc]] to buy its television assets. UTV Media plans to rebrand its remaining assets, but ITV says it has no plans to rebrand [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] as ITV Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Campbell |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34508529 |title=UTV Media agrees sale of TV stations to ITV for \u00a3100m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n*22 October \u2013 Three weeks after being employed on a six-month maternity cover contract, broadcaster Alan Cantwell announces his intention to leave the position of late news editor at UTV Ireland to return to TV3, describing the latter as his \"alma mater\" which will provide him with more \"security and certainty\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Kirsty |last=Blake Knox |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/cantwell-quits-sixmonth-utv-ireland-deal-for-the-security-of-tv3-34133918.html |title=Cantwell quits six-month UTV Ireland deal for the 'security' of TV3 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=23 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*22 October \u2013 ''[[BBC Newsline]]''{{'}}s coverage of the death of the former [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]], [[Ian Paisley]] is named Best News Programme at the [[Irish Film and Television Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34596868 |title=BBC Newsline named 'Best News Programme' at Irish Film and Television Awards |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*26 October \u2013 Following reports that the UTV Ireland flagship news bulletin, ''[[Ireland Live at 10]]'', has an average audience of around 50,000, the ''[[Belfast Telegraph]]'' reports that the programme's anchor, [[Alison Comyn]], has defended the broadcaster, telling the [[Irish Film and Television Awards]], \"viewing figures aren't what makes us\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Horan |first=Niamh |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/business/news/utv-ireland-anchor-alison-puts-brave-face-on-poor-viewing-figures-34140103.html |title=UTV Ireland anchor Alison puts brave face on poor viewing figures |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=26 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*26 October \u2013 ''Daniel and Majella's B&B Road Trip'' debuts on UTV Ireland, giving the channel their best viewing figures to date. The first episode of the programme is watched by an average of 322,000 on UTV Ireland, while it is seen by a further 192,000 on UTV.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/daniel-and-majella-odonnells-new-show-boosts-utv-ratings-attracting-more-viewers-than-eastenders-34149162.html |title=Daniel and Majella O'Donnell's new show boosts UTV ratings, attracting more viewers than EastEnders |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Kirsty |last=Blake Knox |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-reviews/daniels-bb-tour-presents-utv-ireland-with-a-first-hit-34147959.html |title=Daniel's B&B tour presents UTV Ireland with a first hit |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> The series moves to RT\u00c9 in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2016/0512/788000-daniel-and-majellas-bb-road-trip-comes-to-rte-one/ |title=Daniel and Majella's B&B Road Trip travels to RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=12 May 2016 |accessdate=12 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513112040/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2016/0512/788000-daniel-and-majellas-bb-road-trip-comes-to-rte-one/ |archivedate=13 May 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n*28 October \u2013 The [[Broadcasting Authority of Ireland]] (BAI) have rejected a complaint from a female viewer about an item on TV3's ''Ireland AM'' from February 2015 that featured a fake penis. The item, concerning contraception, included a demonstration of how to properly put on a condom, winning the show praise from viewers, and a single complaint that appropriate warnings had not been given before the segment. BAI found that at least three warnings were given before the piece was shown, making viewers fully aware of the nature of the content.<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/broadcasting-body-dismisses-complaint-about-fake-penis-used-on-tv3s-ireland-am-34149019.html |title=Broadcasting body dismisses complaint about fake penis used on TV3's Ireland AM |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n*2 November \u2013 ''Daniel and Majella's B&B Road Trip'', which is simulcast across Ireland on UTV Ireland and UTV respectively, draws an audience of almost half a million. In Northern Ireland, the programme achieves higher ratings than ''[[EastEnders]]'', aired in the same timeslot on [[BBC One Northern Ireland]]. ''Daniel and Majella's B&B Road Trip'' attracts a peak audience of 197,000, while ''EastEnders'' picks up 191,000, and average viewership for the entire programmes also shoes ''Road Trip'' to be ahead in the ratings.<ref>{{cite news|first=Brendan |last=Hughes |url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/2015/11/04/news/daniel-and-majella-s-road-trip-beats-eastenders-in-ratings-313870/ |title=Daniel and Majella's road trip beats EastEnders in ratings |publisher=The Irish News |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n*3 November \u2013 As part of the ''[[RT\u00c9 News: Six One|RT\u00c9 Six One News]]'' presenter [[Sharon N\u00ed Bheol\u00e1in]] interviews [[Web Summit]] co-founder Daire Hickey, but N\u00ed Bheol\u00e1in's confrontational nature during the item attracts much criticism on social media.<ref>{{cite news|first=Clare |last=Cullen |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/technology/web-summit/rte-should-be-ashamed-twitter-reacts-to-sharon-n-bheolins-interview-with-web-summit-cofounder-daire-hickey-34169123.html |title='RTE should be ashamed' \u2013 Twitter reacts to Sharon N\u00ed Bheol\u00e1in's interview with Web Summit co-founder Daire Hickey |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*3 November \u2013 TV3 presenter [[Alan Hughes (presenter)|Alan Hughes]] propose to his long term partner, Karl Broderick on the day's edition of ''[[Ireland AM]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/xpose/article/weddings/183160/Alan-Hughes-pops-the-question-to-partner-Karl-on-Ireland-AM |title=Alan Hughes pops the question to partner Karl on \u2018Ireland AM\u2019 |work=TV3 Xpos\u00e9 |publisher=TV3 |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n*4 November \u2013 TV3 announces that Brian Ormond and former Rose of Tralee Maria Walsh will presenter the 2015 ''TV3 Toy Show''. The programme will be pre-recorded at the broadcaster's Sony HD studios, and air at 9.00pm on 20 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/brian-ormond-and-former-rose-of-tralee-maria-walsh-to-host-the-tv3-toy-show-34170269.html |title=Brian Ormond and former Rose of Tralee Maria Walsh to host The TV3 Toy Show |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> TV3 decided to replace the 2014 presenters, [[Brian McFadden]] and [[Karen Koster]], because Koster has limited her television work after returning to TV3 on a part-time basis following maternity leave, but the broadcaster is forced to reject claims that McFadden was deliberately axed: \"We just wanted to go with someone new. He wasn't axed, we hadn't considered him for the role this year.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Crawford |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/tv3-denies-axing-brian-mcfadden-as-maria-walsh-gets-toy-show-role-34172490.html |title=TV3 denies axing Brian McFadden as Maria Walsh gets Toy Show role |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n*5 November \u2013 RT\u00c9 announces ''[[RT\u00c9 1916]]'', a series of programmes and events to mark the centenary of the [[Easter Uprising]], which will feature drama, documentaries and street events about the events of 1916.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4288726&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=RT\u00c9 unveil programme to commemorate 1916 Centenary |work=The Irish Film & Television Network |publisher= |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n*5 November \u2013 The inaugural [[Royal Television Society Northern Ireland Programme Awards]] are presented at The Mac in Belfast, with [[BBC Northern Ireland]] scooping five of the awards for ''Spotlight'', ''Road'', ''On The Air'', ''Brave New World \u2013 New Zealand'' and ''Line of Duty''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34742001 |title=BBC Northern Ireland claims five Royal Television Society NI awards |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n*6 November \u2013 UTV Media says that it expects to make \u00a313m of losses for 2015, and blames speculation over the sale of its television assets as the reason. UTV had previously forecast an \u00a311.5m loss for the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/business/2015/1106/739992-utv-media/ |title=Sale speculation has hurt UTV's Irish TV business |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=6 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=O'Donoghue |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/utv-ireland-losses-set-to-mount-to-more-than-18m-34175667.html |title=UTV Ireland losses set to mount to more than \u20ac18m |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=6 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n*9 November \u2013 The ''[[Evening Herald]]'' reports that UTV Ireland have signed [[Lorraine Keane]] to present an entertainment show designed to replace ''Pat Kenny's In the Round'', which was axed earlier in the year due to poor viewing figures.<ref>{{cite news|first=Melanie |last=Finn |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/lorraine-keane-set-to-replace-pat-kenny-in-utv-ireland-show-34180579.html |title=Lorraine Keane set to replace Pat Kenny in UTV Ireland show |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=9 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*11 November \u2013 TV3 announces that it has secured the broadcasting rights to the [[Six Nations Championship]] from 2018 to 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/xpose/article/tv-news/183998/TV3-wins-Six-Nations-Championship-rights-from-2018 |title=TV3 wins Six Nations Championship rights from 2018 |work=TV3 Xpos\u00e9 |publisher=TV3 |date=11 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/2015/1111/741148-tv3-secures-rights-to-six-nations-from-2018/ |title=TV3 secures rights to Six Nations from 2018 |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=11 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> The news comes as the channel's chief executive, [[David McRedmond]] defends the length of commercial breaks aired by TV3 during the Rugby World Cup while appearing as a guest on [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/rugby/tv3-chief-defends-lengthy-ad-breaks-in-lively-radio-exchange-as-rt-bemoans-six-nations-loss-34191048.html |title=TV3 chief defends lengthy ad breaks in lively radio exchange as RT\u00c9 bemoans Six Nations loss |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=11 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*19 November \u2013 TV3 staff hold a fundraiser at The Green Isle Hotel in Dublin to raise money for the ongoing medical care of student Clodagh Cogley, who was badly injured in the [[Berkeley balcony collapse]] earlier this year. Clodagh, the daughter of Niall Cogley, group director of broadcasting at TV3, suffered a spinal cord injury during the incident.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan |last=O'Keeffe |url=http://www.herald.ie/news/tv3-boss-thanks-wonderful-colleagues-for-berkeley-fundraiser-34217952.html |title=TV3 boss thanks 'wonderful' colleagues for Berkeley fundraiser |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Evening Herald |date=20 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*20 November \u2013 Irish television premier of ''[[Adele at the BBC|Adele Live in London]]'', which airs at 8.30pm on RT\u00c92. The show, which sees singer [[Adele]] speaking to [[Graham Norton]] about her new album, ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'' and other aspects of her career, is simulcast with [[BBC One]], where it has a different title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/blogs/television/2015/1111/741117-on-the-box-weekly-tv-preview/ |title=On the Box \u2013 Weekly TV Preview |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=11 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329102717/http://www.rte.ie/ten/blogs/television/2015/1111/741117-on-the-box-weekly-tv-preview/ |archivedate=29 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> \n*27 November \u2013 The website [[businesspost.ie]] reports that David McRedmond is to leave his job as chief executive of TV3 by the end of the year. McRedmand confirms his intention to step down from the role during a meeting with TV3 staff on 7 December.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sexton |first=Colette |url=http://www.businesspost.ie/speculation-grows-that-tv3-boss-mcredmond-set-to-leave/ |title=Speculation grows that TV3 boss McRedmond set to leave |newspaper=The Sunday Business Post |publisher= |date=27 November 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sexton |first=Colette |url=http://www.businesspost.ie/david-mcredmond-tells-staff-he-is-leaving-tv3/ |title=Chief executive David McRedmond to leave TV3 |newspaper=The Sunday Business Post |publisher= |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*1 December \u2013 Shareholders approve the \u00a3100&nbsp;million sale of UTV Media's television business to ITV.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/business/2015/1201/750473-utv/ |title=UTV shareholders approve sale of television assets |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=1 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*2 December \u2013 RT\u00c9's Christmas lineup will include two special episodes of ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'', as well as in-depth portraits of singer [[Ed Sheeran]], and [[Niall Horan]] of [[One Direction]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/ed-sheeran-special-and-double-bills-of-mrs-browns-boys-and-fair-city-make-rtes-christmas-schedule-30793195.html |title=Ed Sheeran special and double bills of Mrs Brown's Boys and Fair City make RTE's Christmas schedule |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=2 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> \n*3 December \u2013 TV3 unveils its Christmas schedule, with highlights including a Christmas special of ''The Great Irish Bake-Off'', the concluding episode of ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', and ''The Queen of Ireland's Christmas Message'' featuring [[Panti]] giving her take on the year's events, while ''Red Rock'' will feature a storyline about the death of a prominent character. Highlights for the 2016 winter season include the return of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' and ''[[Doctor in the House (TV series)|Doctor in the House]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Se\u00e1n |last=Brosnan |url=http://iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4288804&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=TV3 unveils Christmas schedule and what\u2019s in store for 2016 |work=The Irish Film and Television Network |publisher= |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*4 December \u2013 RT\u00c9 journalist [[Teresa Mannion]] makes a live broadcast reporting on the progress of [[Storm Desmond]], during which she is seen being buffeted by gale-force winds and heavy rain. The footage quickly becomes popular viewing among internet users.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/rtes-teresa-mannion-breaks-the-internet-following-dramatic-storm-desmond-weather-report-34262038.html |title=RTE's Teresa Mannion breaks the internet following dramatic Storm Desmond weather report |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=5 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*7 December \u2013 [[Virgin Media Ireland]] completes its acquisition of TV3.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/news_sub_page.php?article_id=186502&locID=1.2.883 |title=Virgin Media closes deal to acquire TV3 |work=TV3 News |publisher=TV3 |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/business/2015/1207/751915-virgin-completes-acquisition-of-tv3/ |title=Virgin completes acquisition of TV3 as CEO departs |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*10 December \u2013 Viewing figures for November indicate that UTV Ireland achieved its most successful month to date, capturing a 10.3% share of the audience between 6.30&nbsp;pm and 11.30&nbsp;pm, making it the second-most-watched channel in that timeslot during the month.<ref>{{cite news|first=Se\u00e1n |last=Brosnan |url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/BroadcastNews/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4288824&tpl=archnews&force=1 |title=November marks record month for UTV Ireland |work=The Irish Film and Television |publisher= |date=10 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*10 December \u2013 UTV Ireland confirms that it will not be working on any future projects with broadcaster Pat Kenny.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/exclusive-pat-kenny-and-utv-ireland-part-company-34276795.html |title=Pat Kenny and UTV Ireland 'part company' |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=10 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> \n*12 December \u2013 [[Tony Hanway]], CEO of Virgin Media Ireland, hints that TV3 may expand its coverage area to broadcast in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishnews.com/business/2015/12/12/news/irish-station-tv3-eyes-expansion-north-of-the-border-351505/ |title=Irish station TV3 eyes expansion north of the border |publisher= |newspaper=The Irish News |date=12 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*19 December \u2013 Boxer [[Michael Conlan (boxer)|Michael Conlan]] is named the 2015 [[RT\u00c9 Sports Person of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/other-sport/2015/1219/755196-sports-awards/ |title=Michael Conlan named RT\u00c9 Sport Person of the Year |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=20 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n*22 December \u2013 The Broadcasting Authority of Ireland approves ITV's \u00a3100&nbsp;million takeover of [[UTV plc]], meaning the deal has cleared one of the first regulatory hurdles in the Republic.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulgrew |first=John |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/business/news/utv-ireland-clears-first-hurdle-in-takeover-deal-34306440.html |title=UTV Ireland clears first hurdle in takeover deal |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=Belfast Telegraph |date=22 December 2015 |accessdate=18 March 2016 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*29 December \u2013 Broadcaster [[Gay Byrne]] is taken to hospital after suffering a heart attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-35198373 |title=Irish broadcaster Gay Byrne suffers heart attack |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=30 December 2015 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>\n*29 December \u2013 Viewing figures reveal that ''Mrs. Brown's Boys'' was once again the most watched programme over the festive period. ''Mammy\u2019s Christmas Punch'', aired on Christmas Eve, was seen by 668,400 viewers (a 42% audience share), while ''[[Mrs. Brown\u2019s Boys D\u2019Movie]]'' was the most watched programme on Christmas Day, attracting 591,300 viewers (a 38% share).<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenna |first=Paddy |url=http://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/irelands-most-watched-christmas-tv-shows-revealed-and-theres-a-famous-granny-on-top/525191 |title=Ireland's most-watched Christmas TV shows revealed and there's a famous granny on top |publisher=JOE.ie |date=29 December 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n\n==Deaths==\n*9 February \u2013 Daphne Carroll, 91, actress<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/news/obituaries-daphne-carroll-30993008.html |title=Obituaries: Daphne Carroll |publisher=Independent News and media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=15 February 2015 |accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n*13 May \u2013 [[Derek Davis]], 67, broadcaster<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/rte-broadcaster-derek-davis-dies-after-short-illness-31218934.html |title=RTE broadcaster Derek Davis dies after short illness |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-32723613 |title=Derek Davis: Former BBC and RT\u00c9 broadcaster dies aged 67 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n*25 May \u2013 [[Bill O'Herlihy]], 76, sports and current affairs broadcaster and public relations consultant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/broadcasting-legend-bill-oherlihy-dies-aged-76-31251375.html |title=Broadcasting legend Bill O'Herlihy dies aged 76 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=25 May 2015 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2015/0525/703580-bill-oherlihy/ |title=Broadcaster Bill O'Herlihy dies aged 76 |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=25 May 2015 |accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n*5 June \u2013 [[Paolo Tullio]], 65, Michelin Star-winning chef and resident food critic on ''[[The Restaurant (Irish TV series)|The Restaurant]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2015/0605/706238-paolo-tullio-death/ |title=Well-known chef and food critic Paolo Tullio has died |work=RT\u00c9 News |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=5 June 2015 |accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n*28 June \u2013 [[Liam \u00d3 Murch\u00fa]], 86, writer and broadcaster<ref>{{cite news|first=Aoife |last=Kelly |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/former-rte-broadcaster-liam-murch-has-died-aged-86-31338261.html |title=Former RTE broadcaster Liam \u00d3 Murch\u00fa has died aged 86 |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=29 June 2015 |accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n*9 July \u2013 Diarmuid Mac An Adhastair, 71, actor<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/ros-na-runs-diarmuid-mac-an-adhastair-dies-686033.html |title=Ros na Run's Diarmuid Mac An Adhastair dies |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |newspaper=The Irish Examiner |date=11 July 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n*31 December \u2013 [[Wesley Burrowes]], 85, playwright, screenwriter and creator of ''[[Glenroe]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/writer-of-glenroe-wesley-burrowes-passes-away-34327188.html |title=Writer of Glenroe Wesley Burrowes passes away |publisher=Independent News and Media |newspaper=The Irish Independent|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2015 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2015}}\n\n[[Category:2015 in Irish television|2015 in Irish television]]\n\n==2016==\n*17 January \u2013 The ''[[Sunday Business Post]]'' reports Virgin Media Ireland have plans to launch additional TV3 channels including a 24-hour rolling news channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesspost.ie/tv3-plans-24-hour-news-channel/|title=TV3 plans 24-hour news channel - BusinessPost.ie|first=Colette|last=Sexton|publisher=}}</ref> The TV3 Group later denies such reports.\n*20 January \u2013 RT\u00c9 announces that it has partnered with [[Freesat]], the UK free-to-air television company, to develop a new product for [[Saorview]], Ireland\u2019s free digital television service and the largest television platform in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Saorview {{!}} News {{!}} RT\u00c9 and Saorview partner with Freesat to deliver a next-generation product for Irish audiences|url = https://www.saorview.ie/en/news/article/rte-and-saorview-partner-with-freesat-to-deliver-a-next-generation-product|website = www.saorview.ie|access-date = 2016-01-25|last = Saorview}}</ref>\n*24 April \u2013 [[Michael Lawson]] wins the [[The Voice of Ireland (series 5)|fifth series]] of ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]''.\n*7 June \u2013 Children's strand [[3Kids]] launches on [[3e]].\n*3 July \u2013 [[Irish TV]] has received ministerial approval from Minister for Communications [[Denis Naughten]] to launch on the Irish Digital Terrestrial [[Saorview]] platform.<ref>[http://www.businesspost.ie/big-boost-for-mayo-based-irish-tv-station-as-saorview-deal-extends-its-reach/ Big boost for mayo based Irish TV station as Saorview deal extends its reach] by Michael Brennan and Colette Sexton, Business Post, 3 July 2016.</ref>\n*5 July \u2013 Following the purchase of Setanta Sports' Irish operations by [[Eir (telecommunications)|Eircom]], Setanta Sports Ireland is renamed [[Eir Sport 1]] and Setanta Sports 1 is renamed [[Eir Sport 2]].\n*11 July \u2013 ITV plc announces that it has sold UTV Ireland to [[TV3 Group]] for \u20ac10 million. As part of the deal, TV3 Group inherits UTV Ireland's ten-year program supply contract with ITV.<ref name=\"it-utvirelandvt\">{{cite web|title=TV3 owner Virgin Media buys UTV Ireland for \u20ac10m|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/media-and-marketing/tv3-owner-virgin-media-buys-utv-ireland-for-10m-1.2718283|website=Irish Times|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> \n*3 August \u2013 RT\u00c9 announces its intention to replace ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]'' with an [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|Irish version]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2016/0803/806722-rte-swaps-the-voice-for-dancing-with-the-stars/|title=RT\u00c9 drops The Voice for Dancing with the Stars|publisher=RT\u00c9|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n*18 November \u2013 [[Jennifer Zamparelli]] and [[Nicky Byrne]] are chosen to present RT\u00c9 One's forthcoming series ''[[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*22 November \u2013 It is announced that ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and ''[[Emmerdale]]'' will move from UTV Ireland back to TV3 beginning on 5 December.<ref name=\"thejournal-corriereturns\">{{cite web|title=The rovers return: TV3 is getting Emmerdale and Corrie back|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/tv3-reclaim-soaps-3095795-Nov2016/|website=The Journal|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n*1 December \u2013 TV3's ''[[The 7 O'Clock Show]]'' is moved forward an hour and renamed ''[[The 6 O'Clock Show]]'' in order to facilitate the return of ''Emmerdale'' and ''Coronation Street'' to the channel.\n*6 December \u2013 It is announced that TV3, along with [[3e (channel)|3e]] and its newly purchased channel [[UTV Ireland]], will receive new logos, idents and new schedules.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/tv3-be3-utv-ireland-3122597-Dec2016/|title=UTV Ireland is to be relaunched... as the \"female orientated\" Be3|first=Cianan|last=Brennan|publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n*21 December \u2013 [[Irish TV]] confirms it will cease broadcasting.\n\n==Debuts==\n\n===RT\u00c9===\n*3 January \u2013 ''[[Rebellion (miniseries)|Rebellion]]'' on RT\u00c9 One\n*1 February \u2013 ''[[Bridget & Eamon]]'' on RT\u00c9 Two\n*10 February \u2013 ''[[Easter Rising|1916: The Irish Rebellion]]''. (First part of a 3-part documentary) on RT\u00c9 One.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-reviews/1916-documentary-on-rte-one-review-a-big-lavishly-produced-slab-of-prestige-television-34443631.html|title=1916 documentary on RTE One review: 'A big, lavishly produced slab of prestige television'|date=11 February 2016|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n*21 April - ''[[First Dates (Irish TV series)|First Dates]] on RT\u00c9 Two\n*6 November \u2013 ''[[Know The Score]]'' on RT\u00c9 One\n\n===[[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]]===\n*20 September - ''The Tonight Show''\n\n==Ongoing television programmes==\n\n===1960s===\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: Nine O'Clock]]'' (1961\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: Six One]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' (1962\u2013present)\n\n===1970s===\n* ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' (1975\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News on Two]]'' (1978\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Sunday Game]]'' (1979\u2013present)\n\n===1980s===\n* ''[[Fair City]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n* ''[[RT\u00c9 News: One O'Clock]]'' (1989\u2013present)\n\n===1990s===\n* ''[[Would You Believe (TV series)|Would You Believe]]'' (1990s\u2013present)\n* ''[[Winning Streak]]'' (1990\u2013present)\n* ''Prime Time'' (1992\u2013present)\n* ''[[Nuacht RT\u00c9]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n* ''[[Nuacht TG4]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n* ''[[Ros na R\u00fan]]'' (1996\u2013present)\n* ''[[TV3 News]]'' (1998\u2013present)\n* ''[[Ireland AM]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n* ''[[Telly Bingo]]'' (1999\u2013present)\n\n===2000s===\n* ''[[Nationwide (Irish TV series)|Nationwide]]'' (2000\u2013present)\n* ''[[TV3 News at 5.30]]'' (2001\u2013present) \u2013 now known as the 5.30\n* ''[[Against the Head]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[news2day]]'' (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[Other Voices (TV series)|Other Voices]] (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2005\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Week in Politics]]'' (2006\u2013present)\n* ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'' (2007\u20132017)\n* ''[[Xpos\u00e9]]'' (2007\u20132019)\n* ''[[At Your Service (TV series)|At Your Service]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n* ''[[Championship Live]]'' (2008\u2013present) \u2013 Now rebranded as GAA on 3\n* ''[[Operation Transformation (TV series)|Operation Transformation]]'' (2008\u2013present)\n* ''[[3e News]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n* ''[[Dragons' Den (Ireland)|Dragons' Den]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n* ''[[Two Tube]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n\n===2010s===\n* ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n* ''[[Love/Hate (TV series)|Love/Hate]]'' (2010\u2013present)\n* ''[[Mrs. Brown's Boys]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[The GAA Show]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[MasterChef Ireland]]'' (2011\u2013present)\n* ''[[Irish Pictorial Weekly]]'' (2012\u2013present)\n* ''[[Today (Irish TV series)|Today]]'' (2012\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Works (2010s TV series)|The Works]]'' (2012\u2013present)\n* ''[[Deception (Irish TV series)|Deception]]'' (2013\u2013present)\n* ''[[MasterChef Ireland|Celebrity MasterChef Ireland]]'' (2013\u2013present)\n* ''[[Second Captains Live]]'' (2013\u2013present)\n* ''[[Claire Byrne Live]]'' (2015\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Restaurant (Irish TV series)|The Restaurant]]'' (2015\u2013present)\n* ''[[Red Rock (TV series)|Red Rock]]'' (2015\u2013present)\n* ''[[TV3 News at 8]]'' (2015\u2013present)\n* ''[[Ireland Live]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n\n==Ending this year==\n*24 April - ''[[The Voice of Ireland]]'' (2012\u20132016)\n*28 October \u2013 ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'' (2013\u20132016)\n*23 December \u2013 ''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' (2008\u20132016)\n*Unknown date - ''[[Republic of Telly]]'' (2009\u20132016) and ''[[The Mario Rosenstock Show]]'' (2012\u20132016)\n\n==Deaths==\n*31 January \u2013 [[Terry Wogan]], 77, Irish-British radio and television broadcaster.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-35453541|title=Sir Terry Wogan: Veteran broadcaster dies, aged 77|date=31 January 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\t\n\n==See also==\n*[[2016 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2016}}\n\n[[Category:2016 in Irish television|2016 in Irish television]]\n\n==2017==\n*8 January \u2013 ''[[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' makes its debut on [[RT\u00c9 One]].\n*9 January \u2013 TV3 Group reveals a new on-air presentation featuring the number 3 superimposed on various natural and urban landscapes across Ireland. A new logo is also revealed along with new promos and on-screen graphics. Similarly, new identities are introduced to 3e and its rebrand of [[UTV Ireland]] to [[be3]].\n*12 January \u2013 Viewing figures indicate that ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' was the most watched programme of 2016 in Ireland with a total of 1,571,600 viewers.<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/revealed-the-most-watched-tv-programmes-of-2016-35362777.html|title=Revealed: The most watched tv programmes of 2016|date=12 January 2017|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=13 January 2017}}</ref>\n*2 February \u2013 [[The Irish Post]] acquires Irish TV,<ref>http://irishpost.co.uk/irish-post-acquires-digital-and-intellectual-property-assets-of-diaspora-broadcaster-irish-tv/</ref> saving the channel from closure.\n*8 March \u2013 Irish TV goes off the air. Its Sky slot is subsequently bought by [[Viacom International Media Networks Europe]] to launch [[5Spike|Spike +1]].\n*26 March \u2013 [[Aidan O'Mahony]] and dance partner [[Valeria Milova]] win the [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish series 1)|first series]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*6 July \u2013 [[RT\u00c9 One]] extends its on-air hours, the channel now starting at 6:00am rather than the later 6:20 am.\n*27 July \u2013 [[Vincent Browne]] presents his last edition of ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]'', with Taoiseach [[Leo Varadkar]] as a guest.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/five-things-we-learned-from-leo-varadkars-final-appearance-on-tonight-with-vincent-browne-35972552.html|title= Five things we learned from Leo Varadkar\u2019s final appearance on 'Tonight with Vincent Browne'|date=27 July 2017|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n*8 October \u2013 An Irish version of ''[[Blind Date (UK game show)|Blind Date]]'', hosted by comedian [[Al Porter]], is debuted on [[Virgin Media One|TV3]].\n\n<!--- the \"==Deaths==\" section was TEMPLATED as 'Empty section|date=February 2019'  ... ! -->\n\n==See also==\n*[[2017 in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Years in TV by country|2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in Irish television|2017 in Irish television]]\n\n==2018==\n[[The Late Late Toy Show]] was the most watched programmes on Irish television in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.the42.ie/sports-tv-viewing-figures-2018-4433642-Jan2019/|title =Grand Slam decider the most-watched sporting event on Irish TV in 2018|date=10 January 2019|work=The 42|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\t\n \n*8 January \u2013 ''[[Micko]]'' airs on RT\u00c9 One.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.loosehorse.ie/portfolio-items/micko/|title=Micko}}</ref>\n*23 January \u2013 [[Saorview]] announces the launch of Free TV, a channel designed to promote the launch of its premium service Saorview Connect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saorview.ie/en/news/article/saorview-launches-the-worlds-first-free-shopping-channel-free-tv.-and-its-f|title=Saorview \u2013 News \u2013 Saorview launches the world\u2019s first free shopping channel \u2013 Free TV.  And it\u2019s free-ly good|website=www.saorview.ie|accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n*3 February \u2013 ''[[Ireland's Got Talent]]'' makes its debut on [[Virgin Media One|TV3]].\n*24 March \u2013 RDC win the [[Ireland's Got Talent (series 1)|first series]] of ''[[Ireland's Got Talent]]''.\n*26 March \u2013 [[Jake Carter (singer)|Jake Carter]] and dance partner [[Karen Byrne]] win the [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish series 2)|second series]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*7 May \u2013 RT\u00c9 announce plans for a timeshift channel for [[RT\u00c92]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Laura |last=Slattery |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/media-and-marketing/rt%C3%A9-plans-plus-one-channel-for-rt%C3%A92-1.3485996 |title=RT\u00c9 plans plus-one channel for RT\u00c92 |publisher=The Irish Times Trust |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=7 May 2018 |accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n*6 June \u2013 ''Ireland's Got Talent'' will make its UK television debut on [[5Star]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.c21media.net/5star-adds-tv3-talent/|title=5Star to show Ireland's Got Talent|last=Elms|first=John|date=6 June 2018|publisher=C21 Media|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n*30 August \u2013 TV3 is rebranded as Virgin Media One, while its sister channels [[3e (channel)|3e]] and [[be3]] become Virgin Media Two and Three respectively. A fourth pay TV sports channel, [[Virgin Media Sport]], launches on the Virgin Media platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/tv3-virgin-media-sports-channel-2-4096826-Jun2018/|title=TV3 is officially changing its name \u2013 to Virgin Media One|work=TheJournal.ie|access-date=29 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n*1 September \u2013 To coincide with the rebranding of TV3 to Virgin Media One, the ''Saturday AM'' and ''Sunday AM'' breakfast programmes are renamed as ''\"Weekend AM\"''.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/business/media-and-marketing/tv3-reels-in-the-years-as-it-becomes-virgin-media-one-1.3605593 TV3 reels in the years as it becomes Virgin Media One], ''Irish Times'', 23 August 2018</ref>\n*18 September \u2013 Launch of [[Virgin Media Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the42.ie/tv3-virgin-media-sports-channel-3-4096854-Jun2018/|title=Virgin Media to launch brand new Irish sports channel as part of TV3 rebrand|first=Fora|last=Staff|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://extra.ie/2018/07/02/entertainment/movies-tv/new-channel-virgin-media-sport-takes-on-rival-rte-with-exclusive-match-deals-for-2019|title=Virgin Media Sport Takes On Rival RTE With Exclusive Match Deals|date=2 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.ie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/media/tv3-aims-to-score-with-new-ad-model-on-sports-channel-37067273.html|title=TV3 aims to score with new ad model on sports channel \u2013 Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmedia.ie/bundles/broadband-tv-phone/|title=Broadband, TV & Phone Bundles in Ireland \u2013 Virgin Media Ireland|website=www.virginmedia.ie|accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n*28 September \u2013 ''[[Players of the Faithful]]'' airs on RT\u00c9 One.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.loosehorse.ie/portfolio-items/players-of-the-faithful/|title=Players of the Faithful}}</ref>\n*12 October \u2013 ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'' is broadcast live from [[Central Hall Westminster]] in London, the first time the programme has broadcast from the United Kingdom since 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/1012/1001927-tubridy-says-london-late-late-will-be-irish-on-tour/ |title=Tubridy excited and nervous ahead of London Late Late |publisher=RT\u00c9 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=12 October 2018 |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/1003/1000719-late-late-show-in-london/ |title= London Late Late Shows |publisher=RT\u00c9 |